const SEED_DATA = [{ "cat": "Arrays & Hashing", "num": 217, "name": "Contains Duplicate", "risk": "Low", "back": "Visit each element, insert into hashset, if already present we have a duplicate\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)", "order": 0 }, { "cat": "Arrays & Hashing", "num": 242, "name": "Valid Anagram", "risk": "Low", "back": "a) sort and compare b) iterate through strings s and t, increment hashtable h at h[s[i]], then dec at h[t[i]], every value should be 0\n\nComplexity: a) Time: O(n log n) sort + O (n) compare. Space: O(1) b) Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: check first if their lengths are the same", "order": 1 }, { "cat": "Arrays & Hashing", "num": 1, "name": "Two Sum", "risk": "Low", "back": "Use hashtable. Iterate over arr, look if target - arr[i] is in table, return indices if yes. Otherwise insert (arr[i], i) into table.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: We can do one pass because this is basically backward looking. We'll miss the pair when we visit the first component, but when we visit the second component the first one is in the table. This is why some return the pair with the table index first (its the first component). We avoid hitting the same component twice because we look-up before we insert.", "order": 2 }, { "cat": "Arrays & Hashing", "num": 49, "name": "Group Anagrams", "risk": "Low", "back": "Use hashtable of <string, array<string>>. Iterate over each string, take a copy and sort it. Insert src string into array, then just need to gather arrays\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * nlogn) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Can use \"counting sort\" to improve complexity, rather than normal sort, scan string counting the number of occurences of each letter. Than build a new string, pushing back each letter, in order, occ times. Improves time complexity to O(n * m), where m is the length of each string or the average length of the strings.", "order": 3 }, { "cat": "Arrays & Hashing", "num": 347, "name": "Top K Frequent Elements", "risk": "Low", "back": "Use hashtable to count frequency of elements in array. Then iterate through, pushing into a min sorting priority queue. If queue size > k, pop. At the end return the elements of the queue (exactly k).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n log(k)) Space: O(n) [n + n for dictionary and queue]\n\nNotes: Min sorted queue lets take advantage of k being smaller than n. Once we insert and we have more than k elements, the least frequent element will be at the top. On every insert, the restores the sorting order. Means we have to at worst do log k comparisons for every number, turning the O complexity from nlogn to nlogk\n\n— alt —\n\nUse hashtable to count frequency of elements in array. Then make an array of size n+1 of arrays, mapping freqencies to elments that occur at it. Then iterate backwards through frequencies, pushing elements into out until we found k.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) (n + n + k) Space: O(n)", "order": 4 }, { "cat": "Arrays & Hashing", "num": 238, "name": "Product of Array Except Self", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use two pointers to create a prefix and postfix sum, bubbling the products forward and backward. Use a single output array of size n, all inited to 1. Keep two temp products, prefix and postfix, inited to 1. Then do one loop from 0 to n. Set out[i] *= prefix, then prefix *= nums[i]. Set out[n - i - 1] *= postfix, then postfix *= nums[n - i - 1].\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1) [except output array]\n\nNotes: The first loop step spreads the product of previous elements forward, the second steps spreads the product of next elements backwards.", "order": 5 }, { "cat": "Arrays & Hashing", "num": 36, "name": "Valid Sudoku", "risk": "Med", "back": "Iterate through each cell in board (for each row, for each column). Extract the number, skip if dot. Then, get sets for number. Check if row, col or block is in row_set, col_set or block_set. If yes, we return false and the board is invalid. Otherwise mark in each set. Mark and check can be done at once with insert(). Note block idx can be done with row_major indexing (x / 3 + (floor(y / 3) * 3). If none fail board is valid.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^2) = O(9^2) Space: O(3 * n^2 = O(3 * 9^2)\n\nNotes: There are two ways to track state, per number, or per row/col/block. It comes out the same because with 1) with 9 (numbers) * 3 (rows,cols,blocks) sets = 27. With 2) with 9 (rows) + 9 (cols) + 9 (blocks) = 27 (sets). Note instead of the sets we can use bit masks which are probably faster and definetly use less space. If using nums to index, take care to offset by 1 (rows and cols are in range 0-8, nicely enough). Also need to use u16 for mask, because 0 has to be a represented value and and we need 9 values total (1 << 8 is out of range of u8).", "order": 6 }, { "cat": "Arrays & Hashing", "num": 271, "name": "Encode and Decode Strings", "risk": "Med", "back": "Encode string as len + delim char + str literal. Then decode is iterate over string, find delim. chars between i and delim is len. parse len. then substr from delim + 1 to len is new string, append to result. set i to delim_pos + 1 + len\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Can in theory skip delim and use fixed with len, but delim makes parsing simpler (seek forward until we hit it). Seek until j is at delim, not past, makes from_chars work. Use from_chars (C++17) to parse len. Then use substr(j + 1, len) to get the new string to append.", "order": 7 }, { "cat": "Arrays & Hashing", "num": 128, "name": "Longest Consecutive Sequence", "risk": "Med", "back": "Keep i map<int,int>, key is a number, value is length of connected sequence when we inserted. Iterate nums. If num in map skip. Otherwise check if we have map[num - 1] and map[num + 1], because this num might connect a sequence left and/or right of it. The new length is 1 + left + right lenght. Take max result/lenght. Finally check if we have map[i - left_length] and map[i + right_length]. These are the start/end of the sequence we just connected. Set their value to new lenght, this ensure that any number connecting to them knows how long the sequence currently is.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Source. Code is longer and more complicated, but it runs faster in practice. I dont know why. I think its because the constant matters, the below approach runs in O(2n) at worst\n\n— alt —\n\nBuild a set out of the nums. Iterate nums. Check if i - 1 is in the set, if yes this is the middle of a sequence and we can skip it. Otherwise, start counting length at 1. While i + length is in set, inc lenght. This iterates the numbers in order. Once we iterate the sequence we have the lenght, max with current result. Return result.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: This runs signficantly slower than (2-3x) than the solution above. Runs in O(n) because the inner loop only runs for start of sequence elements, iterating each sequence exactly once.", "order": 8 }, { "cat": "Two Pointers", "num": 125, "name": "Valid Palindrome", "risk": "Low", "back": "Scan the array from the beginning and end, until the indices pass each other. First skip non-alpahnumeric characters, then compare the lowered char at the indices. If they differ at any point its not a palindrome.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Take care to check the indices dont run past each other while skipping non-alphanum.", "order": 9 }, { "cat": "Two Pointers", "num": 167, "name": "Two Sum II - Input Array Is Sorted", "risk": "Low", "back": "Scan using two pointers, i start at 0, j start at len - 1. Loop while i < j. At each step, take the sum of num[i] and num[j]. If the sum is too large, move j left. If the sum is too small, move i right. Otherwise we found it and can return the indices.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 10 }, { "cat": "Two Pointers", "num": 15, "name": "3Sum", "risk": "Med", "back": "Sort the array. Run an outer loop i from 0 to len. Then do an inner loop two sum, with j and k being left and right pointers that move depending on if i+j+k is smaller or larger 0. If its 0, we found a solution, then we advance the l pointer once, then advance it again while its equal to its previous and while it has not overrun r. The two-sum conditions will fix r on their own.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n logn) [sort] + O(n^2) (loop) -> O(n^2) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: We skip early if nums[i] becomes larger than 0. Because we are sorted, there are no negative numbers afterwards, so we cant get a zero sum.", "order": 11 }, { "cat": "Two Pointers", "num": 11, "name": "Container With Most Water", "risk": "Med", "back": "Start with two pointers, l and r, at 0 and n -1. Take the area and see if its max. Now we search forward greedily: We move the pointer on the smaller of the two bars. If they are equal we look forward for l and r and see which has the better neighbor. Keep going until the pointers overlap.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: This is a greedy search approach. We move away from the smaller because we only possibly improve by increasing the height (we're already maximized on the width axis). It is not clear to me that there is a conclusive proof this always finds the best option.", "order": 12 }, { "cat": "Two Pointers", "num": 42, "name": "Trapping Rain Water", "risk": "High", "back": "At each position i, how much water can be trapped is determined by the highest position to the left and right of i. It is then further limited by min(l,r), since it will spill over min. We can do this by determining the max height to the left and right of each i by doing a forwards and backwards scan of the array. Now iterate height, the amount trapped at each i is min(l[i],r[i]) - height[i]. If one of l or r is not tall enough to trap water, the result will be negative, so we just max it with 0 before adding to the total. This solution takes linear memory.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: When doing the min scan passes, we start at 0. At each loop iteration, store the current_max, then replace current with max(current, height[i]).\n\n— alt —\n\nThe above can be turned into O(1) space by doing l/r scan l=0, r=len-1. At each step, check if current l_max or r_max is smaller. Advance the pointer with the smaller max. Then add to the total max(0, current_max - height[i]). Then update the current max. This works pretty much exactly like the 3-scan solution: The min between the two maxes is taken care of by the check which current max is smaller. We know we cant spill over the side of the max we havent chosen, because the we've chosen is smaller already. And we only update the new max after calculating the amount of trapped water.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 13 }, { "cat": "Sliding Window", "num": 121, "name": "Best Time to Buy and Sell Stock", "risk": "Low", "back": "Single scan over array. Keep track of max profit so far, and min price so far. Each iteration, min_price is min(min_price, price[i]). Max profit is max(max_profit, price[i] - min_price).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: We can start loop on i = 1. Technically we should update max profit before we update min price, but the other way around we'd just sell on the same day if that was the min price, and we would just make 0 profit.", "order": 14 }, { "cat": "Sliding Window", "num": 3, "name": "Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use a bitset to track which characters we've seen already (vector_bool size char_max). Keep a second pointer for where the current substring starts. Do one pass over the string. While the current char is true in the dict, make dict at start pointer char false, inc start pointer and dec cur_len. Then always make current char in dict true, increment cur_len, set max_len to max(max_len, cur_len). This works because second pointer catches up to first occurence of the char that brakes our substring, removing the chars we've seen up until that point so we can scan over them again. Basically once the substring breaks, we catch up to and restore up until where it \"un-breaks\" again\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Space is O(1) because we always use a fixed size dictionary of CHAR_MAX bits. Time O(n) because at worst we slide both the left and right pointer over the while array, which is O(2n) [we never move either pointer back]. Problem can also be done with hash_set, but is slower and space is O(n). Alternatively len can be done without inc/dec, cur_len is (i - j + 1).", "order": 15 }, { "cat": "Sliding Window", "num": 424, "name": "Longest Repeating Character Replacement", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use left and right pointers. Use a char dict (array of len(26)) to keep track of how many times each char appears in subwindow. Keep track of max element in dict arr (most common letter). At each step, right increments. Update frequency of letter at right. Then check if it replaces our most common. Next see how many chars we need to replace for our current subwindow, which is the subwindow length (r - l + 1) minus the most common occurrence (since we need to replace all other chars). If this is more than k, we need to shrink our subwindow. We do this by decreasing the frequency at l, then moving l by one. Finally we check the length of the current subwindow (r - l + 1) and see if it replaces our last max window.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Basically, we assume we need to replace all letters other than the most common in the subwindow, which makes sense because this is how we make the longest common substring. If we exceed k, we don't need to update our most common element count because it was the most common previously. We dont care that it got shorter, because it only needs to be replaced if another element became more common, which would extend our subwindow. If that was the case, it would replace the most common element count at the start of the loop when the character with the new highest frequency is checked. Also we dont use the most common element count to decide the max len at the end of the loop, so we dont care if it is technically invalid. If we dont feel like proving that it doesnt matter that we dont update max_freq, we can instead just keep the index if the max_freq el and always look it up, then the modification to freq when shrinking the window will auto apply if it is the same element as max_freq", "order": 16 }, { "cat": "Sliding Window", "num": 567, "name": "Permutation in String", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use a char dict (fixed size 26) mapping how often each char appears. Build a const one for pattern, then keep a mutable one for text. L and r pointers starting at 0, iterate through text. Increase text_dict at r, then while text_dict at r > pattern_dict at r (invalid subwindow), decrease text_dict at l, increase l. Then check if (r - l + 1) is pattern lenght, if so we found a valid subwindow.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n): Space: O(26)\n\nNotes: Dict works because we want to find any permutation of pattern in text, so we only care about char counts and contiguosness. Time cost is O(len(p)) for building pattern + O(2n) for iteration. Basically this relies on the following idea: We know the length of the substring we want to find. Because we shrink the window everytime it includes a char not in the substring, we must have found a valid window if its the same size as substr, because window can only be that size of it only includes the right chars in the right amounts from substr.", "order": 17 }, { "cat": "Sliding Window", "num": 76, "name": "Minimum Window Substring", "risk": "High", "back": "Use a helper data structure with a map from char to struct. The struct is a count of char in pattern string and count of char in current subwindow. We build the Window struct from pattern string. Now iterate once with l and r pointer. Add char at text[r]. Add operation checks if char is in map, ignores if not. If it is, it increases the count in cur window, if pattern and window count is same after inc, we just became valid, so we inc our number of valid chars. Now main loop checks if window is valid, which is true if Window struct num of valid chars is equal to map size (has each char become valid count). While window is valid, replace min_l and min_r (outside loop vars) if current l and r make shorter window. Then remove char at l and advance l. Remove is opposite of add in window dict, if char is in map, check if needed == curr, if yes, decrease valid_chars because this one just became invalid, then decrease curr (need check first for validity). Reduce subloop runs while window is valid. Whole subloop runs until end of main string. At the end, if we have a valid l/r range, return str.substr(l, r - l + 1), otherwise empty string.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(2n) Space: O(alphabet_size) == O(1)\n\nNotes: The dict structure lets us check efficiently if our subwindow is valid. Then we can simply grow the window until its valid, then shrink until it becomes invalid, noting the min size at each step. Rinse repeat until we've scanned the whole string", "order": 18 }, { "cat": "Sliding Window", "num": 239, "name": "Sliding Window Maximum", "risk": "High", "back": "Use a deque of indices. Output array can be reserved to n - k + 1. Use l and r pointers. Iterate r until len. Each step: while index at que back points to value smaller than value at r, pop back. Then push r. If que front index larger than l, pop (shrinks window down to size, only need one cause we inc l by one and check every step). Then, if r + 1 > k (guards the first few iterations where we haven't built a k-size window yet), push value pointed to by que front into output array (que front has max value of window), then increment l. Loop increments r. Return result.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(2n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: We use monotonically decreasing queue, so a queue that is at all times sorted descending. The first trick is that this queue then has the max element at the front, and if a new value comes along, we replace all elements at the back that were smaller, which gets rid of the elements in the window that would never be max, but keeps the the others in the window that are still bigger. The other trick is that the queue stores indices rather than values, that tells the start of our window, ends lets us pop off the front of the queue if our window got too big (e.g. the array is already sorted in decreasing order, so this prevents us from keeping elements that are max but fell out of the array). A nice thing to do here for cleanliness is to wrap the index value into its own struct for type safety.", "order": 19 }, { "cat": "Stack", "num": 20, "name": "Valid Parentheses", "risk": "Low", "back": "Use stack. If the char is open brack, push. Else if stack is empty or top of stack is not matching opener, is invalid so return false. Else pop. At end of function return if stack is empty.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n): Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Empty check is important if e.g. we get string with single closer. Use std::stack because the interface plays nice, vector does not and has weird edge cases. Can in theory use a switch to handle everything nicely in one block. This handles non-brack character, my solution does not.", "order": 20 }, { "cat": "Stack", "num": 155, "name": "Min Stack", "risk": "Low", "back": "Straight forward stack based on vector, just make sure to handle empty. Two approaches to handle min: 1) keep a single min value, and restore it when we pop and top is min by searching for the new min. Check if top is min before popping, restore after popping. Restore needs to also check if stack is empty, and if so, instead set min_val to default. Default for min_val is INT_MAX. 2) Keep two stacks, one of values, other of min values. When pushing, check if new val is smaller then min_stack top. If so, push new val, else push top element of stack again. GetMin returns top of min stack, popping pops val_stack and min_stack always.\n\nComplexity: Time: Amortized O(1) for all ops in both approaches: Space 1) O(n) 2) O(2n)\n\nNotes: 1) amortizes min value tracking by only doing it on pop if top is min. 2) is always O(1) time, but trades it off with constant on space (2n). There is a slightly tricky variant on 2) where we use one stack. Basically on push, we check if we get a new min. If we do, we push the old min and then replace the tracked min_val, then we push the new val. Then when popping, we check if we popped the min_val, if we did, we pop again and set min_val to the popped value. This basically works by recording the old min val into the stack any time a new min val is pushed, so when popping min, we can get the history from the stack directly by popping again. Probably still O(n) space if we push e.g. (5,4,3,2,1), but a cute trick to reduce average expected memory.", "order": 21 }, { "cat": "Stack", "num": 150, "name": "Evaluate Reverse Polish Notation", "risk": "Low", "back": "Use a stack of ints. For each token: If token is an op, pop top two elements from stack, apply op, push result back into stack. If token is a literal, parse with from_chars(first_char, last_char, out_arg), then push into stack. At the end if expression is valid, we should have on arg in stack, the result. Pop it and return it.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Arguments popped are right arg first, left arg second. This is because we are using a stack, so we get things in FIFO order. The left arg gets push first, then the right arg.", "order": 22 }, { "cat": "Stack", "num": 22, "name": "Generate Parentheses", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use backtracking. Recursive, pass an out array, a current string, int of open parens are left, int of close parens left. If open and close is 0, we've made a valid string, push it into out. If open larger 0, push '(', dec open, recurse, then pop string, inc open.  If open is smaller than close (condition that prevents us making invalid strings), repeat for close and ')'.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(2^2n * n) Space: O(num_valid_permutes * 2n)\n\nNotes: This is really a backtracking problem. We use backtracking to walk through a tree of valid solutions. The out string acts as a stack. Complexity can use recursion analysis approach, where its O(b^d), b is number of branches at each call, d is the max depth of the call tree. We get 2 from the 2 recursive calls we can make at each step, the 2n because thats where we terminate (a valid string is 2n chars long). The extra 2n comes from the 2n chars we have to append together to build every solution, or rather in our c++ solution we spend copying the final string out to the result. Space comes from n chars times 2. Tight bounds is to do with catalan numbers, which tells you number of valid permutations. This would also tell us the space complexity exactly. See this and this for catalan numbers.", "order": 23 }, { "cat": "Stack", "num": 739, "name": "Daily Temperatures", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use a stack of indices. Loop through the array. While there are vals in the stack and day i is larger than the top of the stack: calculate the difference by taking i - top. Index to write to is top. Pop. Then after while, push i into stack. Basically, the stack tracks all days that havent had a hotter one so far. It works because if day i + 1 was larger than day i, we would have popped. If day i + 2 is <= day i + 1, it must also be <= day i. If day i + 2 is larger > day i + 1, it may be larger than day i, and we'll get to check because we definetely pop day i + 1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Time O(n) because we process each entry at most twice (once when its the frontier, second when we pop it off the stack to calculate the days)", "order": 24 }, { "cat": "Stack", "num": 853, "name": "Car Fleet", "risk": "Med", "back": "Sort in descending order of positions. Keep a stack. Iterate the sorted array: Calculate how many steps it will take this car to arrive ((target - pos) / vel). Check if something is in the stack and if stack top takes longer or same amount to arrive. If yes, ignore current car, it has formed a fleet with stack top. If current takes longer, push into stack. It will never catch up to car in front, and will bottleneck all cars behind it, preventing them from fleeting with cars ahead of current. But current is now stack top, so cars behind it may still fleet with it. Result is stack length.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n logn) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Can have O(1) space by using a variable and a slowestArrival value each starting at 0. At each step, still compute stepsToArrive. If stepsToArrive > slowestArrival, make slowest equal steps and inc counter (we've found a new fleet/bottleneck). Otherwise skip, it has caught up and formed a fleet.", "order": 25 }, { "cat": "Stack", "num": 84, "name": "Largest Rectangle in Histogram", "risk": "High", "back": "Use a monotic increasing stack. The intution is that from each height, the area of the rect can grow only if the heights to the right are larger or equal. If we find a hole (smaller height), we can work backward for the recorded ones, calculating how big a rectangle they span back, and afterwards discarding them. So, stack stores index + height. Iterate heights. First, declare start = i. Then while back of stack height larger height[i], pop idx and h from stack. Area is h * (i - idx). Save if new max height. Replace start with idx, since our smaller cur height[i] can run up to this idx. After no larger heights remain, push (start, height[i]) into stack. This is a record of where the last larger height was that formed a rectangle with height[i] (not smaller than it). After iterating heights, iterate the stack. For each (idx, height), calc maxArea = height * heights.size() - idx. Replace maxArea if bigger. Return maxArea\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: During pop, i - idx for area beause thats how many entries deep into stack pop we are (the range from current height we are replacing forwards to the height that is replacing it, where the hole is. All heights before it, that we already popped, were larger and so form a rectangle with this one we are popping now. During second stack iteration, size - idx for area because to the right of this height there are only larger heights, so rectangle spans to the end. size - idx gives us num rects in heights without the ones before current idx.", "order": 26 }, { "cat": "Binary Search", "num": 704, "name": "Binary Search", "risk": "Low", "back": "Implement binary search. Do it with a while loop instead of recursively for better perf. low = 0, high = len - 1. Cast len to int first so it goes negative if len is 0 and we early terminate. Mid is (low + high) / 2. If mid is target return, if mid < target set low mid + 1, if mid > target set high mid - 1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Loop while low <= high. Equal important because we might divide logn times exactly, at which point low == high but the element could be target", "order": 27 }, { "cat": "Binary Search", "num": 74, "name": "Search a 2D Matrix", "risk": "Low", "back": "Treat matrix as a 1D array, binary search it. low = 0, high = rows * cols. (rows is matrix size, cols is size of first vector). Do normal binary search. When looking up mid value, calculate row and col. Row is mid / cols, Col is mid - (Row * cols).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(mn)) Space: O(1)", "order": 28 }, { "cat": "Binary Search", "num": 875, "name": "Koko Eating Bananas", "risk": "Med", "back": "Binary search the range of possible numbers to divide. Left = 1, Right is either maxVal (10^9) or (maxEl(piles)). Run while left < right. Calculate mid, then check if mid divides down in less than h steps. Do so by iterating each pile, and adding ceil(p / mid) to sum. If sum <= h, we can divide in time. If thats the case, set right = mid. Else set left = mid + 1. Return left or right (same thing cause we'll end when they are equal).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(max) * n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: For the sum, floating point inaccuracy can fail the ceil() approach. Can instead do a pad up by calculating (p + mid - 1) / mid. For result, we can store of value of mid into a var k when we find a possible divide, then set r = mid - 1 (we cant do mid - 1 if we use r/l for return value). At the end we return k. A little simpler to reason about than returning left.", "order": 29 }, { "cat": "Binary Search", "num": 1011, "name": "Capacity To Ship Packages Within D Days", "risk": "Med", "back": "Binary search the range of possible weights. Left is maxEl of weights (we need a ship with atleast that capacity to carry all packages), Right is sum of weights (if we only have one day, we need to ship all at once). While left < right, calc mid (left + (right - left) / 2). Check if mid (weight) can ship all in maxDays. Do that by iterating weights, suming up. If sum > mid, incr countDays, set sum 0. At the end add 1 to countDays (for the weights left in sum), then check if countDays <= maxDays. If yes, right = mid. Else left = mid + 1. At the end return left.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(m) * n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Finding the correct l and r bounds is important!", "order": 30 }, { "cat": "Binary Search", "num": 33, "name": "Search in Rotated Sorted Array", "risk": "Med", "back": "We do normal binary search, but each step identify if m is in the larger or smaller partition and move it accordingly. m is in smaller sorted part if nums[l] <= nums[m], otherwise its in larger part. If in smaller, we move l = m + 1 if (move to right part) if target > nums[m] (normally binserach condition) or if target < nums[l] (there are values smaller than m, but only bigger than target to the left, so values <= target can only be on the right side). Otherwise we move r = m - 1. If m is in the larger part, we move r = m - 1 if target < nums[m] (normal binsearch condition) or if target > nums[r] (there are values larger than m, but only smaller than target to the right, so values >= target can only be on the left side). If not found return -1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(n)) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: There is a much simpler two pass version to this. We do one binary search to find the pivot, which we can determine based on whether mid is smaller then left, if yes continue left since that partition is out of order, else continue right.\nThen we check if the target element needs to be search for in the left or right partition. We can check if its smaller than nums[0], if yes it must be in the right partition, else it will be right of nums[0] and so in the left partition. If pivot index is 0 (no rotation, just search the whole array).", "order": 31 }, { "cat": "Binary Search", "num": 153, "name": "Find Minimum in Rotated Sorted Array", "risk": "Med", "back": "Binary search while left < right. If (nums[l] < nums[r]), we found a sorted partition and the min can be returned from left. This is because elements only ever rotate around to the right, so rotating only ever puts a bigger element to the left than will be right, until we rotate the min el around. Otherwise, calculate mid. If nums[mid] >= nums[left] we need to step right, left = mid + 1. Because if the mid is >(=), either we found min (see notes) or if we got here, and our early out (l < r) didnt hit, the left portion is all rotated elements, and the min must be right. Else, nums[mid] < nums[left], we need to step left, right = mid. There are rotated elements to the left, but not enough to shift the minEl past our pivot, so it must be to the left of us.If the middle is smaller then the left, there is some rotation on the left, and the min will be to the right of it. But we are smaller so either we are min or the min is to the left of us. At the end, return nums[left].\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(n)) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: The edge case where our partition is two elements, but the left is larger is handled by the nums[mid] >= nums[left] case. Mid will be the left element, which is obv equal to itself. This moves left mid + 1, so the right element which will be the min. L is now R, and we break and return L. If two elements but left is smaller, we fall into the outer case where we return if nums[l] < nums[r]. https://changhaz.wordpress.com/2014/10/15/leetcode-find-minimum-in-rotated-sorted-array/", "order": 32 }, { "cat": "Binary Search", "num": 410, "name": "Split Array Largest Sum", "risk": "High", "back": "Same solution as 1011. We can minimize the sum by checking the space of possible sums, which ranges from left = max(nums) to right = sum(nums). While left < right, calc mid, which is the sum we're testing can be achieved with m parts. Check by iterating nums, adding i to sum. If sum exceeds mid, set to 0, inc num needed parts (which starts at 1 to account for last part left at the end). If needed parts exceeds num, return false, else true. If mid can be achieved as a sum using m parts, halve the search space downwards by setting right = mid. Else the sum we tested for is too small, we need to halve the space upwards, left = mid + 1. Return left.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(sum(nums)) * n) Space: O(1)", "order": 33 }, { "cat": "Binary Search", "num": 981, "name": "Time Based Key-Value Store", "risk": "Med", "back": "Build a map of arrays. Key is string key, value is array pair<timestamp, value>. On insert, get or insert array for key. Push back pair into array. Can just pushback because timestamp values sent to set only increase. Otherwise we could use binary search to do sorted insertion. For get, we first check if we have the key in the map. If yes, we binary search the map. left = 0, right = len(arr). While left < right, calc mid. If mid_val <= target, res = mid, left = mid + 1 (we've found a viable element, now search upward to see if we can find a bigger viable one). Else mid = right (the midval was > target, so not viable, we need to search downward). At the end return res if we found something, else \"\".\n\nComplexity: Time: Insert Amortized O(1) Find O(1) + log(n) Space: O(key map entries) + O(value array entries), O(n)\n\nNotes: See this for a good bisect_right. Bisect_right gives the position to the right of the key, so for find the key is at pos - 1, for insert we use pos since insert puts the key before pos. Also helpful.", "order": 34 }, { "cat": "Binary Search", "num": 4, "name": "Median of Two Sorted Arrays", "risk": "High", "back": "We know the median is the element that splits the array in exactly half. We're going to find the smaller partition in each array so that together they make up the smaller part in the \"merged\" array and the element to the right gives us the median. We binary search the smaller array a not the bigger b, left = 0, right = a_len. While left <= r, we get a_mid = (l + r) / 2. b_mid must make up the rest of the half partition, so it is ((total_len + 1) / 2) - a_mid. Then we get the max el of left part and min el of right part for both arrays. Do so for by checking if mid <= 0, if yes we use placeholder INT_MIN, else its a/b[mid - 1]. For min check if mid >= len, if yes use placeholder INT_MAX, else its a/b[mid]. Now we test if our partitions are correct. If maxLeft1 <= minRight2 and maxLeft2 <= minRight1, we have the right partition. If we have an odd array, we can return then max(maxLeft1, maxLeft2). Otherwise return max(maxLeft1, maxLeft2) + min(minRight1, minRight2) / 2. If we havent found the right partition, check if maxLeft1 > minRight2, if so shift right to a_mid - 1. Otherwise shift left to a_mid + 1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(m + n)) Space: O(1)", "order": 35 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 206, "name": "Reverse Linked List", "risk": "Low", "back": "Keep a prev (starting as null) and cur (starting as head) ptr. Iterate while cur is not null. Take a temp, which is cur->next. Make cur->next prev. Make prev cur. Make cur temp. Return prev.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 36 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 21, "name": "Merge Two Sorted Lists", "risk": "Low", "back": "If either list is null, return the other for early out. Then select list with smaller head as l, the other as r. Make head l. Make curr head. Advance l. While l and r both yield, select node with smaller value, append to curr and advance. Advance curr to next. At the end if l or r has nodes left, append as curr next. Only one list will have a dangling remainder. Return the head we saved at the beginning.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n+m) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Worth looking at my submissions, I wrote a nice solution the first time around, though when I implemented that version again I did a better job selecting r after l (just check if l is list1 or 2).", "order": 37 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 143, "name": "Reorder List", "risk": "Med", "back": "Find the second half, reverse it, splice it into the first half. Find first half using mid and end pointer, advance mid = mid->next, end = end->next->next, while end && end->next. Mid now is the last node of the first half. Unlink the second half and reverse it using the \"reverse linked list\" method. Now using head (head of first half) and prev (head of second half), splice them. While prev, take temp head->next and prev->next. head->next = prev, prev->next = temp1. Head = temp1, prev = temp2. This inserts the second half elements between the first half elements.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 38 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 19, "name": "Remove Nth Node From End of List", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use two pointers to find the nth node, end and nth. First increase n by 1 so we seek to the node before nth. Then while, n > 0 and end != null, advance end and dec n.  Now end is ahead of nth by n + 1 steps. If n == 1, we have to remove the head. If n < 0, we dont have enough nodes in the list. Else, while end != null, advance end and nth. Now we can remove the node after nth by taking its next->next, unlinking the next, and setting end->next to end->next->next. Return head.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 39 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 138, "name": "Copy List with Random Pointer", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use a hashtable to map old node ptr to new node ptr. Put a (null, null) pair in the map so we dont need to handle null links later. Iterate the list once, creating node copies, adding them to the map as (srcNode, dstNode). Then iterate the src list again, looking dst ptr up using src ptr. Then set dst->next to map[src->next], dst->random to map[src->random]. Return map[head].\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Can also be done O(n^2) time O(1) space by skipping the map. Instead create the copied list. Then iterate the copied list. For each node, search the random in src list. For both the inner and outer search keep a pointer in lockstep in the cpy list, next and random can be copied from the cpy pointers.", "order": 40 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 2, "name": "Add Two Numbers", "risk": "Low", "back": "Iterate while l1 or l2 or carry has a value. If l1 or l2, get the value from each and advance. If either null use 0 placeholder val. New digit is lVal + rVal + carry. Carry is digit / 10. Digit is Digit mod 10. Alloc new node with digit value, assignt to cur next, make cur cur next.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Can avoid checking for head in loop by using a stack allocaed fake node as the first cur. At the end return fake node -> next", "order": 41 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 141, "name": "Linked List Cycle", "risk": "Low", "back": "Use a fast and slow pointer. While (fast && fast->next), advance slow by one, fast by two. Then check if (slow == fast), return true if yes. Otherwise loop eventually breaks, return false.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Intuition: Floyd's Tortoise and Hare. Initially the gap between fast and slow is some x. At each step, slow adds one to x, fast removes two from x. This will eventually reach 0 and they hit the same pointer if they can loop around. The distance can at most be n, so at most O(n) complexity. The loop is essentially just a smaller list we have to first reach for the catching up to begin.", "order": 42 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 287, "name": "Find the Duplicate Number", "risk": "High", "back": "Binary search the range l = 0, r = n (len - 1). We're trying to subdivide the problem to find the one element that has a duplicate. While (l < r), calc mid. Then check if 0..mid is a range that  has duplicates by counting the number of elements in nums that are <= mid. If this count > mid, it means we have more than n elements that are <= n, so there must be atleast one duplicate element. In that case step left, r = mid. Otherwise if count <= mid, there are n or less elements smaller n (exactly n if only one duplicate, otherwise possibly less), so no duplicates. So step l = m + 1. At the end return l.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*log(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Proof there must be a duplicate is pigeonhole principle. If there are n + 1 slots, but only numbers in the range 1..n, atleast one of those numbers must double up. Justification for stepping left or right: We know the whole range has too many elements. If our partition has duplicates, then we can search left because we include which atleast has duplicates. If the range doesnt, we can step right, because the right half must have a duplicate, otherwise it wouldnt be the full range.\n\n— alt —\n\nTreat the array as a linked list. Use slow = nums[0], fast = nums[nums[0]] pointers. Step the same way until slow == fast, we have found the meeting point in our cycle. Now reset fast to 0, While slow != fast, step slow by nums[slow] and fast by nums[fast] (so equal speed). Fast will catch up to slow on the duplicate element, which is the entry point to the cycle.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: This is nutty.  We know there must be a cycle because atleast two elements point at the same element, which is equivalent to a cycle in the linked list. The start of the cycle will be the element that occurs >= 2 times therefore. The first step is exactly Linked List Cycle / Tortoise and Hare, find a meeting point = cycle. We cant get stuck on an element somewhere because we cant back to nums[0] (no 0 in array). The second part about finding the list start is a lot more complicated. The distance from head to loop start plus the distance from loop start to meeting point is (m + k). It can be shown that (m + k) is an integer multiple of loop length l, so (m + k) = l * i . When we reset fast, and keep the slow pointer at the meeting point, slow is k ahead from loop start (cause thats the distance to it from meet). When we reset fast to head and let it step by one, it will travel m steps. We know m + k makes a whole loop length, so it will advance slow to the loop start, where they will then meet. Making fast travel m distance moves it to loop start as well, so thats why they meet there. See this and this. This has the best algebraic explanation of why finding entry works.", "order": 43 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 142, "name": "Linked List Cycle II", "risk": "Med", "back": "Null if head or head next is null. Use tortoise and hare to find meeting point. If slow != fast return null. Set fast head, while slow != fast advance each by 1. Return slow. Floyds algorithm\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 44 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 146, "name": "LRU Cache", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use a linked list + hashtable. Hashtable stores keys + nodes, used for fast lookup in get and put. Linked list is doubly, storing key and value. Implement a remove function that unlinks node, and a insert head function (dont forget to fixup m_Head->next->prev on head insertion!). Init the map with empty head and tail node pointing each other, makes code much simpler, for lru just get tail prev. Implement get node that looks for node in table, if found, removes and inserts at head, returns node. Get calls getnode, returns val if found. Put Calls getnode, updates val and returns if found. Else alloc new node, fill out key and val, add to hashtable, inserthead. Then if hashtable size > capacity, get tail prev, is the lru element. call remove on it, remove its key from hashtable, delete node.\n\nComplexity: Time: get/put amortized O(1) Space: O(n) map + O(n) List\n\nNotes: Implementing separate insertHead and remove methods makes this very simple. Pre-allocating fixed, empty head and tail nodes makes this even simpler! Std::list implementation see here, might be nice for interviews. This one looks nicer", "order": 45 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 23, "name": "Merge k Sorted Lists", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use a min heap, priority_queue with > larger compare. Insert all nodes into queue. If empty, return null. Otherwise, pop once to get head/cur. Then while cur, cur->next is q.top(), pop() q, cur = cur->next. At the end set cur->next null, return head.\n\nComplexity: Time: n = num nodes, O(n * log(n)) q build, + O(n * log(n)) list build + q pop/restore. Space: O(n)\n\n— alt —\n\nDivide and conquer, like mergesort. While lists in array, take two lists out of array, merge them (merge works exactly like 21. Merge Two Sorted Lists), put it back. Repeat until we have one merge list, return it. At each step we consider all n nodes, but we can only repeat this step log(k) times until we only we have 1 list left.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*log(k)), Space: O(1) if recursive, O(k) if iterative\n\nNotes: Can be done two ways: 1) recursive divide and conquer. Merge method that takes array, l idx and r idx. If l == r, base case, return array[l]. Otherwise take m = (l+r) / 2. call merge(arr, l, m) and merge(arr, m + 1, r). This will divide down until base case, then merge the two returned lists, and returned the merged one. At the end we get one complete list. 2) Iteratively, have two arrays. While front.size() > 1 outer loop, while front.size() > 0 inner loop, pop pairs out of front (if only one left just take that), merge the pair, push it into back. Swap back and front, repeat. At the end front contains one merged list.", "order": 46 }, { "cat": "Linked List", "num": 25, "name": "Reverse Nodes in k-Group", "risk": "High", "back": "Write helper getKth that takes node and returns node k steps after (or null if run out). Make a dummyhead with next is head. Make a prevGroup pointer is the last node of prev reversed segment, set it to dummy. While true, getKth from prevGroup, is the last node of current unreversed segment. Make a nextGroup, is k->next, first element of next segment. If k is null, we ran out, break loop. Now reverse segment, prev = nextGroup (attach reversed segment to it), cur is prevGroup->next. Reverse while cur != nextGroup. Prev now holds reversed list + rest of list, prevGroup holds start of prev group -> last element of reversed list (first element beforehand, which is why its linked to prevGroup). Take temp is prevGroup->next (last el of reversed segment). Set prevGroup->next to prev (attach whole list back to prevGroup head), set prevGroup to temp (now points to last element of last reversed segment in whole list). After loop return dummy->next.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: There is a stack-based solution taking O(k) space. Push into stack until size k, then pop empty and build a reversed list. Keep track of last reversed list tail and append to that after building.", "order": 47 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 226, "name": "Invert Binary Tree", "risk": "Low", "back": "Swap the left and right child of each node. Done recursively by swapping left and right, then calling invert on left and right, then returning root. Iteratibvely using queue, push root, pop node, swap node left and right, push node left and right if either is not null. Then return node.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1) / O(N)\n\nNotes: Early out if root is null. If recursion, run only if node is not null. If using queue, only push if child is not null. O(1) space only if you're a liar and claim the stack is not \"extra space\".", "order": 48 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 104, "name": "Maximum Depth of Binary Tree", "risk": "Low", "back": "Recursive DFS. Base case node is null, return 0. Else return 1 + max(depth(node->left), depth(node->right)), This selects the longest branch as we explore the tree.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 49 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 543, "name": "Diameter of Binary Tree", "risk": "Med", "back": "Recursive DFS. Pass a second int argument by reference to store the max diameter at any time. Use the stack to return the current max branch lenght. Base case node is null, return 0. Call recursively on left and right. Assign to max_diameter max(max_diameter, l + r), this is the max diameter at the current root. Then return 1 + max(l,r) to return the max branch length from the current root, so the node above can use it in its own diameter calculation. This builds on the Maximum Depth Problem, but adds the second argument to store the max_diameter.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Recursive is the simplest solution, but I came up with something \"cleverer\" that uses returned tuples, see my first accepted submissions.", "order": 50 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 110, "name": "Balanced Binary Tree", "risk": "Med", "back": "Recursive DFS. Pass a bool flag balanced, by reference. Base case root is null, return 0. Call dfs for l, then r. Bool AND balanced with abs(l - r) <= 1, then return max(l, r) + 1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Probably some scope to early return if balanced is already false. abs(l - r) <= 1 is the check that its balanced, height of left and right subtree differs by no more than 1. Binary AND carries the result into the output.", "order": 51 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 100, "name": "Same Tree", "risk": "Low", "back": "Explore both trees in the same order. Either using recursion of queue. If both null, valid, skip. If one null and other isnt, invalid. If one val not equal to other, invalid. Recurse into or push into queue both left and both right.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: recursion O(1)  queue O(2 * log(h))", "order": 52 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 572, "name": "Subtree of Another Tree", "risk": "Med", "back": "Recursive DFS. Implement sameTree(root, sub). Returns true if both null. Else if both non-null and value is equal, return sameTree(left) and sameTree(right). Else return false. Main function returns true if s is null, false if t is null. Returns true if sameTree(t, s), else returns sameTree(t->left, s) || sameTree(t->right, s). Basically DFS on the main tree, at each node try to DFS along with subtree, checking they match up.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|t| * min(|s|, |t|) Space: O(1)\n\n— alt —\n\nUse Merkle tree hashing. Store hash of subtree per node in table. Implement func merkle taking node. If node null, return some symbolic string (e.g. '#').  Else get merkle of left, merkle of right. Combine left  + string(node->val) + right. Hash the string, store in table. Return string(hash). Second recursive function sameTree, returns false if root is null, else checks if table[root] == table[sub], else return sameTree(root->left, sub) || sameTree(root->right, sub). Main function calls merkle t and s, returns sameTree(t, s).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|t| + |s|)  Space: O(|t| + |s|)\n\nNotes: Technically min space is hash per node in t, but with the solution I implemented we also store per node in s. Could easily make it skip tho. Very slow due to string allocs and formats unless implemented carefully with fixed sized buffers and to_chars.", "order": 53 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 235, "name": "Lowest Common Ancestor of a Binary Search Tree", "risk": "Low", "back": "Easy variant for BST: Swap l,r if l_val > r_val. Find the first node where l_val <= node_val && r_val >= node_val. Else if l_val < node_val explore left, else explore right. Done with simple while loop, advancing head. No need for recursion. Ends if cur is null as that is the tree bottom.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(n)) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Works because of BST sorted invariant.", "order": 54 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 236, "name": "Lowest Common Ancestor of a Binary Tree", "risk": "Med", "back": "Not a BST so cant rely on sorting. Instead we have to search the whole tree. if root, p or q are null, return null. Call search and return m_LCA. Search returns false if root is null, Returns false if we already have m_LCA. Bool mid is true if root is p or q. Then call search in root->left and root->right. If left && right true, root is the LCA. Else if mid true and left || right true, mid is also the LCA. Then return mid || left || right.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Basically, at each node, search if left or right contain p and q. If left and right contain one of p or q, we must be the lca. Otherwise if we are p or q and left or right contains p or q, we must also be the lca. m_LCA can also be carried as a TreeNode**.", "order": 55 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 102, "name": "Binary Tree Level Order Traversal", "risk": "Low", "back": "Use a deque. Push the root. While q has elements, take size of q, this is the number of nodes in the level. Alloc a new vec, iterate over number of nodes in level, popping of front and pushing val into vec. If node left or right not null, push back into q, these are nodes for next level. After iterating nodes, push vec into result. Repeat, return result.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Space is actually O(n) output space + queue storing at most nodes equal to last fullest level of tree. Simplifying and assuming its the last level, thats 2^h-1 -> O(2^(ceil(log(n)) - 1))", "order": 56 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 199, "name": "Binary Tree Right Side View", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use a deque for level order. Push the root. While q has elements take the q.back(), this is the rightmost node, append to result. Then normal level order, popping and pushing if children are not null.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Space again is at most our fullest level (technically a little more while we still process the current level). There is also a recursive solution doing pre-order. Passing level count and result vec. if root null, return. If result.size() < level (start level at 1), push root->val. Pushes only the first node for the level. Then recurse into right first with level + 1, then left. Main calls recurse(root, result, 1);", "order": 57 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 1448, "name": "Count Good Nodes in Binary Tree", "risk": "Med", "back": "DFS carrying root and maxVal. if root is null, return 0 (base case). res is 1 if root->val >= maxVal, else 0. maxVal = max(root->val, maxVal). Return res + dfs(root->left, maxVal) + dfs(root->right, maxVal). Main returns dfs(root, INT_MIN).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(log(n))\n\nNotes: Space O(log(n)) because i started counting recursion space. At most our callstack will be height of tree which O(ceil(log(n))).", "order": 58 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 98, "name": "Validate Binary Search Tree", "risk": "Med", "back": "Preorder DFS. Carry root, l and r. l and r start as null. check l is null or smaller than root, r is null or larger than root. If either false, return false, this node fails. Else return valid(root->left, l, root) and valid(root->right, root, r).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(log(n))\n\nNotes: Leftmost branch always carries l null and checks its parent (r) is larger than it. Rightmost branch always checks its parent (l) is smaller than it and carries r null. Inner nodes always have the smallest node above it in l, largest node above it in r. Basically, if we step left, we keep the left boundary the same, but update the right boundard from parent. If we step right, we update the left bounday from parent, and keep the right boundary the same.\n\n— alt —\n\nInorder traversal prints binary tree in sorted order. Can exploit this to check if valid, as each visited element must be larger than its previous. Recursive, pass pointer to prev node*, and ref to valid flag. Recurse left with prev and valid. Then check if prev != null and prev->val >= cur->val, then tree is not valid. Set valid false, return. Else set prev to cur (cur is now the element before the right side in in-order order.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(log(n))\n\nNotes: See algorithm 4 here.", "order": 59 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 230, "name": "Kth Smallest Element in a BST", "risk": "Med", "back": "Iterative in-order traversal. Visit k elements in-order, gives us k-smallest. Make stack. While root or stack is not empty. While root, push root, root is root->next. This pushes the whole left subtree into the stack. Now pop, this is the leaf to visit. Dec k. If k is 0, return node->val. Else set root to node->right. Now we will push the right node into the stack and its left subtree. If there is no right subnode, we'll just pop off the stack and go up the left tree. Along the way it always checks if there is a right subtree to go into. This is how we visit all the nodes.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(h)  = O(log(n))\n\nNotes: Iterative in-order traversal. The (|| !stack.empty()) in the while condition is important, as it will keep us going back up the subtree if there is no right subtree to step into. Can also be done recursive in-order, decrementing k and returning root if k == 0 when we visit root in-order.", "order": 60 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 105, "name": "Construct Binary Tree from Preorder and Inorder Traversal", "risk": "High", "back": "Make use of two ideas: Leftmost node in pre-order is always the tree root. Idx of root in in-order tells us where the tree splits into left and right subtrees. Can use this to divide and conquer. Take the leftmost node of preorder, make subtree root node. Then look up mid index of the element in inorder (can use a prebuild hashmap for this). Now decide the size of the leftHalf by taking mid - inBegin. construct root node. root->left is build(preBegin + 1, preBegin + 1 + leftHalf, inBegin, mid). root->right is build(preBegin + 1 + leftHalf, preEnd, mid + 1, inEnd). Return root. Early return at start of recursion if preBegin >= preEnd (cant halve any more). Start with build(0, preLen, 0, inLen0).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: This solution. Get rid of the -1s at the start by early outing in <= and taking the -1 of end of left in part (no mid - 1), and adding +1 to end of pre in left half (preBegin + 1 lefthalf). End of pre left half and begin of pre right half line up. Begin of in right half is mid + 1 still, while end of in left is mid.", "order": 61 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 124, "name": "Binary Tree Maximum Path Sum", "risk": "High", "back": "Recursive DFS, summing up the paths along the way, clamping out negative values. At each node, return 0 if null. Recurse left and right to get their path sums. Clamp them with 0 to avoid negative paths. Check if node val plus left and right branch sums replaces max, then return node val plus max branch. This returns only the subpath with the bigger sum to the parent.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space:O(h) = O(log(n))", "order": 62 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 297, "name": "Serialize and Deserialize Binary Tree", "risk": "High", "back": "Serialise level order using queue. Pop front, add to string (n if null), push back l and r. Now we have a level order string. Deserialise in the same order, keep a state. State starts as root. Deserial val, if not null make node and push node into queue back. If state root, take root for return later, state is left. If state left, make node queue.front->left, state right. If state right, make node queue.front->right, state left, pop front. Front of queue always has level order parent, after we set the right, we are done with it and can pop.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n) output + O(max level nodes) queue.\n\nNotes: Parsing is easy with left and right pointers and std::from_chars. Can make a little simpler and avoid state flag if we: do root fixed. Then pop_front queue. Parse one node, set it left, push back. Parse another node, set it right, push back. Loop, repeat. Another option is recursive dfs. Serial is recursive, carrying string. Add node to string, then recurse left, right. Serial does a pass over string, reading nodes and putting them into queue. Then recurse carrying q. Pop q front, if null, return null. Else make node, left is recurse, right is recurse.", "order": 63 }, { "cat": "Trees", "num": 701, "name": "Insert into a Binary Search Tree", "risk": "Med", "back": "We traverse down the tree until we find a valid empty slot to insert to. Can be done recursively or iteratively. If root is null, just make a new node and return it. Else if val < root->val, if root->left is empty, insert here. Else recurse into left. Else if val > root->val, insert into root->right if empty. Else recurse into root right. Return root.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(treeHeight) Space: O(treeHeight)", "order": 64 }, { "cat": "Tries", "num": 208, "name": "Implement Trie (Prefix Tree)", "risk": "Med", "back": "A Trie is a tree where each node has a child for each symbol in the alphabet. Each path through the tree builds up a word. The node has an additional flag indicating whether it terminates a word. We set this flag on the last letter of a word on insertion. Insertion is iterating through the letters of the word, inserting a new node for that letter along the path if it doesnt already exist. The last node gets the term flag. Searching for a word is also iterating through the letters following the nodes. If along the path we miss a node for a letter, the word is not in the trie. If the last has the term flag set, we have the word. Searching for a prefix in the tree is the same, but just checking if we have all nodes, ignoring the term flag.\n\nComplexity: Time: Insert O(n), Search O(n), Prefix O(n) Space: O(num_nodes * 26), at worst O(26 * num_words * avg_word_len)\n\nNotes: Handy explenation. Dont forget the node destructor!", "order": 65 }, { "cat": "Tries", "num": 211, "name": "Design Add and Search Words Data Structure", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use a trie, insertion works like normal. Search is modified, uses dfs. dfs takes cur node, word, cur idx. Iterate from idx to len. If word[i] is not '.', do normal trie search, trying to find next letter node in cur, if not found return false, else cur is next. If word[i] is '.', iterate over all valid child nodes in cur, and dfs into them. If any return true, return true, else false. End of search checks cur->m_Term like normal.\n\nComplexity: Time: Insert O(n) Search: Best Case O(n) Worst Case O(num_branches * n) Space: O(26 * num_words * avg_word_len)\n\nNotes: Dfs basically makes sure that all variations of wild cards work. If we have a bunch of wildcards then one letter, we search all branches, then check for the letter of each at then. If we have a letter then a few wildcards we go into letter, then check if branch has a term after the number of wildcards. If we have letter->wildcard->letter, we search for letter, then go down each branch trying to continue the letter search after n children. If we run out of letters to fill wildcards that loop will fail and return false.", "order": 66 }, { "cat": "Tries", "num": 212, "name": "Word Search II", "risk": "High", "back": "Build a trie. Then for each letter in the board, dfs the board, traversing the trie along the way. Start at root letter with root coords. Always pass node to check and next coords. If coords < 0 or > max return. If trie node doesnt have letter to check return. Also need visited set since its graph traversal. If visited return early. Else set visited. If trie node is word, add word to result. DFS using next ndoe into four directions. Unset visited. Result needs a set so we dont add duplicates.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*m*max(wordLen)) Space: O(26 * num_words * avg_word_len)\n\nNotes: Time can easily get out of hand here, so need a couple optimisations. Use array for TrieNode for faster lookup. Store words directly in terminating trie nodes so dfs doesnt need to build word. When inserting into result, dont insert word but TrieNode at word. Then at the end when we build vec from set, we can move/copy the words out the nodes. Inline functions.", "order": 67 }, { "cat": "Heap / Priority Queue", "num": 703, "name": "Kth Largest Element in a Stream", "risk": "Low", "back": "Use a min heap of size k, the top of the heap will be the k largest (smallest in a range of k) element. When we push more than k, heap will push up the smallest one to the top, and we can throw it away.\n\nComplexity: Time: Build = O(n * log(k)) Push = O(2 * log(k)) Space: O(k)\n\nNotes: min heap is priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>>. Ctor sets capacity, then calls add for each num in stream. Add pushes val, pops if heap size > capacity, returns priority_queue.top().", "order": 68 }, { "cat": "Heap / Priority Queue", "num": 1046, "name": "Last Stone Weight", "risk": "Low", "back": "Build a max heap out of stones. While heap size > 1, pop the top two elements. If first > second, push first - second back into heap. Else they are equal and disappear. At end either one el left in heap, return it, or return 0 otherwise.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * log(n)) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Initial heap build is O(n*log(n)). Then the inner loop at best reduces the queue size by two, at worst by one. If we have n elements, and each step removes one, thats n steps. We spend 2 log(n) to pop (3 if we push back). Thats O(n * 2 log(n), which is still O(n * log(n)).", "order": 69 }, { "cat": "Heap / Priority Queue", "num": 973, "name": "K Closest Points to Origin", "risk": "Med", "back": "Build a k-max-heap, using the square distance from origin for comparison. Point struct that caches square dist, implements < operator comparing dist2. For each point, push into heap. If heap.size() > k, pop. The top element is always the one with the biggest dist2, so farthest away from origin. Then yield heap into result.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * log(k)) Space: O(k)\n\nNotes: Can use dist2 since we only care about magnitude. Could also use a min-heap that we insert all elements into and the pop k out of, but that uses more space. Could alternatively sort the array or use quick-select.", "order": 70 }, { "cat": "Heap / Priority Queue", "num": 215, "name": "Kth Largest Element in an Array", "risk": "Med", "back": "Using quickselect, which is like quicksort. Idea is to pick random pivot (if just use right we are vulnerable to n^2 worst case), then partition around the pivot. The pivot will now be in its right place, so it will be the k smallest element (we want k largest, but just convert that to k smallest via len() - k). If pivot_idx == k, we found the right element. If pivot_idx < k, we need to go look in the right partition. If pivot_idx > k, we need to look in the left partion. Main starts with l = 0, r = len -1. Loop. pivot is partition(nums, l, r). If pivot is k, return nums[pivot]. If pivot < k, l = pivot + 1. If pivot > k, r = pivot - 1. Repat until found. Partition computes random offset is (r - l + 1) % rand. Pivot idx is l + offset. Swap nums[r] and nums[pivotIdx] so the pivot is out right. Now set p = l (first largest element idx). Loop for i = l, < r. If nums[i] <= pivot, swap nums[i], nums[p], advance p. At the end, swap nums[r] (pivot el) and p (first largest). Return p. This is basically just quicksort parition step. Time complexity: We do log(n) steps (halving the array), each time on average reducing the array, so n, n/2, n/4 -> converges to 2n. Ignore the log(n), at each step we only look at half the elements of the previous step, which again converges to < 2n. See here.\n\nComplexity: Time: avg O(n), worst case O(n^2) unless we use randomization (e.g. pivot). Space: O(1) if we inplace-partition the array, else O(n)\n\nNotes: Very simple solution is to sort and return nums[nums.size() - k], but that modifies the array -> O(n*log(n)). We can also use a k-min-heap (stores k largest elements, once we get more than k top is k+1 largest, throw away) -> O(n*log(k)).", "order": 71 }, { "cat": "Heap / Priority Queue", "num": 621, "name": "Task Scheduler", "risk": "High", "back": "We can calculate the fastest run: Sort the task groups by number of instances. Grab the largest group, dec count by 1. Add it into queue together with timeout n. Grab the next biggest taskgroup and repeat. If a group finishes timeout, re-insert it into the sorted list, remove from queue. Repeat until list and queue are empty. Impl: Counting sort to count task groups. Insert each non-zero group into a prio-que (maxheap). Keep a queue of pair taskCount, timeOutEndTime. While either has items, cycles += 1. If prio-que is empty, set cycles = time of que back (skip ahead until next item finishes timing out). Else, remove top el from prio-que. Dec count, if it still > 0, add count, cycle + n (total cycle count after which timeout finishes) into front of que. Then either way if que has values, and timeout of back que == cycles (we have reached time where this item finishes timing out), remove back of que, push task count back into prio-que.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * log(26) = O(n) Space: O(26)", "order": 72 }, { "cat": "Heap / Priority Queue", "num": 355, "name": "Design Twitter", "risk": "Med", "back": "Struct user containing queue (or array) of tweets and hashset of followed users. queue because we only keep the 10 newest tweets, use array if we wanna keep all. Tweet is id + time, where time is a counter increasing each time a tweet happens (higher timer -> more recent). When we create a user, add self id to followed users so their own tweets show up when we build the feed. Store users in map id -> user. Follow/unfollow finds or creates user, then adds/removes to/from hashset. Tweet finds/creates user, increases time, pushes tweet into queue. GetFeed finds user, iterates through followed, getting that user. Iterate followed tweets, pushing into a prio_que, sorts descending by tweet time. Then pop out heap into array until empty or we have 10 tweets, return array.\n\nComplexity: Time: Follow/Unfollow/Tweet: O(1) Feed: O(n*log(n) Space: O(users + tweets)\n\nNotes: Feed time is O(u * log(t)) u = # followed users, t = total tweets. log(t) is a constant in our case because we only keep n last tweets.", "order": 73 }, { "cat": "Heap / Priority Queue", "num": 295, "name": "Find Median from Data Stream", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use two prio_ques to partition the stream into sorted halfs. The low half will be a max heap, so it has the largest element at the top. The high half will be a min heap, putting the smalles at the top. This always gives access to the two elements that straddle the middle of the stream, which is all we need to calculate the median. Add is: insert into low, push low top into high, pop low. That ensures both heaps remain sorted. Then if low size < high size, move high top into low. That ensure when they should be equal size (at that point high will have one more than low), the straddling elements sit at each top, or if they are unequal the median sits on top of low. Return is if unequal size, low top, else avg if low and high top.\n\nComplexity: Time: Add O(log(n)) Get O(1) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Add time is actually a little larger to maintain sorting. We do up to 3 insertions and two removals, so its really 5 log(n).", "order": 74 }, { "cat": "Backtracking", "num": 78, "name": "Subsets", "risk": "Med", "back": "Solve by cascading. Start with an empty subset in the output. Then iterate over each number. For each number, go over each existing subsets and add each with current number appended to output. Return output.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*2^n) Space: O(n*2^n)\n\nNotes: n time to create subset, 2^n because thats how many unique subsets there are. ouput space 2^n subsets, taking n space each. Generates outputs like this: {}, {1}, {2}, {1,2}, {3}, {1,3}, {2,3}, {1,2,3}\n\n— alt —\n\nSolve by backtracking. Recurse taking i (current element), cur (current set) and out (output array).  Push cur into out, then iterate from i to nums.len. Each step, append nums[i] to cur, recurse with i + 1 and cur, then pop_back cur again (backtracking step). Start recurse with (0, {}), return output.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*2^n) Space: O(n*2^n)\n\nNotes: Can be done non-recursively with a queue. Generates outputs like this: {}, {1}, {1,2}, {1,2,3}, {1,3}, {2}, {2,3}, {3}. Another way to think about this is as DFS on the decision tree, where each decision is to include or not include element i. We can then dfs from 0, if we ever hit nums.len add the current subset and return. Else append nums[i], recurse with i + 1. pop nums[i] from cur, recurse again with i + 1.", "order": 75 }, { "cat": "Backtracking", "num": 39, "name": "Combination Sum", "risk": "Med", "back": "Solve by backtracking. We start at the first element, at each element we have the choice to include the same element again or try the next element. We try until we either reach target as sum, which gives us a solution, or we overshoot target, discarding the attempt. By recursion, pass the cur idx, sum, elements (plus target, candidates and out). If sum > target, return. Sum == target, add els to out, return. Else from idx to nums.len, append nums[i] to els and sum, recurse with i (not 1 + i, because we're allowed to use the same element multiple times). After recurse pop back from els and sum.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(candidates^(target/min_candidate)) Space: O(target/min_candidate)\n\nNotes: First tries all permutations from current element onwards, then from first element onwards, etc. For space complexity, the max depth of our tree will be target divided by min_candidate. E.g. if min_candidate is 2 and target 7, nothing will try more steps than [2,2,2,2]. So space wise our buffer never grows bigger than that. Time complexity wise, we use the O(branches^depth) shorthand. Branches worst case is len(candidates), because we try to choose each el in candidates (in theory less at each depth, but that amortizes just like halving n^2 does), and our max depth is target/min_candidate as said earlier, so time is at worst O(candidates^(target/min_candidate))", "order": 76 }, { "cat": "Backtracking", "num": 46, "name": "Permutations", "risk": "Med", "back": "Multiple ways to do this, but all come down to the idea of removing and reordering as part of backtracking. My chosen way recurses. Basically we remove elements until we hit one el, this is our base case, if hit return an array with that one element. Otherwise, iterate through all elements currently in nums. Remove nums.front(), recurse and take the perms. Now push the removed num into each perm, append each perm into our results. Push removed num back at the end of the nums, now another element is at the front. At the end return result.\n\nComplexity: Time: something resembling O:(n*n!) Space: O(n*n!)\n\nNotes: Another option is to use a visited array and iterate all nums, skipping if visited, during each backtracking step. Simple to write, n*n! time complexity tho. Our chose solution recurses like this for [1,2,3] - [2,3] - [3] (base) -> put [3,2] into result. -> [2] (base) -> put [2,3] into result -> put [2,3,1], [3,2,1] into result. -> [2,3,1] - [3,1] - [1] - [1,3] - [3] - [3,1] - [1,3,2] - [3,1,2] - [3,1,2] - etc..\n\n— alt —\n\nSolve with recursive backtracking. We still want to re-order elements as we backtrack. Pass into recursion, index i, nums and cur. If cur.size is num.size, add to result and return. Else iterate from j = i to nums.size(). add nums[j] to cur, then swap nums[i] and nums[j]. Recurse with i + 1, basically we swapped the element we want to ignore during recursion out before the range we consider next. after recurse, pop_back cur and swap i/j back.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n!) Space: O(n*n!)\n\nNotes: Recurses like this: \nn [1,2,3] c [] n [1,2,3] c [1] \nn [1,2,3] c [1,2] n [1,2,3] c [1,2,3]\nn [1,3,2] c [1,3] n [1,3,2] c [1,3,2]\nn [1,2,3] ....\nn [2,1,3] c [2]", "order": 77 }, { "cat": "Backtracking", "num": 90, "name": "Subsets II", "risk": "Med", "back": "Same solution as Subsets I, but we need to find a way exclude duplicates. We do this by adding extra step to backtracking. After we remove an element from the solution, we also scan the current index forward over all other elements of the same element. This will guarantee that we dont select the same element in the same position multiple times. Scanning forward only works correctly if we sort the array, so we do that before we backtrack.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*2^n) Space: O(n*2^n)\n\nNotes: 2^n because there are 2^n subsets (think of it like the recursion branches^depth rule), each of size n.", "order": 78 }, { "cat": "Backtracking", "num": 40, "name": "Combination Sum II", "risk": "Med", "back": "Combine the techniques of Combination Sum I and Subsets II. Before doing Combination Sum, sort the input array. Then after removing an element from the solution, scan forward while we're still on the same element as previously. Avoids us including the same item multiple times in multiple solutions.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(candidates^(target/min_candidate)) Space: O(target/min_candidate)\n\nNotes: Here we recurse forward with i + 1 because the problem statement says each combination may only use each candidate once, not like Combination Sum I where we're allowed to reuse candidates.", "order": 79 }, { "cat": "Backtracking", "num": 79, "name": "Word Search", "risk": "Med", "back": "Classic dfs with backtracking if we fail. Iterate over each cell in the board, calling dfs. Pass x, y, w, board, visited, and word to dfs. If board[y][x] != word[w], return false, this is not a correct path. else if w == word.size() - 1, return true, we found the full word. Set x,y visited. Now dfs into the four neighbors, always checking bounds or if already visited. dfs, if returns true, return true, we're done. If no neigbors pass, unset visited x,y and return false.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n*4^len(word) Space: O(m*n) visited, O(len(word)) stack space\n\nNotes: Time is m*n for visiting each cell, then 4 (branches) ^ len(word) (max depth) for each dfs of cell. We can avoid visited space by reusing the board and setting the board x,y to a symbolic character when visiting. If we do this, we cant return directly from neigbor loop, we need to break if neighbor true and unset the symbolic character to word[w] so we dont leave the board mutated. Then return if any neighbor was true.", "order": 80 }, { "cat": "Backtracking", "num": 131, "name": "Palindrome Partitioning", "risk": "High", "back": "Think of this as a dfs. At each step with have two choices: if the current string is a palindrome, continue building a palindrome and try further chars, or put the current palindrome into our result and try further chars. We actually express this a little differently: We dfs through the array. At each step, why iterate through to the end from current start. Each iteration, we check if the current string substring from i to j forms a palindrome. If it does, we put into the cur array and dfs a step deeper. This can have two outcomes: it is a palindrome, this will always be true for single characters, or subpalindromes and so we include them in the solution. Otherwise the current substring might not be a palindrome. If its not, we dont abandon the solution, we keep trying to grow the solution and see if more characters build us a palindrome.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(2^n * n) Space: O(2^ * n)\n\nNotes: Can be sped up by keeping an array that maps for each start index i, is the subtring ending in j a palindrome. If true, we can save ourselves the check. We still check failed one so i think maybe a hash map could help. Or i think we have to prebuild pal at the start. Complexity is cleverer than what I describe here, but its easier to think about. Worst case, we have string made of all the same character. In that case we basically try every way to partition the array, where at each step we have two choices, include the element in the palindrom or not, and we can do that at most n times, so per recursion formula branches^depth = 2^n. And each time we would susbtring copy the palindrom, so * n.", "order": 81 }, { "cat": "Backtracking", "num": 17, "name": "Letter Combinations of a Phone Number", "risk": "Med", "back": "Simple backtracking. Create a dict from number to possible letters. Then backtrack using idx, cur and digits. If idx >= digits.size(), we find a solution, add it to result and return. Else iter through each possible letter for the digit at dict[digits[idx]]. Add the letter to cur, backtrack with idx + 1, pop the letter from cur.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(4^n * n) Space: O(n) stack space, O(4^n) output space\n\nNotes: Time: Worst case 4 branches, worst case n tree depth. When found one of the permutations, O(n) time to add to result. Space: There are at worst 4 options we can choose for every key, and there are n keys.", "order": 82 }, { "cat": "Backtracking", "num": 51, "name": "N-Queens", "risk": "High", "back": "Solve via backtracking. Each step, we try the next row. For the row, we iterate each column. We check if we can put a queen in the cell. We can if there are no queens on the same row (we know because we already tried all previous rows, and the ones after a free), on the same column (we can keep a bitset to track which cols have queens), and the same diagonal or antidiagonal (we can keep hashsets of the occupied ones). If we can place in the cell, we add a queen to the state (note the row and col). We add the cur row, diag and antiDiag to our sets and we backtrack with row + 1. If we have n queens in our state, add to result. After backtrack we pop the queen from state and unset col, diag and antidiag. We run our root backtrack with empty state and row 0. Afterwards we have all results, map them to string and return.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n!) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: We can generate diagonal and antidiagonal using row and col. Diag is row - col, which generates neg indices in the northern half, positive in the south. Further north indices decrease, south they increase. Anti diag is row + col. Anti diag indices increase as we march towards the bottom right corner. The col, diag and antidiag sets massively speed up the algorithm.\nSpace O(n) because our solution doesnt track the board state, it generates it later from O(n)-sized data. Time comes from: In the first row, we have n options to place a queen. In the second row we n - 2 options to place a queen (one col and one diag taken atleast). n * n - 2 * n - 4, etc. -> n!", "order": 83 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 200, "name": "Number of Islands", "risk": "Low", "back": "Use dfs to identify connected components. Iterate over each cell in grid. If it hasnt been visited, and if its value is '1', increase num islands, run dfs exploring l,r,u,d if cur is also '1'. This identifies all the '1's we can reach from the current island, so when we later visit them during the loop, we skip over them.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(2*m*n) Space: O(m*n)\n\nNotes: We can use constant space if we're allowed to modify the input grid.", "order": 84 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 133, "name": "Clone Graph", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use bfs or dfs to traverse the graph. Skip visiting node if already visited, else make or get node copy. Iterate node neighbors, get or making neihbor copy, adding to copy node neighbors. Add discovered nodes.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(nodes+edges) Space: O(nodes + edges)\n\nNotes: DFS version is terser, but slower and takes more memory (recursive).", "order": 85 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 695, "name": "Max Area of Island", "risk": "Low", "back": "Same principle as number of islands. Dfs or bfs over each cell with peristent visited array. Instead of counting up the islands, we cant the number of nodes we visit, then take the max between result and max so far. Return max.\n\nComplexity: Time O(2*m*n) Space: O(m*n)", "order": 86 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 417, "name": "Pacific Atlantic Water Flow", "risk": "High", "back": "Key observation is that any cell that can reach both seas can be also be reached from both seas. Its obvious that we dfs to identify paths, but rather than dfs each cell, we can dfs only the cells bordering the seas, marking along the way which cells we visit. At the end we can check if each cell was visited by both seas, if so, its reachable. Have two visited sets a and b. Dfs for each column in first and last row, passing atlantic set in first row, pacific set in last row. Then, for each row in first and last column dfs, again passing atlantic and pacific. Then loop over grid, adding cell if its in both visited set. Dfs also takes last height (self height for first cell) to check if current cell can be reached from last. Dfs returns if out of bounds, already visited or if cur height < last height, since we could only get from cur to last if cur height >= last height. If we pass, add to visited set, dfs into four directions.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n) Space: O(m*n)", "order": 87 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 130, "name": "Surrounded Regions", "risk": "Med", "back": "Solve in two passes. First passes traverse border cells and does DFS. DFS exits if we're out of bounds or if cell != 'O'. Else mark it as 'E'. This marks all 'O' regions that are connected to the border as edges. Then do a second pass over every cell. If the cell is 'E' set it 'O' (was an 'O' connected to the border before), else mark it 'X' (either it was already 'X' or it is a surrounded 'O').\n\nComplexity: Time: O(2*m*n) Space: O(1)", "order": 88 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 994, "name": "Rotting Oranges", "risk": "Med", "back": "We simulate the rotting in waves using BFS. First we do a pass over the whole grid. If the cell is rotten, we add it to our queue. If its fresh, we increment fresh count. Then while queue has elements, we do n steps for the n elements currently in que, these are the rotten ones this frame. Now bfs, popping of the queue, considering each neighbor. if in range, and it is fresh, set it to rotten, dec fresh count, push into queue. After loop, if we still have elements in queue, inc time. Finally if fresh count is 0 return time, else return -1 (if we didn't reach any of the fresh ones during bfs that we counted during first pass, its unsolvable).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n) Space O(m*n)\n\nNotes: Space m*n because worst case all oranges are rotten so they are all in queue after first pass.", "order": 89 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 286, "name": "Walls and Gates", "risk": "Med", "back": "Similar to rotten oranges. Find all gates, add them to the queue. Keep a dist counter, starting at 1. While q has elements, process all elements in queue at start of step. For element, visit each neighbor. Skip if out of range, or if neighbor not empty. Else set room value to dist counter, add room to queue.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n) Space: O(m*n)\n\nNotes: There is a simpler dfs solution using a visited array (see neetcode), but mine made intiutive sense to me.", "order": 90 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 207, "name": "Course Schedule", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can turn the prereqs into a directed graph and then apply toplogical sort to see if there is a path through the graph. If we find a loop instead, we know it cant be completed. Map prereq into a graph by adding prereq[0] as a neigbor into the entry for prereq[1] (we have an edge from 1 to 0). Now keep a visited array and a processed array. For each node in graph, dfs. Dfs set visited[node] true. Then iterate neighbors. If neighbor has been visited, but not processed return false. This means that we've found an edge back to a node we're dfs-ing from, telling us we've found a loop. Else if neighbor has been visited (and processed), skip. Else dfs into neighbor, return false if that dfs fails. After visiting all neigbhors, set processed[node] true, return true.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(V+E) Space: O(V+E)\n\nNotes: We can collapse the visited and processed array into one using an enum.", "order": 91 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 210, "name": "Course Schedule II", "risk": "Med", "back": "Same as \"Course Schedule 1\", using topological sort. Only modification is that we now record the topological order, by pushing the processed node into a stack after we are done dfs-ing it and will set it processed. Into a stack because we visit the topo order in reverse order, we finish processing the last node in order first, the one that will have no outgoing edges. That means the first node in topo order will be at the top of the stack, the one with no incoming edges.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(V+E) Space: O(V+E)\n\nNotes: Instead of a stack we can use an array and just reverse it before we return, instead of pushing into a array out of the stack.", "order": 92 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 684, "name": "Redundant Connection", "risk": "Med", "back": "Build the graph progressively, at each edge checking if it might be a back edge. Iterate through edges. If either vertex doesnt have neighbors, just add it to the graph and continue, it cant be a back edge. If both have neighbors, we first check if its redundant. We do so buy doing a dfs from the source vertex, checking if we can find our way to the target vertex. DFS returns true if it ever finds vertex, false otherwise. If we can find our way back to target vertex before inserting the current edge, we already have an edge that forms the same connection, and so the current is redundant.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^2) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: n for time is V+E, at worst, for every edge we have to visit all edges we previously inserted. This is a bad solution because it doesnt fulfil one of the problem requirements: it returns the first redundant edge, not the last provided. But it also doesnt let me pass a graph with multiple cycles as a test case.\n\n— alt —\n\nIdentify redundant edge using union find. Construct a union find, making the join operation return false if the components are already connected. Then for each edge, try to join them. If we find a redundant edge (where the two nodes being connected are already in the same component), we get false and can return the edge.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(E*log(n)) Space: O(V)\n\nNotes: Also doesnt fulfil the \"the last redundant edge\" requirement, but again, the problem doesnt let us test for this. We could just keep going identifying all redundant edges, and returning the last one. UnionFind's find operation can be sped up to near constant time by doing \"path compression\". During find, before advancing the cur pointer, set parent[cur] to parent[parent[cur]]. This flattens the search data structure so we almost always point directly at the tree root.", "order": 93 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 323, "name": "Number of Connected Components in an Undirected Graph", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use union find to identify number of connect components. Implement UF, then run through all edges and join them. We can get numComp two ways. We can do a pass afterwards counting the number of entries in uf.parents where uf.parents[i] == i, these are the root nodes and form individual components. Or we can do it while joining, by making join() return 0 if two nodes already share a root, 1 if they were joined. Then we start compCount at n, and reduce by result of join(). So we count numComp down each time we actually join, since that by definition reduces the number of individual components.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(E*log(n)) Space: O(V)\n\nNotes: Could also be solved by building the graph and identifying components with bfs/dfs, but that takes O(V+E) time and space.", "order": 94 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 261, "name": "Graph Valid Tree", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use union find to detect cycle. Iterate through edges, join each one. If any ever already have the same parent, they were joined previously and so this edge would create a cycle. Basically \"684. Redundant Connection\". There is an extra edge case though, we could have multiple disconnected trees, so no cycles but not fully connected. We can detect this with an extra pass, either checking that each vertex has the same root, or checking rank to see if atleast one element has rank n (root of the tree).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(E*log(V)) Space: O(V)\n\nNotes: Can also be solved with dfs/bfs. For this, build the adjacency list and dfs/bfs from root. If we ever find a back edge, return false. Otherwise, also check if visited all nodes. If so, we found no cycle and we visited all nodes so its a fully connected tree. Take care with the skip condition during neigbor iteration though. We need to skip if state != Undiscovered since this graph is undirected, so each tree node will have an edge to its parent. Also pass prev into dfs so we can correctly check if a we have a back edge that violates tree condition, since having a \"back edge\" to our parent is allowed and valid.", "order": 95 }, { "cat": "Graphs", "num": 127, "name": "Word Ladder", "risk": "High", "back": "We can express word steps as a graph. First we append the beginword to the list incase its not there. We can now iterate through each string in the wordlist and check it against each other string by scanning through in lockstep. If more than one letter differs, we cant step. Else add an edge to each word from the other. Our graph is an adjacency list the size of word list. Now we have a graph telling us what words we can step from to which. Now we can do a BFS in waves to tell us how to get to endword. First find index of beginword and endword, these are our node ids. If endidx is past wordList.size(), return 0, its not in the list. Now bfs from beginidx, at each step doing iterations for the amount of nodes currently in queue (waves outwards). Steps starts at 1. If cur node we pop is endidx, return steps. Else traverse the neighbors. If we make it through an entire wave, inc steps. If we never find endidx, return 0.\n\nComplexity: Time: Graph build = O(n^2 * strln) O: (V+E) BFS\n\nNotes: There is a way to trade off the cost of building the graph for extra working during the bfs. Instead of generating the graph via compare, we go through word, and generate a \"wildcard\" pattern at each char by replacing it with *. Now if two different words can change into each other, the will have atleast one shared pattern (e.g. hot and dot share *ot). We keep a hashtable from pattern to word that has the pattern. Cost of that is (n*strlen). The bfs now keeps a q of source strings. At each iteration, we re-generate the wildcard patterns for that word. Then we look up the pattern in our hashmap, check each string to see if it has already been visited, and if not add it to the q. There is another version I dont like as much where we keep a set of source words, then at each iteration, go through each char in word, replace it with every possible letter 'a'-'z', check if the permutation is in our set, and if yes and it hasnt been visited, add it to the queue (or return res + 1 if its the end word).", "order": 96 }, { "cat": "Advanced Graphs", "num": 332, "name": "Reconstruct Itinerary", "risk": "High", "back": "Using backtracking. Build a graph out of the edge list, then sort the neighbor lists. Also next the neigbor entry keep a visited flag. This will tell us if we've visited an edge, and allows us to walk back to a parent but stops us getting trapped in cycles. Now backtrack, providing a cur string and a result vector. If our result vector is size numTickets + 1 (each ticket adds two airports, plus one for the first/last), we found a valid tour, return true. If graph doesnt contain cur, return false, we cant leave from this airport and are trapped. Otherwise, iterate through cur's neighbors. Set visited true for next, append next to the flight list, backtrack with next. If backtrack returns true, return true. Else unset the edge visited and pop the list. If we leave the neighbor loop return false, we found no result. At the end return the flights list / result vector.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(f^t) Space: O(A + f)\n\nNotes: Time: We use recursion shorthand O(branches^depth). Max branches f is max number of flights leaving from an airport and t is the number of tickets we have (max number of times we can fly anywhere in total, so the deepest we can recurse). Therefore f^t. Space is number of airports A (vertices) + f (number of flights leaving from airports (edges).                                         We can avoid sorting the graph neighbors after building by sorting the input list. Sort first by src, then by dst, this uses dst as tiebreaker and orders results with the same src by their dst ascending. This is fine because we;re not changing the order of a ticket, just of the ticket array. Todo: Can be solved with eulerian cycles / hierholzer's algorithm, look into if we have time.", "order": 97 }, { "cat": "Advanced Graphs", "num": 1584, "name": "Min Cost to Connect All Points", "risk": "High", "back": "Generate minimum spanning tree using Prim's algorithm. Start from any vertex, add to tree, compare distance to each non-selected vertex, pick the closest, continue with that vertex.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(V^2) Space: O(V)\n\nNotes: O(V^2) because we pick each node for the MST, which is N steps, and then we iterate each other unvisited node for that node, taking another N steps. This gives N^2, but the second N also shrinks at each step, giving us a speed-up constant. Because the graph is complete, we have many more E than V. By bounding ourselves by V instead of E, we are squared, but still in practice much faster. In theory you can run Prim here by generating the adjacency list graph upfront, then using a min_heap you insert each unvisited neighbor into after visting a vertex (just BFS), but I think that basically hurts us as much as kruskal because that constant in V^2 is much larger.\n\n— alt —\n\nGenerate MST using Kruskal's algorithm. For each unique pair of vertices, generate the manhatten distance. Insert these into a min_heap. Next implement union find. Count cost and num_edges. While num_edges < (num_points - 1), pop the next element from heap. Try to join the two verts. If they were already in the same component, skip. Else inc num_edges, add edge weight to cost. When finished return cost.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(V^2) to generate edge weights. O(E*log(E)) to run kruskal. Space O(n^2) to store edges.\n\nNotes: Kruskal performs worse here because its bounded by edges. Kruskal is better on sparese graphs but here, each vertex is theoretically connected to each other vertex not yet in the tree. By calculating edges costs upfront we do much more work than we would by delaying it until the last point, which excludes all the vertices already in the tree. Prim does this, and so it performs better.", "order": 98 }, { "cat": "Advanced Graphs", "num": 743, "name": "Network Delay Time", "risk": "High", "back": "Use Dijsktra kinda, BFS with prio queue. We dont need to compute the full shortest path array, only keep track of the longest path we encounter during traversal. Build the graph out of our edge list. Keep a min_heap that stores next_node and cost_sofar, sorted by cost_sofar. Start heap with {k, 0}. Then while heap is not empty, pop off the heap. If visited cur, continue. Else add cur to visited. Update max_path if cost_sofar is larger. Now iterate each neighbor of cur. Skip it if visited. Else add {next.to, cost_sofar + next.cost} to min_heap. At the end return max_path if size(visited) == n, else -1 (we couldnt visited every node).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(V + E*log(E)) Space: O(V+E)\n\nNotes: We can early return if visited.size() == n. We basically bfs outwards trying to visit every node, always greedily exploring the next shortest path. This works because we use the path cost so far to sort heap, not just edge cost. So if we have two possible paths to a node, and one starts shorter but gets longer than the other over time, we'll eventually get the shorter path at front of the queue first and it will cause us to explore node before the longer path brings us to node.", "order": 99 }, { "cat": "Advanced Graphs", "num": 778, "name": "Swim in Rising Water", "risk": "High", "back": "Use a greedy bfs to search for the best path. Use a min_heap store (x,y,height). Start with (0,0,height[0]). While q has elements. Pop q, update max_height with height. If x,y is bottom right, return max_height. Else check if we've already visited x,y, if yes skip. Else set visited x,y true, then step in all four directions. Check bounds are safe, then check if we've already visited. If all good, push n_x,n_y,n_height into queue. At the end if we run out nodes return 0, cause we didnt find bottom right.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(mn*log(mn)) Space: O(mn)\n\nNotes: A variation is to encode max(height, next_height) into q, which basically records what was the max height we found along this path, but I like my version better. This basically greedily explores forward until we find bottom right. At each step the min_heap leads us towards the cell with the lowest height. If we later find a different path, and it has a bigger height, we still would've needed the old height anyways. We cant accidentally explore a path with bigger height because we wouldnt have chose it out of min_heap unless it was the smallest at any point that we needed to get to bottom right.  Time comes from \"nodes\" is grid size m*n, at worst we explore all, at each step we do at worst 4 min_heap pushes, 4*log(mn) (at worst all nodes in queue), drop the constant. Space for at worst all nodes in queue.", "order": 100 }, { "cat": "Advanced Graphs", "num": 269, "name": "Alien Dictionary", "risk": "High", "back": "The sorted word list can be used to extract directed edge info about the sorting, from which we can build a graph. Then topological sort that graph, all nodes we have order info for will be output in that order, all other letters will go in any order, which we're allowed to. We first add an entry to our graph for every letter we have, to make sure its included later. Now we check every word pair i,i+1. Get the min_len between them, then scan through in lockstep. If we find a differing letter, we know that letter i comes before i+1, so we have an edge, add it to the graph and break. After the loop we check if we did a full scan of min_len and if word i is larger than i+1. If yes, we just return empty because according to the problem description its an invalid case. The only other invalid case is found by the topo sort, which will identify if we have a back edge. If there is a cycle, we cant create an ordering. We get all letter in the output because we run dfs on every entry in the graph (we inserted all unique letters at the start). For letters we have no order info on, topo sort just inserts them, any position for them is valid. For other letters that have edges, topo sort runs and outputs them in the correct order (technically reversed until we reverse the order at the end before returning result).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|words|*avg_word_len) to build, O(num_letters+(25)) traversal. Space: O(num_letters + 25)\n\nNotes: Traversal time is num_letters plus constant because at worst we ever have a fully sorted alphabet, which has n - 1 edges, with 26 english letters thats 25.", "order": 101 }, { "cat": "Advanced Graphs", "num": 787, "name": "Cheapest Flights Within K Stops", "risk": "High", "back": "Find shortest path using a slightly modified Dijkstra. Implement dijsktra like normal. Build graph out of edges. Keep cost_so_far array init to MAX. But also keep path_so_far array init to MAX. Now start with (src, 0, 0), which are cur node, cur_cost, cur_path. Pop the node. If cur is dst, return cur_cost. If cur_path is k + 1, we havent found dst but our path is as long as it can be, so just return (abandon path). Else iterate neighbors, normal dijkstra check if shorter path, add if yes, update cost_so_far with cur_cost + neighbor.cost and path_so_far with cur_path + 1. Add an extra else clause to neighbor check checking if cur_path is shorter than path_so_far. If yes, reinsert neigbor with next_cost and cur_path + 1 into queue, but dont update the so_far arrays. This makes us consider new shorter paths later if the current cheaper ones dont fulfil k (but doesnt choose them right away, since we dont update so_far). If while doesnt return, no valid path, return -1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(V + E*log(E)) Space: O(V+E)", "order": 102 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 70, "name": "Climbing Stairs", "risk": "Low", "back": "Recursion + caching, too slow without caching. At each step, we have a choice to make, we either choose step 1 or 2. Which one we pick depends on which has the minimal path after it. This we can solve recursively, with the base case being that we hit one of the last two steps. So, recursive methods checks if cur is in range of last two elements. If yes, return cost[cur]. Also check if our memo array has a value (if not its inited to -1). If it does, just return that. Else, we need to calculate if taking 1 or 2 steps has a smaller cost, so recurse for both and take the min. Then add cost[cur] to this, this is how much our path cost is right now. Write it into memo[cur] and return it. Because we technically start \"outside\" of the array at -1, our main function calls climb(1) and climb(2) and returns the min (since we have no cur cost at the start). Memo is inited to cost.size() and -1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Time complexity without cache is O(2^n). With cache O(n), because we prune all duplicate results fromt the tree. So there are only n unique possible steps. Good solution description, read it later.\n\n— alt —\n\nAnother way to think about the idea of always choosing the min path from 1 or 2 two steps ahead is that we can compute what we do with recursion iteratively. We can iterate forwards over cost, since we depend on the result to the right, but we can do it by iterating backwards. First we push an extra INT_MA element to the end of the cost. This accounts for when we only have two elements, so we dont step out of bounds since we \"start outside the array\". Now iterate backwards over cost, starting at cost.len() - 3, since that is the first element that is not a step to the final level. At each i, we add min(cost[i + 1], cost[i + 2]) to cost[i], building up the min cost right to left. Now we can just return min(cost[0],[1]), which are the two paths taking either 1 or 2 steps at the start.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: This solution does modify cost, so we have to be allowed to do so. Otherwise we need to copy it, returning Space to O(n).", "order": 103 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 746, "name": "Min Cost Climbing Stairs", "risk": "Low", "back": "Add up along the path and always pick the min. Recurse by passing in cur steps and cost array. We start with cur = -1 because we count up. If cur >= (cost.size() - 2) return 0, base case. -2 because either we are at the end (past - 2) or 2 away, either way our last step. Else check the cache for cur and return if found. Else, get the min between recur(cur + 1) + cost[cur + 1] and recur(cur + 2) + cost[cur + 2]. Basically we start outside the array and let the first call take care of the branching, branching both ways afterwards each time. Add min to cache, return min.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Solution that counts the other direction (n->1) reads a little more elegant. Good solution description, read it later.", "order": 104 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 198, "name": "House Robber", "risk": "Med", "back": "We have a choice to make at the start. We can either rob house 0 and then include everything at house 2 and onwards. Or we can start at house 1 instead, which does not include 0. Now for the value of house 1, we can solve it the exact same way. Start at 1, include everything from 3 onwards, or start at house 2. This is where we can recursively break it down, always selecting the max each path gives us. So for implementation: Recurse start at 0. Return 0 if cur >= nums.len. Then select the max value between nums[cur] + recurse(cur + 2) or recurse(cur + 1). Return the max value. Would be O(2^n), to speed up use a cache as always.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Important to remember: While could choose to make a jump forward larger than 2 at each step, it makes no sense to do so, because we can always get to the same element by including previous elements along the way, always giving is a larger result than if we jumped forward directly to the big element. This deals with cases like [2,1,1,2] (result is 4) because we step [0] -> [2] and then from two we choose to either rob 1 + rob(i + 2), which is 1 + 0 or rob[i + 1], which looks only at two and so selects. So we figure that from [2], the best choice is actually to rob [3], which gives us 2 money.\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can also solve this iteratively, by only looking at the last two results, rob1 and rob2. Rob2 holds our last max, Rob1 holds the max before that. Rob1 comes before Rob2 in order. So, following the logic from the recursive approach, we can either select rob1 + cur (because rob2 sits between them), or rob2 (which cant include cur since they are right next to each other). So, at each step we select the max between rob1 + cur and rob2. then we move rob2 into rob1, and now rob2 becomes our max. On the next step, rob2 can hold previous rob1 + cur. The next cur cant be included in that sum since it is next to prev cur, but that works as we only consider rob2. Our rob1 will be atleast one step removed from cur. Rob2 can also hold our previous rob2, which would be atleast 1 step removed as well. At the end, rob2 holds the max sum, return it.\n\nAnother way to think about it: Rob2 holds our last max we select for the current step, Rob1 holds the previous Rob2. At each step we select whether its better to choose current rob2, or rob1 + cur. This allows us to skip a house if its more optimal to do so because a previous adjacent house was better value. So Rob1 always holds a sum atleast one over from the current value. Rob2 holds either the sum from the last adjacent house, or if it was better one from more houses back. Rob1 and Rob2 basically hold the best sums in the previous sub array, which can either be the i-1 house value plus the best sum from the i-2 sub array and in rob1 the best sum from the prev i-2 sub array. Or they can both hold the best sum from the prev i-2 sub array.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Examples:     \n     [2,7,9,3,1] (rob1 and rob2 are the values they have after we consider the previous values with i)\n     s->  rob1 0  rob2 0\n     2 -> rob1 0  rob2 2\n     7 -> rob1 2  rob2 7\n     9 -> rob1 7  rob2 11\n     3 -> rob1 11 rob2 11\n     1 -> rob1 11 rob2 12\n    \n     [2,1,1,2]\n     s -> rob1 0  rob2 0\n     2 -> rob1 0  rob2 2\n     1 -> rob1 2  rob2 2\n     1 -> rob1 2  rob2 3\n     2 -> rob1 3  rob2 4", "order": 105 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 213, "name": "House Robber II", "risk": "Med", "back": "The only modification to the problem is that if we rob the first house, we cannot rob the last house. Essentially, that splits our problem into two tours, house robber from 0 to n - 2 and house robber from 1 to n - 1. We can just reuse house robber 1 encapsulated into a helper that takes a to and from. Just return the max between rob(0, n-2) and rob(1, n-1). Only special case to handle is when the array has one element.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(2n) Space: O(1)", "order": 106 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 5, "name": "Longest Palindromic Substring", "risk": "High", "back": "Weird definition of DP. The naive approach would be to iterate each start/end pair in the string do O(n) check if its a palindrome. That would be O(n^3). We can do better: Iterate each letter in s, then expand outwards left and right from i, checking if it stays a palindrome. This we can do in O(n^2) since for each letter we consider at worst each other letter once. We keep track of the max len so far and the associated l and r. Then for each i, we set l = i, r = i. While these are in bounds and s[l] == s[r], we check if (r - l + 1) > maxLen. If yes, replace max_len, max_l and max_r. Then move l left and r right. This finds odd length palindromes spreading out from a single letter. But it misses even length ones, where the center is two letters. We solve this by doing second scan with l still = i, but r = i + 1. Now we do the same spreading out loop. At the end, return s.substr(max_l, max_len).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^2) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: At first, doing two scan loops for each character sounds expensive, but consider that you will never run both loops for a character further than one step. If the odd or even loop runs more than one step, the other cannot. My last submission for this is very nicely written.", "order": 107 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 647, "name": "Palindromic Substrings", "risk": "Med", "back": "Pretty much exactly like \"Longest Palindromic Substring\", loop over each letter, check even and odd palindromes for each letter expanding outwards. Now, inside the expand loops, instead of checking maxLen, just increment palindrome_count on each iteration. Return count at the end.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^2) Space: O(1)", "order": 108 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 91, "name": "Decode Ways", "risk": "High", "back": "Can be solved recursively by traversing the decision tree. At each digit, we have two choices. If the digit is not '0', then we can take that one digit. Second, if its '1' and the digit after is in '0'-'9' or its '2' and the digit after is in '0'-'6', we can take two digits. We start recursion at cur=0. Each call checks if we hit base case which is cur >= s.size(). If so, return 1, we found one valid way to decode. Otherwise we need to make a decision. Count the number if ways, initially 0. If s[cur] == '0' we have no valid path, just return ways. Else, recurse with cur + 1 and add to ways. Then check our two digit conditions and if valid, recurse with cur+2 and add to ways. To speed this up, we use a cache array of size s.size() inited to -1. We return ways from cache if its cached, otherwise we add ways to cache after computing it through recursion.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Without cache this would be O(2^n), since we have two branches over n choices.\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can also do this iteratively. We init a dp array of size s.size() + 1 and init the last element to 1. The last element is what we grab to initialize the first actual entries in dp. We then iterate backwards through s. If s[i] == 0, set dp[i] to 0, as there is no solution through this element via single element. Otherwise, we set dp[i] to dp[i + 1], we can continue the number of previous paths through this one. Then if we are in bounds, and the two digits conditions described above are true, we add dp[i + 2] to dp[i], because we also continue a two step through this element. At the end return dp[0].\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Consider dp[s.size() - 1]. If its any non zero, we set to one, grabbed from the extra element we added to dp. If its zero, we set it to zero since we cant end there on a single step. Then, from dp[s.size() - 2], we might be able to make a two step with the '0' at the end, in which case we again grab the one element off the end of the array. If we had a non-zero in s.size() - 1, s.size() - 2 gets both that one value and the one of the array end, because there two ways through end (one step and two step).\nCan also be done in O(1) space. Keep vars ways1 init to 1 and ways2 init to 0. Each step keep local var ways. If single condition, set ways to ways1. If double condition, add ways2 to ways. Then set ways2 to ways1, ways1 to ways. At the end return ways1.", "order": 109 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 322, "name": "Coin Change", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can solve this top down with recursion. We try each kind of coin, then for that we try each type of coin again and so on. The base case is when we used enough coins to make amount or more. Doing this brute-force would be at worst n(coins)^A(mount). So we need to speed it up with a cache. We do this by caching for each remaining amount, what is the min amount of coins we can use to make up the rest of amount. So, our recursion takes coins, amount and memo. If amount < 0, return -1 (or some null type) to represnt that this was not a valid path. Else 0 to denote a valid path. Otherwise, if the cache has a non-0 value, return that. If not, we're going iterate through each coin and recurse with (amount - coin). If the result is > 0 and smaller than any other result from this iteration, save it to minResult. After loop, minResult either contains the minimal amount of coins we need to finish this path, or nothing if there was no valid way. If minResult is not valid, save -1 to memo. Else save minResult. Return memo[amount].\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*A) Space: O(A)\n\nNotes: Time is amount * coins. Thanks to chaching we compute at most A unqiue subproblems (how many remainders we can have), and each subproblem takes coin number of steps to compute.\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can also solve it bottom up iteratively. Init a dp array of size[amount + 1] with initial value amount + 1. dp[i] stores the min number coins it takes to get to i. Set dp[0] 0. Then we iterate through 0 -> amount inclusive. At each step, we iterate each coin. If i - coin >= 0, this is a valid path. Now we check if this path is better, by assigining to dp[i] the min between dp[i] and dp[i - coin] + 1. dp[i] if another coin this step created a shorter path. dp[i - coin] because thats how many steps it took to complete the path from the remainder we would get to if we subtracted the current coin from amount. If from that smaller remainder we had no solution, its value will be amount + 1, so the min will not select it if we already have a valid solution. At the end we have the min path solution in dp[amount], return it.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * A) Space: O(A)\n\nNotes: The amount + 1 is a symbolic value that says \"no result here\" and is bigger than any result we would get so it never gets selected during min(). We could try to use INT_MAX but that overflows when we add 1 to it in the loop.", "order": 110 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 152, "name": "Maximum Product Subarray", "risk": "Med", "back": "Can be solved iteratively. We need to keep track of three things: the max product seen so far, the current max conitgous product and the current min contiguous product, inited to INT_MIN, 1 and 1. We basically keep track of the minimum and maximum sub-array product prior to the current element at each step. Now step through each number and calc maxProduct = curMax * i and minProduct = curMin * i. These are the smallest and larget contigous products we can achive. Then we select curMax from (maxProduct, minProduct and i). maxProduct will only be largest if have a contigous series of positive products. minProduct will be largest if we have adjacent negative products that multiple to a large positive number. i will be largest if we just had a negative product that made the max negative, but i is positive. we keep curMax obviously for contigious increasing products. curMin keeps track of negative numbers which can become large if multiplied with another negative. After, we set result = max(result, curMax).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Because we multiply everything up contigously, we cant accidentally select non-contigous products since any negative numbers inbetween will be mixed into curMax (curMax never gets set from previous curMax alone). If we we have only contigous positive numbers, even if they decrease in size, they still increase the product.\nZeros are handled by us selecting the i as part of min and max, it basically resets our curMin and curMax after a 0 gets mixed in.", "order": 111 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 139, "name": "Word Break", "risk": "High", "back": "We can solve this bruteforce similar to coin change with recursion. We start at position 0. From this position, we iterate each word in dict. We check starting from cur position, if s contains the word. If no, skip this word. If yes, we can split that word off from s. If so, recurse with pos = cur + len(word). Finally if we hit cur pos == s.size(), we know we found an exact split and can return true. If we went over return false. In the word loop, return true if the recursive call returned true. By itself, this would take exponential time, we can speed this up with memoization. For each cur pos, we need to remember if we havent checked the split yet, or if we succeded or failed in splitting the string from cur. We can keep an array of enum {None, True, False} of size |s|, inited to none. When we enter the recurse, we can check if memo[cur] != None and return the value. Else we set memo[cur] false if we found no split and return false in the end. Or if a recursive call found a split, set memo[cur] true before returning.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^3) Space: O(len|s|)\n\nNotes: brute force time complexity: O(words^(len(s) / |min(word)|) * avg(|word|)).\n\nmemo: time complexity: you'll try at each split atleast every string once before memo starts kicking in (O(n^2)), and each string check takes time linear in |len| (O(n)) -> O(n^3)\n\nSplit check can be done with substr operation or manual lockstep loop.\n\nWe actually dont need to set true values in the cache at all, since we return on first success anyways. We just need to remember if we havent check or failed. So we could probably turn this into a map<int> and just insert cur on failure and save some space.\n\n— alt —\n\nCan also solve this bottom up iteratively. We keep a dp array size |len| + 1 and set dp[|len|] true. This is the value we lookup if manage to split the string up until the end. Then we iterate backwards through the string s. For each char, we iterate each word in dict. If |word| is bigger then we have space from i to end, skip. Else check if we can find word from i onwards in s. We can use string::find, but we have to provide and offset and make sure the result matches i (it starts at our offset). If found, we set dp[i] to dp[i + |word|]. This is because this word is only a valid split if the position we end the split at also had a valid split before hand (this bubbles our result up to the start). If dp[i] is now true, we can break, we have a found a valid split for this position, we dont need to find more. At the end if there is a complete split, dp[0] will be true.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * m * n) Space: O(|s|)\n\nNotes: We dont need to search the other words once we have a match for a position because we're only updating this i. It doesnt matter if there is another long or shorter string that matched, since this string will only match if there is already a viable break before hand. Even if we have different length matches, we're iterating through every position in is, and by doing so we'll find those other length matches too. Also if there other, longer strings that can split we'll find those a few i further back. If there were shorter strings that split, we already found them at that point. Basically, the dp doesnt store which string it was that split, just that at position i, there was a string of the right length that split up until a position i + len that also had a valid split.", "order": 112 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 300, "name": "Longest Increasing Subsequence", "risk": "Med", "back": "Break the problem down into subproblems. The longest increasing subsequence for an element is its length + the longest subsequence before that it extends. It extends it if the element the previous sequence ends in is smaller than the extending element. So we can figure out e.g. seqLen[3] if we know seqLen[0], [1], and [2]. We can pick the longest out of these sequences where nums[i] has a value smaller then nums[3]. Our base case is that each element starts with seqLen 1, since each el forms its own sequence. So we make dp array inited with 1. Now we can iterate through each element in the array. For that element, iterate each element from 0 before it. Check if that element's num is smaller than i's num. If yes, we set dp[i] to max(dp[i], dp[j] + 1), since we'll either want to keep our longer sequence if we already have one, or extend the other sequence by one with i if its longer than / equal to our current seq. Once finished, we can return the max_el in dp (or keep track of it during iteration).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^2) Space: O(n)\n\n— alt —\n\n300. Longest Increasing Subsequence\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*log(n)) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: See this", "order": 113 }, { "cat": "1D Dynamic Programming", "num": 416, "name": "Partition Equal Subset Sum", "risk": "High", "back": "Solve with top down DP. To get an even partition, we need to find a subset that adds up to half the total sum of the array. We can calculate the total sum and divide by 2 to get our target. If the total sum is odd, there is no solution. Else we can backtrack, taking the cur element, target and total sum we need. If sum > target return false, not a valid answer. If sum == target return true, we found an answer. By itself this will be 2^n, too slow, so we need a cache. The cache will record if we went down a path and already failed (we bail on the first success). The cache is 2D, indexed by [cur][sum]. If cache is true, just return false, we already tried. Else iterate each element from cur, try backtracking with it added to sum. If any backtrack returns true, return true. Else if we found nothing set memo[cur][sum] true and return false.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m * n) Space: O(m * n)\n\nNotes: Time is because there are m (1->targetSum) * n (nums) possible calls to to backtrack that are unique. All other ones will hit the cache.\n\n— alt —\n\nCan solve it bottom up too. Same as above on needing to reach sum/2. What's our problem? Can we add up to target sum using the elements in our array? How can we break it apart? We can answer individually if parts of our target sum can be added up to each. If two parts can be added up to, then the whole part can be added up to. But we need to take care to only use each element as many times as we have it. We can cache our subproblems in array dp, where dp is size target + 1. dp[i] records if i can so far be added up to with the elements in our array. We set dp[0] true, base case we can always reach. Now we iterate through our nums. For each num we iterate downward from target up to and including num. At each x, we set dp[x] = dp[x] || dp[x - num] (could we already reach this or can we reach it now if we use num to get there). dp[target] holds the answer at the end.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m * n) Space: O(m)\n\nNotes: Why do we iterate backwards? If we iterated from num to target, elements would be self perpetuating. Consider target is 500 and we have one 100 in our array. If we iterate 100 -> 500 dp[100], dp[200], dp[300] etc. would become true, even though we only have one 100. If we iterate backward and we e.g. have two 100s, the first one will iterate down and set dp[100] true since it'll reach x=100 and x-100=0 dp[0] is true. The next 100 when going downwards will see dp[100] when it reaches dp[200] and set dp[200] true. That way we can only dp[500] if we have five 100s.", "order": 114 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 62, "name": "Unique Paths", "risk": "Med", "back": "Using DFS count the number of ways to reach the end. Dfs takes r,c and target tr, tc. If r,c == tr,tc return 1. Else check if r,c is in cache, if so return cached value. Else set r,c visited. If in bounds and not visited, dfs into r+1,c, add up the number of ways returned. dfs into r,c+1, add up the number of ways returned. Unset visited r,c. Update the cache, return ways. Caches are 2D size of m * n.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n) Space: O(m*n)\n\n— alt —\n\nCan also be solved iteratively by breaking it down into its subproblems. How many ways can we reach cell[m][n]? In as many ways as we can reach the cells that we can reach it from, so cell[m - 1][n] and cell[m][n - 1]. We can do that recursively over the whole array. We still make a 2D array size m,n, init each field to 1 (initially each cell can be reached 1 way). Now iterate over m and n, starting at 1. We start at one because each border cell can only be reached one way since we cant step left or back. Now we set each cell dp[r][c] to dp[r-1][c] + dp[r][c-1]. This will terminate at dp[m - 1][n - 1] which contains all the ways to reach the bottom right cell.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n) Space: O(m*n)\n\nNotes: We could make this a 1D problem if we were motivated enough to do the index mapping math.", "order": 115 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 1143, "name": "Longest Common Subsequence", "risk": "Med", "back": "Solve as a special case of edit distance. We're interested in the position [i,j] in t1 and t2 that has the most common characters. How can decide what the LCS at a position is? If the characters at t1[i] and t2[j] match, then it is the LCS at our previous match + 1. Otherwise it just the LCS so far of t1 or t2. We can compute this with a 2D table of size |t1|*|t2|, where dp[i][j] represents the LCS at the positions i and j. We init the table with 0, then we do a nested loop over |t1| and |t2|. At i,j whether there is a match or not, the LCS will the bigger LCS between the one at the same pos in t1 but the prev pos in t2 (dp[i][j - 1]) or at the same pos in t2 but the prev pos in t1 (dp[i - 1][j]). If the characters at i,j match, then we can also extend the previous biggest LCS by 1. So in this case dp[i][j] becomes max(dp[i][j], dp[i - 1]dp[j - 1]). We might already have a bigger LCS from a previous position. See notes why it has to be i-1,j-1. At the end the max result propagates to the bottom right cell in DP. Or we can keep track of max LCS during iteration.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n) Space: O(m*n)\n\nNotes: Care must be taken when i or j is 0, because we cant reach back (we'll voilate the bounds), but we do need to correctly init the border row and column. For this, if we overstep i or j, we just select 0 for that value instead.\n\nWhy do we use i-1,j-1 when we have a match? Because if we allow to select from the same row or col, we would pollute the result with previous matches in the row and would count a character potentially multiple times. Only the i-1,j-1 will be unaffected by double matches.\n\nThis problem has a good solution explenation on LC.", "order": 116 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 309, "name": "Best Time to Buy and Sell Stock with Cooldown", "risk": "High", "back": "We can think about this in terms of a decision tree. At each day, we can choose to have a cooldown day and do nothing. Or, if we have previously bought something, we can choose to sell. If we have not bought anything yet, then our choice is to buy instead. We can implement this decision tree recursively. By itself this would be O(2^n) because we have 2 choices over n values. But we can add a cache to speed this up to O(n). Our recursive method has to take two args: the day and if we're buying or selling. So the cache is keyed on the day, but stores two values: the max when we sell on that day and the max when we buy on that day. So recurse starting with 0 and buy. Each step, if day >= |prices|, return 0, this is the base case. Else if buying, check the cache and return if we have a value. Otherwise compute the value of buying as buy(i+1, sell) - prices[i] (because the profit will be less what we spend today). The other option is cooldown, which is just buy(i+1, buy). If we're selling compute the profit as buy(i + 2, buy) + prices[i]. + prices[i] because the profit will be plus what we gain today. i + 2 because we're forced to skip i + 1 on cooldown. Also compute cooldown(i +1, sell). Select the max from either option, add it to cache, return it.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(2*n)\n\nNotes: I implemented the cache as vector<pair<option<int>,option<int>>. Pair for the buy/sell combo, option so we can tell if the cache has a value yet.\n\nThe buy/sell arguments are a bool flag that gets flipped when buying or selling or stays the same when choosing cooldown.", "order": 117 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 518, "name": "Coin Change 2", "risk": "High", "back": "One way to solve this is exactly like \"Combination Sum\" but with a 2D cache. Recurse with an amount and index, And every step try each coin from current index included until the last coin. Because we pass the current index we can reuse elements, but because we dont start from the beginning of coins we generate unique combinations. The cache is indexed by [amount][i].\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n)\nSpace: O(m*n)\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can also solve it like \"Coin Change\", but we look for the total number of ways rather than min. Init a dp array[amount + 1]. Set dp[0] to 1. Iterate each coin, then iterate from coin to amount + 1. Set dp[i] += dp[i - coin]. Return dp[amount].\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: In our [1,2,5] & 5 example: For 1, each dp becomes 1 since there is one way to get there. For 2 dp[2] becomes 2 (1,1 or 2). dp[4] becomes 3 (1,1,1,1 or 1,1,2 or 2,2). etc.. It stacks up the number of ways, but we explore linerearly so no duplicate branches.", "order": 118 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 494, "name": "Target Sum", "risk": "High", "back": "Can be implemented with recursion and caching. At each step in the decision tree we have two choices: we can add +nums[i] to the sum or -nums[i]. Dfs for element i and current sum, both initially 0. If i >= nums.size(), return 1 if sum is target, else 0 (sum over- or under-shot target and we ran out of elements to add). Our cache is 2D and maps i -> sum -> #ways. Check if we have a cache value, if yes return it. Else calc ways, which is dfs(i + 1, sum + nums[i]) + dfs(i + 1, sum - nums[i]). Add ways to cache, return ways.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(target * sum(nums)) Space: O(target * sum(nums))\n\nNotes: Complexity involves sum(nums) because we dont stop when we under or overshoot target, because the path can still be valid. Instead we explore for all possible values of sum, which can be +/- the sum of the values in nums. \n\nThe cache is really annoying to implement in C++ because we cant hash combine through the standard. I did vector of maps.", "order": 119 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 97, "name": "Interleaving String", "risk": "High", "back": "We can solve this top down. To reach a valid solution, we need to have consumed all characters of both strings (s1 and s2) without changing their relative order, and built the third string (s3) correctly. We can run through the decision tree starting at the beginning pos p1, p2 and p3 of s1, s2 and s3. At each step we we can check if we reached the end of all strings, if so return true. Otherwise, if s1[p1] == s3[p3], we can choose to put this char into the interleaving and recurse with p1 + 1. If s2[p2] == s3[p3] we can also choose this char instead and recurse with p2 + 1. We need to try both option if valid since either could produce a valid interleaving. If either recursion returns true, return true, we're done. Else return false. By itself this would take O(2^(|s1| + |s2|)) time. But we'll be computing a lot of duplicate failed paths along the way, and we can cache those. We use a 2D bool array indexed with p1 and p2. If the cache value is false, we havent tried this path yet. If its true, the path is not valid and we can skip checking it. We check the cache before recursing and update it after recursing.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|s1| * |s2|) Space: O(|s1| * |s2|)\n\nNotes: We can use a bool flag for the cache because we dont need to store if a path was valid, only if it was unchecked (grey) or invalid (black). If we find a valid path we immediately return.\n\nThere are also 1D and 2D DP solutions, see on LC solution.\n\n— alt —\n\nWith tabulation. Build a table size |s1| + 1 * |s2| + 1. 0,0 is default true. The first column i,0 notes if s1[i] matches s3[i]. First row 0,j notes if s2[j] matches s3[j]. Every cell i,j in table tells us if either s1[i] or s2[j] matches s3[i + j] (because we have to include both i and j chars to get to each). This is basically our two choices in the top down approach. If either matches we then also have to check if there is a match in the previous step, which can either be s1[i - 1] or s2[j - 1]. We still have to include the same number of characters from the other string, so these values are found at either table[i - 1][j] or table[i][j - 1]. At the end table[|s1|][|s2|] denotes if we can interleave all chars in s1 and s2 to build s3.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|s1| * |s2|) Space: O(|s1| * |s2|)", "order": 120 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 329, "name": "Longest Increasing Path in a Matrix", "risk": "High", "back": "We can solve this with DFS. We iterate each cell and run DFS for it. Dfs runs for a cell r,c.  If the new cell nr,nc is out of bounds, skip. If the value in nr,nc is larger then r,c we dfs. For each neighbor dfs we check if the result is the largest we've seen and keep it if yes. Afterwards we return the largest neighbor path (0 if none) + 1. The +1 because this cell adds one to the path, and the dfs returns us the longest path from that cell. By itself this is slow because we have a very densly connected graph, brute force would be roughly O(n*m * 4^(n*m)). So we use a cache to store the longest path from a cell, mapping from r,c. At the start of the DFS we check if the cache has a value (!= -1) and return it if yes. Otherwise we write the result (1 + maxNeighborPath) into the cache before returning. With this we only visit every n*m cell once.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*m) Space: O(n*m)\n\nNotes: There is no base case because we want to potentially explore the whole grid. For each cell, we check the four neigbhors.\n\nWe dont need a visited array because we will never revisit the same cell twice. We only follow paths that increase in value, so its impossible to renter a previous cell that would have a lower value.", "order": 121 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 115, "name": "Distinct Subsequences", "risk": "High", "back": "We can solve this top down, by basically sliding s over each letter in t and checking if we find a subsequence. We can do this by testing every combination s,t and seeing if we find t before we run over s. This can be implemented recursively, taking i,j -> idces into s,t. If j == |t|, we found a subsequence (explained why in a second), return 1. Else if i == |s|, we ran out before matching t, invalid so return 0. Now we have two choices: If s[i] == t[j], we can try two paths. We can choose to skip matching this letter, where we call recurse(s + 1, j). Or we can match this letter, and so we call recurse(s + 1, j + 1). The combined result is the number of seq from this path. If s[i], t[j] dont match, then we can only choose to skip and we call (s + 1, j) and take the result. Return result at the end. By itself, this is O(2^max(|s|,|t|). So we need to speed it up with a cache. We can add a 2D cache mapping from (i,j) to #ways, the cache is checked before recursing and updated afterwards.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*m) Space: O(n*m)\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can translate the recursion into tabulation, represented by a table of size |s + 1|* |t + 1|. The +1 gives space for our base cases. So our rows index s, our columns index t. We init the bottom row to 0, this is our base case where we ran out of values in s and did not match t. Then we init the last column to 1, this is our base case where did manage to match t from s. Now we build our table bottom up. We have to calculate dp[i,j] before we can calculate dp[i-1][j-1], [i-1][j] or [i][j-1] as those earlier calls are dependent on the later result (we have a subsequence if letter j matches and the string beforehand was a valid subseq too). So we start at [|s|][|t|] and iterate backwards. We grab our non-match case same as the recursion from dp[i+1][j] and set dp[i][j] to it (just like the recursion). If s[i] == t[j], just like the recursion, we have an extra case where we add dp[i + 1][j + 1] also to dp[i][j]. Repeat this for the whole table. The final result will be in dp[0][0].\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*m) Space: O(n*m)\n\nNotes: Amazing explanation on LC", "order": 122 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 72, "name": "Edit Distance", "risk": "High", "back": "We need to calculate what the cheapest path from word1 to word2 is. We can define it like this: We keep pointers p1 and p2 into our words. At each step, we can match the two letter if they are the same, or we can substite the one in w1 to match the on w2. Alternatively, we can remove a letter from w1, or add a letter to it. If we match/substite we make progress on both words so we advance p1 and p2. If we insert, we need an extra letter in w1 and so we only advance p2. If we delete, we need to remove a letter from w1, we only advance p1 because we havent made progress towards w2. Now we just to define what the \"distance\" is. Arbitrarily, we say substituing, inserting or deleting costs \"1\". Matching is free since we dont need to do anything, so we pay 0. \nThis can now be implemented recursively. Our base case is we have run out of letters in p1 or p2, in that case we pay 1 for insert/delete * the number of letters left in the other. Otherwise we try the match path, so we recurse with i-1,j-1 and add the cost of matching at w1[p1 - 1],w2[p2 - 1] (-1 because we start the method with size of our strings). Then we try inserting, we recurse with i,j-1 and add the cost of insert(w2[j-1]). Finally we try deleting, so we recurse with i-1,j and add the cost delete(w1[i - 1]). Then we return the min of the three. By itself, this runs in O(3^max(|w1|,|w2|), so we need a cache to speed it up. We can have a 2D cache indexed with i,j storing the min result.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*m) Space: O(n*m)\n\nNotes: Edit Distance / Levenshtein Distance.\n\nThis is still very slow with caching due to wasted checks / function call overhead.\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can implement the same thing tabulation. Make a table |w1 + 1,||w2 + 1|. Rows are w1, cols are w2. Our base case like before is that we need to insert/delete the remaining characters. So we init dp[0][0] to 0, then we iterate for |w1| through the first column and set the cell to i (i is how many letters we would need to delete from the word). We do the same for |w2| and the first row (i ==  how many to insert). Now we iterate over dp, starting at 1,1. Like in recursion, we get the cost for match,insert and delete from dp[i - 1][j - 1], dp[i - 1][ j ] and dp[ i ][j - 1]. If match is the min, we set dp[i][j] to it. If w1[i - 1] != w2[j - 1], then we actually have to substitute and we add an extra 1 to dp[i][j]. Else we insert or delete, so we set dp[i][j] to 1 + the min between the two. At the end dp[|w1|][|w2|] contains our min edit distance.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*m) Space: O(n*m)\n\nNotes: Much faster than recursion because we actually visit every cell once and have no function call overhead.", "order": 123 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 312, "name": "Burst Balloons", "risk": "High", "back": "We could try to solve this top-down recursively, where our input state is the set of balloons we've popped so far. At each step we then loop over all balloons, try one that hasnt been popped and recurse. Even with memoization, that is still slow because our possible states are 2^n (select a balloon or not) and at each step we do at worst n work (try each unpopped balloon). To speed this up, we want to reduce our possible states for which we need to make our state smaller.\nTo do that, we change how record our state. Instead of recording all chosen balloons, we partition the array into halves where we pop. Our function takes l and r of that partition. When we select a balloon, we recurse with two new partitions: l,i-1 and i+1,r. To make out of bounds work, we append a 1 at the start and end of array. There is only one problem. When calculating the value of the current balloon, if we use i - 1 and i + 1, we dont take popping into account and so we will re-use already popped balloons. We can fix this by instead using l -1 and r + 1 as our left and right when calcualting value. What does this do? It actually flips the recursion bottom up, the first element we select on the top of the tree will be the last in recursion order. If we start our partition as the whole array, the first popped balloon will select the 1s at the borders of the array we added, which is what would happen with the last balloon. Each recursion our borders shrink in, such that there are elements between i and the borders equivalent to what the number of ballons that would have not been popped at that stage. Now each step we just try each balloon, recurse into the two partition and see if the three values added up are the max. Finally we add a cache indexed by l and r to store the max, which makes sure we only visit the N^2 (l * r) state once, where each state takes N work, giving us a complexity of N^3.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^3) Space: O(n^2)\n\nNotes: I honestly dont know how you are supposed to intuitveily come up with the border approach in the time of an interview. The only way I would have come up with this would be stare at the problem for hours.\n\nYou can translate this into tabulation by writing a 2D dp array, reading from it for the previous result and reading from nums for the \"gains\", but the iteration order was taking more mental effor to understand than I could spare. It basically used the upper right half of the matrix, started at the bottom cell offset up by the fake balloon boundaries (nums.size() - 2), and would then zig zag back up left right up left right. The final element would be in [1][nums.size() - 2]", "order": 124 }, { "cat": "2D Dynamic Programming", "num": 10, "name": "Regular Expression Matching", "risk": "High", "back": "Top down recursion. Will also use a cache to store already explored, invalid positions. We take two positions p1,p2 into p and t. If p1 >= |p| and p2 >= |t|, we managed a full match, return true. Else if only p1 >= |p|, we ran out of pattern before we found a match, return false. Then we check the cache, but only if also p2 < |t|. This can happen if we hit the end of t, but are still finishing checking a star in p. Next we check if p1 and p2 have a match, which is either if its the same char, or p has a wildcard. We also need to && that with p2 < |t|, because we might be finishing a star and so dont want to take the \"match star\" path as that would recurse forever. Now, the next char in p might be a star, so we check if p1 is in bounds to look forward and if p1 + 1 is a star. If so, we have the option to branch. We can either finish the wildcard, where we recurse with p1 + 2 (skip wildcard and star) and p2 - this is what implements the \"0\" part of star and lets us stop along the other number of checks. If we had a match, we can also use the star, where we recurse with p1 and p2 + 1. Return if either using the star or not using it is true. The \"not using star\" part is what makes wildcard+star work. With that we keep using it until we finish p2 (which breaks hasMatch), and we follow the \"dont use\" part, skipping p1 2 over the wildcard and star, finishing p1 and p2. If we dont have a star next, if we have a match we just recurse with p1 + 1 and p2 + 2 and return that. Otherwise there were no possible matches, so we set the cache for p1,p2 and return false.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|p|*|t|) Space: O(|p|*|t|)\n\nNotes: The cache needs to store both true and false values, because we can compute true subproblems but fail at the path above, despite the true subproblems being able to be re-used later.\n\nComplexity without cache. With cache.\n\nSomething I missed about why we need to do the star lookup forward rather than backward: p and t dont have to be equal, s can be a substring of t. See for example s=\"aab\" t=\"c*a*b\", which should pass. This passes because \"c*\" means use c 0 or more times, and in this case we use it 0 times.\n\n— alt —\n\nThe recursion can be directly translated into bottom up tabulation. We make table |p|+1,|t|+1, all false. We set dp[|p|][|t|] true, bottom case where we run out on both strings. Then we iterat over i |s| -> 0 and j |p| - 1 -> 0. We start i at full |s| because we also want to run through the last row, where dp's offset by j-2 will take the true value, these are the cases where we finish a wildcard+star at the end by stepping the pattern forward 2. Inside the loop, we check isMatch as (i < |s|) && (s[i] == p[j] || p[j] == '.'), just like recursion. Then if j + 1 is in range to look forward and j + 1 == *, we do the star path. dp[i][j] becomes dp[i][j + 2] (dont use star) || isMatch && dp[i + 1][j] (use star). If the next char is not *, dp[i][j] instead becomes isMatch && dp[i + 1][j + 1] - these paths are just like the recursion. At the end the result is in dp[0][0], return it.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|p|*|t|) Space: O(|p|*|t|)\n\nNotes: Note to avoid confusion: I switched the order of p1/p2 p/t from the recursion to i/j t/p here.", "order": 125 }, { "cat": "Greedy", "num": 53, "name": "Maximum Subarray", "risk": "Low", "back": "Start maxSum at INT_MIN. Keep a var sum initialized to 0. Iterate though each i in nums. Compute newSum = sum + i. Set maxSum to max(maxSum, newSum). Now set sum to std::max(0, newSum). The intution is that if an element drops our below 0, the sequence included in sum currently doesnt increase our sum overall, as it has wiped any gains we had from positive elements beforehand with negative ones afterwards. So connecting that previous subarray with future ones will not give us the max. Instead we reset sum to 0 and start counting a new subarray from the next element.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 126 }, { "cat": "Greedy", "num": 55, "name": "Jump Game", "risk": "Med", "back": "Rather than searching forward and trying to find if there is a valid path, we can implement this is a backwards search. We start target as nums[len - 1], the last element. Then we iterate backwards through nums, starting at len - 2. If i + nums[i] >= target, we know we can reach that next position in the array, and we can move our target back. So we set target = i. At the end, if there was a valid path through the array, our target should be 0, as that would be the last element that can reach forward.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: We can also do this with a forward search, where if we ever hit a 0, we start a backwards search that runs until it finds a position that skip past that 0. If we find one, we set i to that and continue normally. If that backwards search goes all the way back to the start, we dont have a valid path and return 0. This is susceptible to bad input though and can have some large constant atttached to n.", "order": 127 }, { "cat": "Greedy", "num": 45, "name": "Jump Game II", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can think of this as almost like a graph search. We can start at the first element. This element reaches each other element that is within its jump distance. This gives us a new range of elements to search forward in. The minimum number of jumps is the number of windows we create until we include the last element. So e.g. if nums[0] is 2, it can reach nums[1] and nums[2], which span our next window. We represent the window using l and r counters, both starting at 0. Then while r < nums.size() - 1, we search the window. For this, we iterate i = l to <= r. We keep track which jump i + nums[i] is the biggest, this jump will gives our new biggest window. Once we have found that, we set l to r + 1 (we dont need to consider any values in the old window since we would've chosen the largest available) and r to maxJump. Then we increment numJumps. Return numJumps at the end.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 128 }, { "cat": "Greedy", "num": 134, "name": "Gas Station", "risk": "Med", "back": "We rely on the fact that this problem has a single unique solution. To solve, we break it into two things: we find the first position that we can scan through the array from that our amount of gas doesnt become negative. Then we also verify that the total amount of gas is positive, so our sum(cost) <= sum(gas). We keep three counters: start, curGas, totalGas all 0. We iterate 0 -> n. At each step we add gas[i] - cost[i] to curGas and totalGas. If curGas becomes < 0, we reset to 0 and set start to i. We're basically saying the last starting pos we tried wasnt valid, so we restart at i instead. At the end if totalGas >= 0, we return start, else -1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: The total tank part of the solution is obvious - we cannot complete a tour if the available gas doesnt cover the cost of the tour. It is not so obvious why we restart \"start\" at the station after curGas becomes negative, and why we dont have to verify the whole tour after failing. If we identify start as P, its clear that we verified P -> len(gas) is a valid tour, if it wasnt we would've reset start after P. I dont fully get this, one explanation is that if we reach negative fuel we are running a deficit before hand so this cant be solution, as we wont gather enough gas to complete the tour, but I dont fully see this. I think it helps that the array wraps around, so I think if we start at 0 and run to N we can consider this \"a full tour\"\n\n— alt —\n\nAnother way to think about this is that we want to find the point on the tour where we have the biggest fuel deficit. We want to start the tour right after this point so we have the longest possible time to gather fuel. We keep a counter start = 0, minFuel = INT_MAX and totalFuel = 0. Each step we add gas[i] - cost[i] to totalFuel. If totalFuel < minFuel, set minFuel to totalFuel and start to i. At the end, if totalFuel < 0, not enough gas on the tour, return -1. Else we want to pick the point after our minFuel, so we return (start + 1) % |gas|.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: I still dont quite get why its enough to just do a pass from 0->N and why there cant a more minimal solution that starts in the middle of the array.", "order": 129 }, { "cat": "Greedy", "num": 846, "name": "Hand of Straights", "risk": "Med", "back": "First, if |hands| % groupSize != 0, return false, because we cant evenly divide into groupSize-sized groups. The way we will build the groups is: for the number of groups we need, pick the mininmum element available to us (a new group will always start with that), then iterate throught its groupSized next elements, and decrement down elements along the way. So to count our elements, we use a hashmap card->frequency. Then we build a min-heap using our card values in the map. Now iterate 0 -> |cards| / groupSize (this is groupcount). Select the element in top of the heap startEl, the min element available to us. Then iterate 0 -> groupSize. Check if start startEl + i is in map, if not return false, we cant build a consecutive group. Check if count in map > 0, if not return false. Now decrement the count in map for el. If the count hit 0, check if this is the top el in our minheap. If yes, pop from the minheap. If not, we return false. This is because we consume the elements in sorted order, and they most be contigous. If we consume an element completely before our minElement, that means there will be a hole somewhere in our groups and we cant build k valid ones. If we made it through the loop, return true.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * log(n)) Space: O(n)", "order": 130 }, { "cat": "Greedy", "num": 1899, "name": "Merge Triplets to Form Target Triplet", "risk": "Med", "back": "Because we can only use the max operation to merge triples, we know right away that any triplet, that contains a value larger then any of the target values in its position, can be thrown away, as it would stomp one of our target values. Because we dont need to output the actual order of merging, we only need to identify if we have a set of triplets that can merged into target in some order. If we exclude all triplets that would stomp, then we only need to identify if for each value in target, we have atleast one triplet that contains that value in the same position. If so, they can be merged into target. There are multiple different ways to identify this. One is to have a bool array of size 3. We iterate through triple. We check if its disqualified, and if so, continue. Else we iterate 0 -> 3, checking if triple[i] == target[i]. If yes we set found[i] true. If found[0,1,2] are all true, return true, we find one more triplets that get us to target. If we exit the loop, return false, we did find valid triplets with all our target values.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*3) Space: O(1)", "order": 131 }, { "cat": "Greedy", "num": 763, "name": "Partition Labels", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can greedily create intervals be scanning through the string, when we first encounter a character identify the smallest partition for it, and then merge it with any existing interval it overlaps with. First create an array that for each char has its last index in s, just iterate 0 -> |s| and set lastC[c] = i. Then keep two maps first and last that map char to beginning and end of their interval. Now iterate through s. If s[i] is in first, skip. Else interval l = i, r = endC[c]. Iterate through intervals last. If i > last[other], continue, they dont overlap. Else set i = other[c], since we are merging them. If r > last[other] set last[other] = r (our new interval extends the old one). Else r = other[last] (the old interval completely surrounds the new one). Now we have a complete set of intervals in first,last for each character in s, but they are not unique. To get a unique list, we insert each pair from first,last into a set. This removes duplicates, and incidentally also sorts them. Now we can map the set to a vector of lengths and return it.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*log(n)) Space: O(26)\n\nNotes: In theory the interval merging loop is nested, but the number of intervals is bounded by 26. Also there should rarely be more than one or two merge operations per new interval.\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can build the partitions greedily left to right. First we need to know where the last occurrence of each char in s is. We iterate through s, build an array lastChar[26]. At each i, lastChar[s[i]] = i. Then we set partBegin = 0, partEnd =0, begin and end of the current partition we are building. Iterate 0 -> |s|. Set partEnd = max(partEnd, lastChar[s[i]]). If a letter occurs in the middle of our current partition, then the partition has to extend atleast as far as that letters last occurence. Then if i = partEnd, we reached the end of the current partition without extending it more, so we can finish it. Push (partEnd - partBegin + 1) into output array and set partBegin = i + 1, next partition starts on next letter. Return output array.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(26)", "order": 132 }, { "cat": "Greedy", "num": 678, "name": "Valid Parenthesis String", "risk": "High", "back": "Using top down dp. We want to count if the number of open and close parens is even, and if they are in the right order. \"The right order\" can be verified easily: when we encounter a clos e paren, check if we have more open paren than close. If not, we are unbalanced and there are more close parent to the right of our open parens. Implement this as recurse(i, l, r). If i == |s|, return l == r (is the string balanced). Else check if we have a cache entry, return false if yes (we tried this branch and failed). Else, if s[i] == '(', recurse(i + 1, l + 1, r). If s[i] == ')' recurse with r + 1 instead. If s[i] is *, check both branches and recurse s(i + 1, l, r) (empty string). For the close parents, we also need to check && l > r, to make sure the string has not become unbalanced at that point (check for both ')' and '*' close branches before recursing). If any branch is true, return true. Else set cache for this i,l,r and return false.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^3) Space: O(n^3)\n\nNotes: Cache can either be n sets of pairs l,r or 3d bool array i,l,r\n\n— alt —\n\nWe could easily solve this if there were no *. Keep an \"open\" count. If s[i] == '(', inc open. If s[i] == ')', dec open. If open becomes negative return false. At the end return open == 0. We can modify this algorithm to take into account *. Instead of keep one open count, we keep a minOpen and maxOpen, representing open count if we chose * to be '(' or ')'. We scan s again. If s[i] is'(' we increment min and max. If s[i] is')' we decrement both. If s[i] is '*' we decrement min and increment max (choosing '(' and ')') respectively. If maxOpen ever becomes negative return false, because the string is unrecoverably unbalanced. It can happen though that our minOpen also becomes negative (e.g. \"(*)\"). That is ok though so long as maxOpen >= 0. So we just reset minOpen to 0 if it becomes negative, this is basically retroactively choosing an empty space instead for '*'. At the end, our minOpen should be 0 if we managed to build a balanced, valid string, so return minOpen == 0.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 133 }, { "cat": "Intervals", "num": 57, "name": "Insert Interval", "risk": "Med", "back": "Because we have to make a copy of the full input array (minus merged intervals), we can do a full loop over the input array. For each src interval, there are three possibilities: 1) src is smaller than our newInterval, so we insert it beforehand. 2) src is larger than our newInterval, so we insert it afterwards. 3) src overlaps with newInterval. It can either lie fully inside newInterval, or they can partially overlap and so extend each other. The trick that we use to make this code simple is that we can separate the operations of merging and inserting our new interval. So inside our loop: We first check if src[1] < newIntv[0], if so we add it now. Then we check if src[0] > newIntv[1]. If this is true, two things can happen a) it is time to insert our newIntv or b) we are inserting larger intervals after newIntv. We can do these in one operation: we insert newIntv and assign src to newIntv. The first time this runs, it inserts newIntv that we merged. Every time afterwards, it inserts and interval larger than newIntv and temporarily stores src in the newIntv variable, to be inserted on the next step. Finally the third option in our loop is if neither of the above is true, and so src and newIntv overlap. We can simply merge them be min-ing newIntv[0] with src[0] and max-ing newIntv[1] with src[1]. Finally after the loop, we insert the last newIntv (either the largest interval, or newIntv if it ate all intervals up to the end), then return result.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: If we want to save ourselves copying src once we hit larger intervals, we can instead in the larger branch just check if newIntervals has elments and if yes insert if first and then clear it. Then always insert src. We just have to modify the end of the method to only insert newInterval at the end if its not been cleared. Normally we'd always have an element, either the big merged one to the end, or the last src.", "order": 134 }, { "cat": "Intervals", "num": 56, "name": "Merge Intervals", "risk": "Low", "back": "Very similar to \"Insert Interval\", but we dont have to deal with intervals that come before our current one. First we sort the input because its not guaranteed to be. Then we set mergedInterval to input[0]. We iterate 1 -> |input|. input[i][0] > merged[1], we found a larger interval so we insert merged and set merged to input[i]. Else we have an overlapping interval, so min together input[i][0] and merged[0], and max together input[i][1] and merged[1]. Because we reset merged when we insert a larger, this also works if there are multiple blocks in the array that need merging. After the loop, insert the last merged, then return result.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * log(n)) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: We can save some time by re-using the input array and keeping \"mergedInterval\" as an index into the input array, rather than a separate array.", "order": 135 }, { "cat": "Intervals", "num": 435, "name": "Non-overlapping Intervals", "risk": "Med", "back": "If we sort the input list, we can greedily work through it and decide which intervals we should keep. So first we sort the list. Then we keep a pre index, set to 0. We iterate 1 -> |input|. Now there are three cases: 1) input[i][0] >= input[pre][1]: the later interval does not overlap pre, we can keep both. We only advance pre by setting it to i. 2) input[i][1] > input[pre][i]: The later interval extends further than pre, in this case we remove i and keep pre, as it gives us more space for future intervals. We increment remove count and keep pre as is. 3) Else [pre][1] > [i][1]: pre extends further than i. In this case case we throw away pre and keep i, as it will lead to more space later. We increment remove count and set pre to i. Finally return remove count.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * log(n)) Space: O(1)", "order": 136 }, { "cat": "Intervals", "num": 252, "name": "Meeting Rooms", "risk": "Low", "back": "We can use the starting times to figure out any overlaps. Sort the input array by starting points. Iterate 1 -> |input|. If we ever find a pair where input[i - 1][1] > input[i][0], we found a meeting at i that starts before meeting i - 1 has ended, and its not possible to attend both, so return false. Else if we make it through the loop, return true.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * log(n)) Space: O(1)", "order": 137 }, { "cat": "Intervals", "num": 253, "name": "Meeting Rooms II", "risk": "Med", "back": "If we can keep track of the maximum simultaneous meetings, we know how many rooms we need at most. To track this correctly, we also need to know whether when a new meeting starts, there is a free room or if we need to allocate a new one. We can track this using a minheap (std::priority_queue with std::greater). Into the heap we insert the ending time of the meeting, so the top element will always be the one that ends the soonest. Now we sort the input so we have the meetings in the order they start. We iterate 0 -> |input|. If we have elements in the heap, and the top of the heap is smaller than the starting time input[i][0], we know that previous meeting has ended before the i-th started. If so we pop from the heap. Then we insert input[i][1] into the heap to claim the room. We set roomsNeeded to max(roomsNeeded, |heap|). At the end we return rooms needed.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * log(n)) Space: O(n)\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can notice something from the prio_que solution: It seperates the ending times from their respective start times. This is a hint that we dont need to look at each data point together. In terms of the end times, we only care about when the earliest meeting ends, which can be any meeting and we dont care when they started. So to solve this, we could iterate through the start times, and check if there is a meeting that ended before the start time, if yes, we dont need to allocate an extra room. \n\nWe create two new vectors, start and end into which we copy the start and end time of each interval. Then we sort both. Start contains the meetings in the order they start in, end in the order they end in. We now keep two indices, s and e pointing into the respective arrays. We keep two counters, maxMeet and concurrMeet. Init everything to 0. While s < |start|. If start[s] < end[e], this meeting starts before the next earliest one has ended, so we need another room -> increment s and concurrMeet. Else if its >= end[e], this meeting starts after the last earliest one has ended and we can reuse the room -> increment e, decrement concurrMeet. After the branches set maxMeet = max(maxMeet, concurrMeet). Return maxMeet at the end.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * log(n)) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Basically start is the meetings in order they start in and that we traverse them in. End is only there to tell us what time a meeting is going to end next, so we can check if we can re-use a room for the next s.", "order": 138 }, { "cat": "Intervals", "num": 1851, "name": "Minimum Interval to Include Each Query", "risk": "High", "back": "This can be solved pretty easily in O(m*n) time by going through each query and scanning all intervals to find the smallest that includes the query. We could spead this up a lot if we could find the smallest valid interval without doing a scan. We can do this with one pass by sorting intervals by their start value and sorting queries. This way, we can iterate through queries and keep a pointer into intervals. On each new query, we shift up the interval pointer until we find an interval that starts after the current query. So we only need to consider intervals up until the pointer r. We can include more intervals though, because any that end before the current query, we do not need to consider either. Finally we'd like to find the min-sized interval in less than O(n). We can use a min_heap that sorts by interval size. So, we sort intervals and queries. We make a min_heap that stores an interval size and its end value, we sort primarily by size and secondarily by end value. Then we keep an index i into intervals. We iterate through queries. While i < |intervals| and intervals[i][0] <= query (interval starts before or on query), we add that intervals size and end value to the min heap and increment i. This adds all intervals to consider. Then while min_heap has values, and heap top end value is smaller than query, we pop them from the heap. This removes from consideration intervals that ended before query, which are invalid even if they are the smallest. We're allowed to do this because queries is sorted, so its impossible for a later query to be included in intervals that a previous query wasnt. Then if the heap still has elements, we take the size of the top interval as the answer for query, else -1. Finally, we need to ensure the results are in the same order is the original order queries was in before sorting. We can either copy the original array and store our intermediate result in a hashmap so we can remap them before returning, or we can do an index sort on queries instead of sorting the array itself, so we can insert directly into an output array, doesnt much matter because memory will still be linear.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(max(m,n) * log(max(m,n)) Time: O(n)\n\nNotes: After we pair down the heap by discarding expired intervals, its possible that there are still invalid intervals under the heap top, but we dont care because the heap shows us the smallest valid one. Those invalid ones can either stay in the heap or get discarded later, but if they ever bubble to the top, we'll throw them away anyways and so they are never an issue.", "order": 139 }, { "cat": "Math & Geometry", "num": 48, "name": "Rotate Image", "risk": "Med", "back": "basically, we go trough the rows top to bottom\nafter each row, the width of the column we need to swap shrinks by two since we already swapped the borders to represent this we keep row which grows by one each step from 0, and col which shrinks from width by one each step.\nthen for each row, the elements basically move in a spiral shape, where we swap top left -> top right -> bottom right -> bottom left -> top left.\nFor each row we we start at 0 and iterate through our column width (col - row), which we use as an offset, with which we can calculate the swap positions:\ntop left is: row, row + offset, its column moves 1 right every offset step\ntop right is: row + offset, col, its row moves 1 down every offset step\nbottom right is: col, col - offset, its column moves 1 left every offset step\nbottom left is: col - offset, row, its row moves 1 up every offset step.\nnotice how for the tops and bottoms their variable value is the same, just switched beteween row and column. we take advantage of the fact that the matrix is symmetrical so we can reuse row and col interchangably for min and max.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(row*col) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: You could also just do this with math. Generate a 90 degree rotation matrix (cos, -sin, sin, cos). Then step through the cells, calculate their position relative to the center of the matrix, rotate the position and swap.", "order": 140 }, { "cat": "Math & Geometry", "num": 54, "name": "Spiral Matrix", "risk": "Med", "back": "We set up for boundaries that we use to step right -> down -> left -> up, decreasing the boundaries so we spiral inwards over time. L = 0, R = |matrix|, T = 0, B = |matrix[0]|. While L < R && T < B. Visited the top row L -> R adding m[T][i] to out. Increment T as we are done with this row. T -> B pushing m[i][r - 1] into out. Decrement R, we are done with the column. Check if L >= R || T >= B, if this is a non-square matrix we could be done, if so break. Iterate R - 1 -> L - 1, pushing m[B - 1][i] into out. Decrement B, done with this row. Iterate B - 1 -> T - 1, pushing matrix[i][L] into out. Increment L, done with this column. Loop repeats now, our spiral keeps shrinking. Return out at the end.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(row*col) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: We could also treat this like a dfs stepping in alternating directions, tracking visited elements.", "order": 141 }, { "cat": "Math & Geometry", "num": 73, "name": "Set Matrix Zeroes", "risk": "Med", "back": "Simple solution is to iterate the matrix. Keep a vector of row indices that contains 0 and a vector of col indices that are 0. If m[i][j] is 0, add i to rows, j to cols. Then iterate over each vector, and for each row, set each column in that row 0, for each column set each row in that colum 0.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(row*col) Space: O(row+col)\n\nNotes: Though it uses less memory than copying the whole matrix, it is not in-place.\n\n— alt —\n\nInstead of using seperate vectors to store which rows and cols we need to 0, we can use the matrix itself for that. We use the cells in the 0-th row and col for this. We only need to give special care to the first row, which we'll need to 0 in a separate way. We iterate through rows and cols i,j. If m[i]][j] is 0. We need to mark. If i > 0, we set m[i][0] and m[0][j] = 0 to denote that this column and row need to be zero-ed later. If i = 0, we instead set a special flag zeroRow so we can 0 the first row later and not stomp our other info (we consider the top left cell to only be part of the first row, not the first cell). Now we do a pass over the first column from 1 -> height (we skip the first row since that has infor on which cols to 0). If m[0][row] is 0, zero that whole column. Now do a pass over the first row from 0 to width. If m[0][col] is 0, zero that whole column. Now that we used the information in the first row, we can also zero the first row if required. If zeroRow was set true in the first pass over the matrix, iterate the first row and set each cell zero.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(row*col) Space: O(1)", "order": 142 }, { "cat": "Math & Geometry", "num": 202, "name": "Happy Number", "risk": "Low", "back": "While our current n is not 1, compute the next number (get the next digit with % 10, then slice it out with / 10 until cur n is 0). Keep a hashset if seen numbers. If hashset already contains new n, return false. Else add new n to hashset, set cur n to new n.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log n) Space: O(log n)\n\nNotes: Complexity is number theory bullshit (see LC solution). But its related to how many possible steps there are to get down to 1 or a cycle and the fact that we slice through the digits, which there are at most [logN] to go through per N.\n\n— alt —\n\nCan also use floyd's cycle detection algorithm for this. Factor next number calculation out into method. Set int slow = n, int fast = nextNumber(n). While (slow != fast), fast = nextNumber(nextNumber(fast)), slow = nextNumber(slow). Will meet either at 1 or during cycle. Return slow == 1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log n) Space: O(1)", "order": 143 }, { "cat": "Math & Geometry", "num": 66, "name": "Plus One", "risk": "Low", "back": "Basically just addition with carry. Start i = |digits| - 1, carry = true. While (i >= 0 && carry). Set carry false. Add 1 to digits[i]. If its 10, set it to 0 and set carry true. Decrement i. Then make out vector. If carry is still true, push one into vector. Then copy digits into out vector. Return out.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)", "order": 144 }, { "cat": "Math & Geometry", "num": 50, "name": "Pow(x, n)", "risk": "Med", "back": "We could calculate this linearly multiplying, but we can be faster if we divide and concquer. Consider 2^10, which is multiplying 2 by itself 10 time. In that there is a large repeated suproblem, multiplying 2 by itself 5 times. So 2^10 = 2^5 * 2^5. 2^5 = 2 * 2^2 * 2^2. 2^2 = 2 * 2. 2 = 2 * 1 -> 1 is our base case. We've just calculated the result in 4 steps, which is ceil(lg(10)). So, lets implement this via recursion. Recurse takes x and n. If x = 0, return 0, no point calculating. If n = 0, return 1, our base case. Then call result = recurse(x * x, n / 2). If n is even (% 2 == 0), return res. Else return res * x (the extra multiply we need to make up for a power not divisible by 2). Main function calls res = recurse(x, abs(n)). Then if n >= 0, return res, else return 1 / res (reciprocal for negative power).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(n)) Space: O(log(n))\n\nNotes: x = 2, n = 10 -> 1024 (2^10)\n       x = 4, n = 5 -> 256 * 4 = 1024\n         x = 16, n = 2 -> 256 \n           x = 256, n = 1 -> 256 * 1 -> 256\n             x = 512, n = 0 -> 1", "order": 145 }, { "cat": "Math & Geometry", "num": 43, "name": "Multiply Strings", "risk": "Med", "back": "We need to do long multiplication, where we iterate through one number, and multiple out with the digits in the other number scaled by the place and carry the tens digit. We can cheat a bit because we'll store the digits seperately, meaning we dont need to track the place manually. We reserve a result vector<int> of size |num1| + |num2|. If every place carries we'll have that many digits. Then we iterate backwards through one number, and for that digit, backwards through the other number. We parse out the two digits and multiply them. Then we calculate the output index in result as (|nums2| - 1 - i) + (|nums1| - 1 + j). We add the multiplied to result[idx]. Then we need to carry, so to result[idx + 1] we add result[idx] / 10 (to get the  tens). Then we set result[idx] %= 10, to reduce it to the ones place. We now have the number in reverse order in result, with possibly some leading 0s. We seek backwards through result until we find the first non-0 digit. If we find none return \"0\". Else iterate from that index to 0, pushing each digit into an out string (this also reverses the number for us), then return out.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|num1| * |num2|) Space: O(|num1| + |num2|)", "order": 146 }, { "cat": "Math & Geometry", "num": 2013, "name": "Detect Squares", "risk": "Med", "back": "To build a square with a point query, we need a point that lies diagonal 45 degrees to that point. We can check this if the another point has the same distance in x and y to the query point, and those points are not the same. If we have such a point, we can check if we can complete a square if we have two points that lie the same distance on both sides of the diagonal. This is easy to check because both of those points would share one coordinate with each of our diagonal points. Because we must support duplicate points, we can save some time by reducing that information. So we keep a dict that maps point to number of occurences. We also keep a list of unique points. On add, we check if the point is in the dict. If yes, we just increment the dict counter. Else we add (point, 1) to the dict and the point to the unique list. On query point (px, py), we iterate the unique list. We check if point x,y is same as px,py, if yes kip. We check if abs(px - x) == abs(py - y). If no skip, this does not form a diagonal. Then we check the count of (px, py) in dict. Now we check if (px, y) is in dict and how often, this is our first point completing a triangle. Then check (x, py), this point completes the square. If we dont have either, skip, we cant make a square. If we have both, multiply the three counts, this is how many different ways we can choose from the points to make a square. Add this value to result. Then return result.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) build, O(n) query Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: To make a dict of points, we can combine the 32 bit point coordinates into a 64 bit key and hash that. Every unique combination of 32 bit ints will give a unique 64 bit int key.", "order": 147 }, { "cat": "Bit Manipulation", "num": 136, "name": "Single Number", "risk": "Low", "back": "Keep a counter, xor every number in nums with it. xor-ing once mixes the bits of a number into counter. xor-ing the same number again unsets the relevant bits. If there is only one number that appears once, it will leave all its bits set at the end.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 148 }, { "cat": "Bit Manipulation", "num": 191, "name": "Number of 1 Bits", "risk": "Low", "back": "While n > 0, add to bit counter (n & 1 -> is lsb set), then shift n >>= 1 right. return bit counter.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(32) or O(floor(log(n)) + 1) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Can also do while n > 0, n &= (n - 1) -> slides bit pattern one over to offset leftmost bit and unset it, inc counter each iteration. But i like my version more, machine efficiency should be a wash. Could also just use popcnt intrinsic.", "order": 149 }, { "cat": "Bit Manipulation", "num": 338, "name": "Counting Bits", "risk": "Med", "back": "Iterate [0,n]. For each value count the number of n bits.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*log(n)) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Time log(n) because to represent a number n we need floor(log(n)) + 1 bits. So at most that many bits can be sat one before we hit 0 for each n.\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can exploit bit patterns of previous numbers to do this in linear time. Bits[0] is 0. Bits[1] is 01. Bits[2] is 10, Bits[3] 11. Now, Bits[4] is 100, Bits[5] is 101. Notice how bits 4 and 5 are just the patterns for 0 and 1 offset by an extra bit. This offset happens each time we pass a power of two. This means we can do the following, by checking when we a pass a new pow2 and tracking the offset. We init bits[0] = 0. We init an offset counter at 1. Now we iterate [1..n]. First check if (i == n*2), this means i has double from last offset, so reached a new power of 2 (1->2->4->8...). If so, we double the offset too. Now we can compute the offset as we outland before: bits[i] = bits[i - offset] + 1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Example of how this walks;  So 1 is bits[0] + 1, 2 is is bits[0] + 1. 3 is bits[1] + 1. 4 is bits[0] + 1, 5 is bits[1] + 1, 6 is bits[2] + 1, 7 is bits[3] + 1, 8 is bits[0] + 1, 9 is bits[1] + 1, 10 is bits[2] + 1 (because 10 is the 8 bit, the one our + 1 describes and the 2 bit, which we get from bits[2]), etc.", "order": 150 }, { "cat": "Bit Manipulation", "num": 190, "name": "Reverse Bits", "risk": "Med", "back": "Slide to patterns over the number in opposite directions. Src mask starts with 1 in the MSB, dst mask with in the LSB. While n > 0, check if src_mask is set in n, and if set it dst_mask in dst. Then shift src_mask right, dst_mask left.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(32)) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: You can also iterate offset 31 through 0, use the offset to check the bit in src, and set in dst using in invert of the offset mask.", "order": 151 }, { "cat": "Bit Manipulation", "num": 268, "name": "Missing Number", "risk": "Low", "back": "Use the xor trick to identify the missing number. Go through each num in n and xor it into mask. Then iterate through all numbers [0,n] that we expect in the range. One number will be in [0,n] that isnt nums, leaving its bits set. All other numbers will have been xor-ed twice, unsetting their bits. Return mask.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(2n) Space: O(1)\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can use euler sum formula to figure out to how much we expect the values in the array to sum up to. We expect n, but have (n - 1) in nums, so our is nums.size() + 1. Now calc what the would sum to by (n * (n - 1)) / 2. Iterate through nums, subtracting each i from sum. Return sum, it now contains the only number we havent subtracted, which is the one we are missing.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 152 }, { "cat": "Bit Manipulation", "num": 371, "name": "Sum of Two Integers", "risk": "High", "back": "two step algorithm: xor to get the addition, and the two values to get the carry repeat xor with previous result and carry until carry is 0. the xor mimics the add step taking the carry into account: 1 ^ 0 = 1 (added), 0 ^ 0 = 0 (added), 1 ^ 1 = 0 (added, taken away by carry) now we can get our carry by and-ing the two numbers pre-xor together, since we only carry if we have 1 & 1. Now we shift the carry one left, since we want to add it to the next digit over, and we repeat with our previous result and carry. So: assign a to result, b to carry. Importantly, we have to make carry unsigned, because otherwise signed shifts (especially on negative values, will screw us). While (carry != 0), temp is unsigned(result) & carry << 1. result is result ^ int(carry). The xor works on twos complement so casting back carry takes care of that for us. Now assign temp to carry, repeat. Return result.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(32)) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: example: 11 + 9 = 20\n          1011\n          1001\nxor:    0010\nand:  1001 (<< 1)\nxor:  10000\nand: 00010 (<< 1)\nor: 01010 -> 16 + 4 = 20\nand: 00000", "order": 153 }, { "cat": "Bit Manipulation", "num": 7, "name": "Reverse Integer", "risk": "Med", "back": "Reconstruction is simple: while x > 0, take x % 10, this is our digit. divide x by 10 to round off the bottom digit. Result is result by 10 (to make space for now digit) plus digit. Dont have to worry about negative because neg mod 10 gives us neg digit. Bounds is tricky. We basically wanna check if the next result value will overflow our int (our underflow if negative). Problem tells us our bounds are 2^31 - 1 and - 2 ^ 31 so two's complement but with one less bit. We can check this way (for positive). Calc our max value pow(2^31) - 1. Now calc the value this would be before one last shift, which / 10. Now calc its last digit, so max value / 10. Now we can check at each step if result is already > max_val before shift (we're already screwed on the next shift) or if result is equal to max and the next digit is larger or equal to max_vals last digit (we would create a value larger than max by shifting max before shit and adding a digit larger than max values largest digit)\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(n)) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Bounds check for negative works in the same way but with < and <=.", "order": 154 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 528, "name": "Random Pick with Weight", "risk": "Med", "back": "To achieve a weighted selection, we need to basically be able to map a random index into our range according to the weighting. One way to do this would be to build an array that has each w in it according to its frequency, pick a random element, and return the index of the element in the original weight array. But this would take O(sum(w)) space. We can achieve the same thing with a prefix array. On init, we walk w, and add up w[i] with the sum of all previous w, and insert this into pre[i]. This basically gives a weight range mapping how often we want each index to be picked. To make our selection, we can now generate a random value (e.g. rand()) and map it into the range [0,sum(w)] (e.g. % sum(w)). Now we need to find the entry in pre who's value includes the random value (>= rand_value), and return its index. We could do this with a linear search, but the pre is naturally sorted. So we can use binary search instead. We can use lower_bound and distance(begin), or implement a normal bin_search that runs while l < r and returns l. This gives us the index of rand_val if its in array, or the first index at which we would expect rand_val.\n\nComplexity: Time: Build O(n) Pick: O(log(n)) Space: O(n)", "order": 155 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 366, "name": "Find Leaves of Binary Tree", "risk": "Med", "back": "The \"level\" of each node isnt how far down the tree it is, its how many levels there are below it. So a leaf has level 0, the leafs root has level 1, the node above that has level 2. We can implement this using DFS. Our base case is that node is null, which means we went past a leaf, so we return -1. Then we call dfs for node->left and node->right, this returns how many levels there are below left and right each. We determine the current node's level now by selecting the max between the two levels and adding 1 (so if we hit a leaf, both branches would return -1 and we'd step up to 0). If our output vector is too small for level, we grow it, then we push node->val into the level. Then return level.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: We can grow the output using just push_back because we'lll always find new levels in the order the are supposed to be in the output. We'll dfs all the way to a leaf node, which inserts level 0, then we find the leaf neighbor if there is one, then we insert the parent at level 1 above, etc.", "order": 156 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 359, "name": "Logger Rate Limiter", "risk": "Med", "back": "Keep a hashmap of message to last time printed. When a new message arrives, check if its in the hashmap. If no, add it to the map and return true. If yes, check if the last time printed was 10 or more seconds before the current timestamp. If yes, update the map with the new timestamp and return true. Else return false.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(1) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Only possible problem with this approach is that the hashmap keeps growing over time. We could run occasional maintenance on it to remove expired entries. An alternative solution is to have a literal queue of messages implemented and a hashset of messages. When a new message arrives, we first pump everything from the queue that expired. When something expired we purge it from the set. Then we lookup the new message in the set, if its not there we insert and return true, else false as it hasnt expired. O(n)/O(n)", "order": 157 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 68, "name": "Text Justification", "risk": "Med", "back": "This is a straightforward implementation problem with no real algorithmic tricks. We keep a counter i, which is the next word we'll process. While i < words.size(). We start counting the num chars in the line = 0. We start a second counter j, which is the word after our current line ends. While j < words.size() and numChars + words[j].size + (j - i), advance j and add its lenght to numChars. (j - i) represents how many spaces between words we have, numWords - 1. Now we found the words we need to include in the line. If j == words.size(), we reached the last line, requires special handling. Calculate totalSpaces in line, maxWidth - numSlots. NumSlots is (j - i - 1) (because j is 1 past the end of the line). For last line, we iterate i -> j, add words[j] to line, if totalSpaces > 0 add a space to line and dec totalSpaces. After adding all the words, add space for each remaining totalSpace. For all other lines, we max numSpaceSlots with 1 (in case we only have one word, need to justify the right of it). Iterate i -> j, add word[j] to line. Calculate how many spaces we add to this slot as ceil(totalSpaces / numSpaceSlots) (we scale how many spaces we spend left to right). add that many spaces to the line. Then dec totalSpaces by that amount and dec numSpaceSlots by 1. Add line to result, set i to j.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Time basically scales with the number of words. We have scan forward n times to break our lines, and then do a second pass over that set of words to paste them into the line. Space calcuation doesnt require any loops, so this is basically a linear algorithm (possibly 2n)", "order": 158 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1293, "name": "Shortest Path in a Grid with Obstacles Elimination", "risk": "Med", "back": "This is a shortest path problem, with the slight modification that the the eliminations add a \"extra\" dimension to explore. So we could could implement this as a BFS and in addition to checking visited, also check if we've seen the path with the same eliminations before. Or we can implement it as a Dijkstra, but in addition to a minPath array, we also keep a maxK array that tracks the largest number of elims this path has seen. We reopen a path if the pathSoFar is shorter or the kSoFar is larger.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * m * k) Space: O(n * m)\n\nNotes: One of the simplest way to include k is to literally add it as a third dimension to the visited array. Instead of each visited[y][x] being a bool, its an array of bool of size k + 1. This increases the space to n*m*k.", "order": 159 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 2096, "name": "Step-By-Step Directions From a Binary Tree Node to Another", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can break this into three steps: 1) Find the path from root to src and dst. Find path function is recursive, returns true if root->val == target. Else if left node != null and find(left node), push 'L' into string. Else if right node != null and find(right node), push 'R' into path. Return path ! empty. Now we have the two paths in reversed (stack) order. The root may not be the least common ancestor, so we shorten the paths by popping off the back of both while they are the same. Then we create a src string of all 'U's of the length of src path. Then reverse the dst string to undo stack order, we combiner the two and return them.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)", "order": 160 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1048, "name": "Longest String Chain", "risk": "Med", "back": "This is a DP problem. We flip the problem upside down, rather than trying to add a letter, we see if we can delete a letter from the next word to turn it in our current one to chain. First we sort our strings ascending by length, since we can only chain to a string of len + 1. We create a cache of size word array, value -1. Main method has a loop through words and checks if dfs with i is max len. Dfs takes cur idx and words. If cache[cur] != -1, return cache[cur]. Dfs sets up chain_len = 0. Iterates cur + 1 -> |words|. If the |next word| == |cur word|, skip by continue. If |next word - 1| > |cur word| break, this word is too long to chain and there will only be longer ones later. Now we check if we can chain from cur to next. If yes, dfs(i, words) and check if max chain_len. After loop, add 1 to chain_len for current word, write into cache and return. \nChain check has two indices i and j and loops while i < |cur|. If cur[i] == next[j], advance i and j. Else check if deletes (inited to 1) is 0, if yes return false. Else dec deletes, inc only j. At the end return if (i == |cur| && j == |next|) || deletes == 1 (there is one mismatch at the end of the word and we're allowed to delete it).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|words|^2 * word_len) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: We need to try for each word, how long of a string chain we can form with the next word, recursively forward until we run out.", "order": 161 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 818, "name": "Race Car", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can treat this like a bfs finding the shortest path. We keep a queue of triplet [steps,pos,speed] with initial (0,0,1). Each step, we pop off the queue, check if pos is target and if so return steps. Else we have two choices: we can accelerate, so (steps + 1, pos + speed, speed * 2). Or we can reverse so (steps + 1, pos, speed > 0 ? -1 : 1). Because we process in BFS order we naturally find the shortest path. But, because we double our speed when accelerating, we very quickly shoot off into infinities, so we need to do some pruning. One, we abandon any path where our abs(pos) is > 2 * target, we assume we just went to far past or back. Two, we only consider reversing under certain circumstance: 1) if our speed is positive and we'll overshoot the target or 2) our speed is negative and we'll undershoot the target. Otherwise we'll gets lots of paths where we reverse, reverse again to become position, then reverse again.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(log(n)) Space: O(log(n))\n\nNotes: This. O(log(n)) time because we halve our distance to target each time. When we cant exactly reach it it gets messy, but it should be close to amortized log. Queue grows similarly slowly.", "order": 162 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 759, "name": "Employee Free Time", "risk": "Med", "back": "Free time is any time slot where no meeting is currently in progress. We find can such timeslots by scanning through the meetings left to right in the order they start and keeping track of when they end. We create a min heap of intervals, sorted by start. Then we insert all intervals from all employees. We keep track of latestEndTime = INT_MIN, the latest time any current meeting ends. Then while the heap has elements, we pop [start,end] off the heap. If latestEndTime != INT_MIN and latestEndTime < start, there is free time with no meetings between latestEndTime and start, so insert an interval [latestEndTime, start] into the result. Then set latestEndTime = max(latestEndTime, end). Return result.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n * log(n)) Space: O(n)", "order": 163 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 9, "name": "Robot Room Cleaner", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can implement this as a backtracking dfs. We assume the starting pos as a our virtual (0,0). From there we can dfs in all 4 directions unil we hit an obstacle. So we set up a cache that maps for each x we visited, which y we visited. Dfs takes robot, pos and cur facing. Call robot.clean(). Cache pos. Then iterate through the four facing directions. Calculate the new pos from pos and new facing. If we already cached new pos, continue. Else save the current facing, and turn the robot to point in the new facing (Implement a helper method the can turn the robot from current facing to the facing we want). Now try move. If we could move, dfs with new pos and new facing. Then turn the robot in negative current facing direction (the direction we came from), and move. Finally turn the robot back into our previous facing direction.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(4 * n * m - obstacles) Space: O(n * m)\n\nNotes: We can save a little time by not turning back to original facing on every loop iteration, but instead keep track of cur facing throughout loop. Turn from curfacing to dx,dy, then from that to -curfacing. Only after the loop turn back towards our original facing.", "order": 164 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1146, "name": "Snapshot Array", "risk": "Med", "back": "If we try to version the entire array by copying it, we end up with immense memory usage. Instead, we only store values that have been set, and we store them with the snapshotId they were set at so we can query later. We ignore the initial length and instead keep a hashmap of int -> vector<int,int>. The key is the index, the value is an array of pairs (value, snapId). We start snapId at 0, and increase it at each snap. When a value is set, we check if we already have an entry for this index. If we do, we check if its snapId is the snapId we are currently on, if so we override this value with the new one, since no snap has been taken since the last set. Else if we have no values yet, or the current snapId differs from the one we last set at, we push a new entry into the array. Get queries the hashmap for index, returns 0 if nothing found. Else we have an array of history for the index. We run upper_bound looking for snap_id. We want to find either the exact snap_id if we saved with it, or the next closest smaller snap_id (since if there is larger snap_id afterwards, all snap revision between that one and the smaller are implicitely included in the smaller, e.g we set at snap 2 and snap 4, snap 3 is implictely included in snap2). If upper bounds returns begin, return 0, else return the value of prev(result) (if we look for 4 and we have 4, we get end or the snap after it from upper_bound, so prev works. If we have 2 and 4 and we look for 3, upper_bound gives us 4, so prev(4) is 2, which works since as previously described, 3 is implicetly included in 2).\n\nComplexity: Time: Insert O(1) Snap O(1) Get O(log(s)) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: Instead of array we could use an ordered map and its built-in upper bound.", "order": 165 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1937, "name": "Maximum Number of Points with Cost", "risk": "Med", "back": "Its pretty easy to come up with a top-down DP solution that we can either speed up with memoization, or translate into tabulation. But, both of those solutions are O(m*n*n) -> O(n^3), which is too slow for the tests in this problem. So you basically need to pull a solution of your ass that is at most O(m*n) -> O(n^2). There is a different bottom up dp approach. In this approach, we go through each row. For each cell in the row, we then compute what the max points you can get from the previous row are. We run this all they way down, which computes us the max points each of the last cells can get, and we pick our max from that.\nWe init vector of size m (columsn) prev to 0, these are maximum points each of the previous row's cells could get. The key observation is that a current cells maximum points is the maximum points from the row above it with the cost factored in, it is not dependent on the current cell's points. To reduce our complexity, we must avoid comparing each current cell against the complete previous row. We can do this with two linear passes over the row instead. The observation here is that for each cell, its max can come from the left (or above) of it or from the right (or above of it). For cell[0], the max from the left is prev[0]. For cell[1] it is max(prev[0], prev[1]). But for cell[2], we can compress it, we already know the max of (1,2) is in cell[1], so we can just select max(cell[1], prev[2]). To avoid special casing, we store the previous max in a runningMax variable, so for each cell[i] the max is max(runningMax, prev[i]). But, we also need to factor the cost of selecting an offset row in. We do this by actually selecting runningMax - 1. This works because we do it at each step. So if both cell[1] and cell[2] choose to the runningMax over their prev, they would've both selected runningMax - 1. So at 2, we subtracted 2 already from running max, which is exactly the cost of selecting column 0 for column 2. If we instead choose prev[i], the cost resets accordingly.\nAll of the above is also true for the scan from the right, so we just repeat the same logic keeping a running max, but we iterate right to left and write into a different array. We need to do left and right scans so that each cell sees all cells before it. On the left pass, a cell only sees the prev cells before it. On the right pass, a cell only sees the cells after it. Only if we do the left and right pass, does it see all the cells before and after it (and the cell right above it twice). Once we have done the left and right pass, we can select if the biggest value before or after each cell gives us the biggest points gain. We do this by doing one more pass over prev, and assigning to prev[i] std::max(left[i], right[i]) + points[i], so the maximum value out the biggest value to the left and right of it (with cost factored) in, plus the points for that cell. If we repeat this process over each row of points. Prev will at the end contain the max points we can get if we choose each column in the last row. Now we can just select the max_element from, and we get the max points achievable.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: https://walkccc.me/LeetCode/problems/1937/\nhttps://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-number-of-points-with-cost/discuss/1344908/C%2B%2BJavaPython-3-DP-Explanation-with-pictures-O(MN)-Time-O(N)-Space", "order": 166 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 539, "name": "Minimum Time Difference", "risk": "Med", "back": "This is a simple interval difference problem with on edge case, where we can wrap around the back of the intervals to the front. We parse each string, converting the hours to minutes and then pushing the total minutes into an array. Calculating the difference in minutes is straight-forward compared to trying to do it in 24-hour format. Once we parsed everything, we sort the array ascending. Now we handle the edge case, which can be if we have two intervals at the start and end of array that are closer to midnight than each other. E.g [01:12,22:15], it is shorter to wrap-around midnight than to go from 1 am to 10 pm. To handle this, we take the front of the array and push it into the back, but with 1440 minutes (24 * 60, full day) added. This emulates wrapping around midnight and gives the wrapped-around distance when we compare the original last time with this one. Now we can iterate from 0 to len - 2, taking the difference between array[i + 1] and array at each step and keeping track of the minimum. Return the minimum.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*log(n)) Space: O(n)", "order": 167 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 2034, "name": "Stock Price Fluctuation", "risk": "Med", "back": "We use two self-correcting heaps to implement min and max in O(1) time. We implement a record struct containing time and price, that sorts itself based on time. We keep a hashmap from time to price, a Record latest, and a min and max heap of records. Current() returns the price of Latest, min and max return the price of the top of the heaps. When we update, we first update the time entry in hashmap. Then we push the new record into both heaps. There will now be a valid and invalid record for the timestamp in each heap, but it only matters if they are at the top. So we do self correction on update: For each heap, while the top record's price doesnt match whats in the hashmap, we pop from the heap and and push back with the correct price. This will ensure that all records at the top actually match the most recent price. Finally, if the update timestamp is >= Latest.time, set Latest to the new record.\n\nComplexity: Time: Getters O(1) Update best case: O(log(n) Worst case: O(n*log(n)) Space: O(3n)\n\nNotes: Update worst case can happen if we updated ever single record in a heap except the top, and then we get an update from the top, which then exposes every invalid record in the heap. This causes us to fully rebuild the heap, which is n * log(n). But in the average case this cost is amortized.", "order": 168 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 715, "name": "Range Module", "risk": "Med", "back": "Simple approach is to implement each operation in O(n):\n- Search scans all intervals and returns true if it finds one where i.left <= left && i.right >= right.\n\n- Add builds a new list of intervals. Start an itv merged {left, right}. Iterate the original list, add all itvs that end before left. If an itv. starts after merged.right, add merged to list, clear merged and copy the rest of intervals to the update list, break the loop. If an itv overlaps with left,right, set merged.left to min(self, itv.left), merged.right max(self, itv.right). After the loop ends, check if we've not cleared merged yet and insert if we didnt. Then move the update list to intervals.\n\n- Remove builds a new list. Iterate. If itv ends before left, add to new list. If itv starts after right, copy rest of src to dst, break. If overlap, if itv.left < left, insert new itv {itv, left} (range before they overlap that isnt being erase). If itv.right > right, insert {itv.right, right} (range after they stop overlapping). Move dst into src. These are independent if-clauses, so also works if we're splitting an interval by erasing only part out of its middle.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: We can improve search complexity using binary search. L = 0, R = len - 1. While L <= R. If intervals[M].left > right, intervals in the right half are bigger than our query, discard by setting R = M - 1. If intervals[M].right < left, intervals in left half our smaller than query, discard by setting L = M + 1. Else we have an overlap, return if intervals[m] includes query. If search exits, return false.\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can use an ordered set to emulate a segment/interval tree. Use std::set<Interval>, sorted on Interval.left.\nThe key thing we abuse is set::upper_bound, which returns us the first interval with left > query left, so the previous iterator (if one exists), has left <= query left.\n\n-) Add looks up upper_bound(left). If returned it isnt begin, we check if the prev interval overlaps. If its right >= our add left, it to prev. Then while it isnt end(set) and it->left <= right (still overlaps with add range), we merge by setting left = min(self, it->left), right = max(self, it->right). Then erase it. At the end re-insert the merged interval. \n\n-) Query for first overlap. Set up a vector of new split intervals. While it isnt end(set) and it->left <= right. If it->left < left, add to split (it->left, left). If it->right > right, add to split (right, it->right). Erase it. At the insert all split intervals into set.\n\n-) Query looks up upper_bound(left). If return it is begin(set), return false, the left side of the query doesnt overlap. Else check the prev of it, return prev.right >= right, does the right side of the query overlap.\n\nComplexity: Time: Query O(log(n)) Add/Remove: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: This improves the wall clock time, but complexity wise is the same as linear with binary search. Based on this bullshit, but I rewrote the code to be much, much nicer.\n\nThe upper_bound lookup for add/remove can be factored out into a common method. upper_bound(left,0). If it isnt begin, get prev. check prev->right >= left, if yes set it to prev. Return it.", "order": 169 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 642, "name": "Design Search Autocomplete System", "risk": "Med", "back": "Solve using a Trie. Each TrieNode in addition to nodes has sentence (if that node terminates one) and rank counter. It also has 27 nodes, where the first one is for ' '. When we construct AutoSuggest, we insert each sentence into the Trie and set the last node's rank to times. AutoSuggest stores a cur_input string and a cur_node which is the node in Trie where cur_input ends. On input, if we get '#', we push cur_input into node sentence if node doesnt have one yet, and inc rank by 1. Clear cur_input and set cur_node null, return. Else, if cur_node is null, set it to &root. Then push input char into cur_input, set cur_node to cur->getOrAddNode(input char). Now we get the suggestions. We do a DFS from cur_node, collecting all nodes under it that have a sentence. Then we sort the found nodes by rank, if rank is the same by sentence. Finally we iterate over sorted nodes and push their sentences into result. If we collect 3 sentences, break early, return result.\n\nComplexity: Time: Build O(sent * len) Input: O(V+E of cur_node as root) for query, O(n*log(n)) sort output\n\nNotes: Some speed improvements could be made if you didnt have to re-DFS the tree but could instead reduce the suggestion list we collected last input.\nInstead of collecting all nodes and sorting, we could collect into a k-min-heap, where k is 3.", "order": 170 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 419, "name": "Battleships in a Board", "risk": "Med", "back": "Pretty much exactly like \"200. Number of Islands\". Iterate over board, if cell is ship, inc ship counter and start a bfs. The bfs explores any 4-adjacent cell that is also a ship. We can either keep a visited set, or mark visited cells in the board with a special character. This explores the whole connected component for that ship. Doing this over the whole board identifies all blocks of ships.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n) Space: O(max(m,n))\n\nNotes: At worst we'll explore a ship that takes entire row or column, at which point our queue could take space for a whole row or column.\n\n— alt —\n\nWe can simplify this solution by taking advantage of the rules of the game. If we can identify the \"beginning\" of a ship, we dont need to mark cells as visited and we can do it in a single pass over the board. We can do this, because the beginning of a ship is any cell 'X' that doesnt have an 'X' at board[y][x - 1] or board[y - 1][x]. So we can do one pass over the board. If cell is '.' skip. If cell is 'X' and board[y][x - 1] is 'X', skip. If cell is 'X' and cell board[y - 1][x] is 'X' continue. Else inc num_ships, we found the beginning of a ship. Return num_ships.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n) Space: O(1)", "order": 171 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 2115, "name": "Find All Possible Recipes from Given Supplies", "risk": "Med", "back": "The relationship of recipes, ingredients and supplies forms a graph. Recipes and supplies are nodes. Ingredients can be either recipes or supplies, but the existence of an ingredient doesnt imply a node, only an edge. So we can build a graph as a map<string, vec<string>>. We iterate through recipes and an entry for it to the map. For each ingredient in the recipe, we add an edge from recipe to ingredient. This forms a directed graph, where a recipe has nodes going to its ingredients (dependencies). Then we iterate through supplies and an entry with no edges for each to the map. Finally we need a visited set, we'll have a map from string to state (unknown, visting, visited). We iterate over each recipe. If visited[recipe] is Visited, we verified that this recipe is cookable as a dependency of another recipe earlier, so we can just add to cookable list and continue. Else we topo sort with recipe, graph and visited. Topo sort sets visited[cur] (recipe) to Visiting. Then we iterate through cur's edges. For each next, we check if visited[next] is Visiting, if so, we return false. This means there is a back edge and therefore a cyclic dependency. If visited[next] is Visited, we already verified this, continue. Now we check if next is in graph (has a node), if its either a recipe or supply is must have one. If not, this is a supply we dont have, or a recipe we dont know how to cook, so we return false. Else we call topo_sort(next, graph, visited) and if this returns false we also return false. Otherwise if pass all neighbors, set visited[cur] visited. Finally in our main loop, if topo sort returns true, add to cookable recipes, return cookable recipe.\n\nComplexity: Time: Build O(recipe * ingredient + supplies) Topo sort: O(recipe * ingredients) Space: O(recipes + ingredients + supplies)", "order": 172 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 939, "name": "Minimum Area Rectangle", "risk": "Med", "back": "We need to identify potential rectangles, and then check to see if there are points that complete it. We check all n^2 pairs. If they share a coordinate, we ignore the pair, since they would form a vertical or horizontal line, which infinitely many sets of 2 other points can complete a rectangle with. Instead, if they dont share a coordinate, we consider that they might lie on opposite ends of a diagonal of a rectangle. There are only two points that would complete a rectangle for this, which we can lookup in O(1). First we build a hashset from all points, so we can check for the existance of points quickly. Then we iterate all pairs of points. At each inner loop step, we have p1 which is points[i] and p2 which is points[j]. If p1.x == p2.x or p1.y == p2.y, continue. Check if the map contains points (p1.x, p2.y) and (p2.x, p1.y). These would complete the rectangle by forming the other diagonal. If we dont have them, continue. Else calculate the area w * l (abs(p1.x - p2.x) * abs(p1.y - p2.y)) and check if its the min_area. If we find no rectangle, return 0, else return min_area.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^2) Space: O(n)", "order": 173 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 2128, "name": "Remove All Ones With Row and Column Flips", "risk": "Med", "back": "To figure this out you have to play with some examples and observe what happens. Ideally start from an empty matrix and see what you can construct. The key observation is that you need symmetry to flip all bits to 0. Basically, every row needs to be the same or an invert of the other rows. If we dont have that, we'd need more than one flip on the same row or column, which is impossible to make progress with, since that should just revert us back to the original. You can check this two ways:\n1) Iterate through the first row, if a bit is 1, flip its entire column. Afterward check each each column, it must be either all zeros or ones.\n2) Iterate each row, and check that the row is either entirely the same or entirely inverted from the first row. We can keep track of this with two accumulating flags each row iteration, if after iterating the row they are both false, this row is asymmetrical and we can return false.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1) if you mutate in-place or use option 2)", "order": 174 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 843, "name": "Guess the Word", "risk": "Med", "back": "This problem has a terrible description. Basically, you auto-fail if you call guess more than 10 times, and to pass you have to succeed in the guess within 10 tries for all test cases. The problem is that it is very difficult to write a solution that pass every case 100% because the easiest solution relies on a heuristic with random guesses. The way to approach this is a process of elimination where you try to reduce the candidate set after each guess, but it is easy to construct an example that relies on random chance: A list of 26 words that only differ in the first letter, using each letter of the alphabet. Just word other than the once chosen as candidate is as similar as the other ones to the secret, so there is no reasonable way to eliminate. But somehow, if you pass this test case into Leetcode, it actually accepts if you fail. So we choose to use this approach anyways.\nWe do 10 iterations of guesses. Each step, we pick a random word and guess. We take its similiarity. We then iterate through the wordlist, calculating how similar each word is to our guess. We check to the guess word how many same letters are in the same position. If that score is not the same as our returned guess, we discard the word. Else we push it into a temp list. We do this because each word with the same score as an equally good score, everything else will be a worse guess. We keep repeating this, hoping that we do select the right guess, which is not guaranteed, but has a good chance. If we guess and the score is 6, we return right away as we found a solution.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(10 * n^2) Space: O(n)", "order": 175 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 729, "name": "My Calendar I", "risk": "Med", "back": "We need to keep track of all valid bookings and reject any that have overlaps. We can naively keep a vector of intervals. When we get a new booking we check if each stored interval overlaps the new one. There are two possible overlap cases when comparing intervals l and r. l starts between start/end of r, or r starts between start/end of l. So we check if either l.start >= r.start && l.start < r.end or r.start >= l.start && r.start < l.end. If so, either if the interval starts sits in the other interval or overlaps is.\nComparing each interval and then inserting is at worst a n operation if you compare all intervals, and then inserting in the middle of a vector is O(n). This is approach 1), O(n^2) over all bookings.\n\nWe can be a bit faster for approach 2) if we binary search the array. We can use upper bound to identify the first interval that starts after the new one. We can then have two cases, either the interval before the upper_bound extends into the new one, or the new one extends into the upper bound. We need to check both, and if not, we can insert the new one before the upper bound. We need to be careful with edge cases, where the upper_bound can be end, in which case we have no smaller interval, or begin, in which case we have no larger interval. We dont check it or its pre in that case. Else we insert at the found it and return true. Here the search is O(log(n)), but insertion is still O(n), so over all intervals we are still O(n^2).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^2) Space: O(n)\n\n— alt —\n\nInstead of an array we can use a balanced tree, so a std::set. Define a less-compare on start for interval, now the set does the sorting. The code is identical to 2) of the previous approach, still need to guard for no upper_bound or pre. But insertion is now amortized O(log(n)), so search + insert is 2*log(n).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*log(n)) Space: O(n)", "order": 176 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 2178, "name": "Maximum Split of Positive Even Integers", "risk": "Med", "back": "If we draw out some first n max splits, we notice how the beginning up of the split is the same for some consecutive numbers, until the sum grows large enough to fit another even number in. We can simulate this iteratively. Keep an array split, a counter i starting at 2 and a sum at 0. Loop. Add i to sum, i to split, increase i by 2. If sum + i would be larger than finalSum, break. We now have the maxSum until we would overshoot finalsum. We can now adjust by adding in the remaining the difference we have to finalSum. We can't fit another element, so instead we add to the last element of the existing split (finalSum - sum). Return split.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(sqrt(n)) Space: O(sqrt(n))\n\nNotes: The time is related to the sum of even numbers between 1 and n. Say we take i iterations from 2 -> 2 * i. The sum of numbers in between those bounds is (2i * (2i + 1)) / 2. We only use even, so half as many numbers -> 2i * (2i + 1) ~> i^2 + i. That means that dropping the non-dominant i, n ~= i^2, so i ~= sqrt(n). This and this", "order": 177 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 833, "name": "Find And Replace in String", "risk": "Med", "back": "We need to realize two things, then this is easy. 1) the order of indices is not guarenteed to be sorted. 2) we have to check all ops on the src string, not the string we modify on-the-fly. To deal with 1), we make an index array op_order and sort it based on the contents of indicdes, which we can now traverse in sorted order. For 2), we just built a new string while traversing the old string. We keep an s_idx into string and op_idx into op_order. While s_idx < string.length(). If op_idx isnt past op_order, and indices[op_order] == s_idx, we need to check for substition. We check if sources[op_idx] appears at string[s_idx], and if so, we append targets[s_idx] to new_string, then advance s_idx by |source|. Else we still advance by |source|, but instead append a subtr from src to dst. Then increment op_idx. If we dont have a substitution to check, we append string[s_idx] to new string and increment s_idx. Return new_string.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|sources|) + O(|indices| * log(|indices|) Space: O(|newString|)\n\nNotes: Time is either dominated by having to check all sources strings if each starts on an adjacent letter and fails (though i dont think that is possible since they cant overlap) - since they dont overlap I think we always do at most O(|s|) checks. We also have to sort indices so that could dominate if there are a a lot.\n\nWe can save a few while iterations due to the subs not overlapping. If a sub fails, append a substring of length |source| from s_idx out of s onto new string, then always jump ahead s_idx by |source| if we do a sub check. Complexity remains the same though, still O(|s|) i think.", "order": 178 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 652, "name": "Find Duplicate Subtrees", "risk": "Med", "back": "Use merkle tree hashing. We calculate the hash of each subtree, then store a hashmap from hash to number of times we've seen that hash. When we see it the second time, we add it to duplicate nodes.\nDFS merkle, return \"#' when cur is empty. Else get merkle l and r, combine string l + val + r, hash it, insert into map and add cur to duplicates if we've found it for the second time. The return stringified hash value.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(#nodes) Space: O(#nodes)\n\nNotes: There is time cost for building the strings for nodes. The worst case cost of appending the string together is 3 * the number of digits in a 64 bit hash value (size_t max has ~20 digits), so the strings should never get longer than 60 characters.\n\nWe can save ourselves the cost of stringifying the hash to return it by instead assigning each newly found node an id that we get from an increasing counter. Then we make merkle return the id, and we have easy way to assign a unique id to each node.", "order": 179 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 792, "name": "Number of Matching Subsequences", "risk": "Med", "back": "To solve matching all subsequences, we need to first know how to match one subsequence. We can do this with two indices, the one into t advances each step, the one into s advances when t[i] == s[j]. If we ever reach the end of s, we found the subsequence. To do this for all s, we could keep an index for each s and at each step in t, check each index for the s and advance if the letter match. This would have complexity |t| * num_s, because at each letter of t we check all s. \nWe can notice that at each letter of t, only the s whose index points at the same letter as the letter we are considering in t are relevant. To take advantage of this, we keep a map of letters to a list indices that currently point at that letter in an s. We init such a struct for each word, storing the idx into words and the first pos 0, added to the map entry for the first letter of s. Now we do a pass through t. We get the list for the current letter in t. For each entry, we advance the pos. If we hit the end of the s, we increase our match count and discard the entry. Else we move it to the map entry for the letter at the nex pos (or keep it in the current list if the next letter is the same). We once we complete the pass through t, we will have found all s we advance through, and can just return num matches. With this approach, we at worst consider each letter in t once, and each letter in each s once.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|t| + |all s|) Space: O(|words|)", "order": 180 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 2158, "name": "Amount of New Area Painted Each Day", "risk": "Med", "back": "One approach is to merge intervals. Keep a sorted set or vector of Ranges. Ranges sorted by start. Iterate through paint. Search upper_bound on area for new_area. If found it has a prev, and prev's start extends into new_area end, take prev(it) instead. Calc the new_paint as new_area.end - new_area.start. Iterate while it != end && it->start <= new_area.end. Calculate the difference between the two intervals by checking which extends into which, then taking min(l.end,r.end) - r.start or l.start (depending on if r or poke in). Subtract from new paint. Merge it with new_area by min/max-ing the start end. Remove it from area. Once done, insert new_area into area, insert new_paint into results. Return results.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*log(n)) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: For wallclock time it pays to use a vector instead of a set.", "order": 181 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1610, "name": "Maximum Number of Visible Points", "risk": "Med", "back": "This is basically a linear algebra problem. We can offset all points to the origin to make it simpler (origin normally is \"location\"), calculate the angle with the + x-axis. Then sort the points, now do a sliding window through the list that shrinks when the angle between the first and last becomes bigger than our cone angle.\nWe iterate through points. If point is equal to origin, discard and increment a always_seen counter. Else, we want to calulate the rotation of the point around the positive x-axis so we check it against our cone. We offset to origin by subtracting location from point. Then we can use atan2 to get the angle. atan2 returns radians so we convert to angle by multiplying with (180 / PI). If the angle is negative, we wrap it around by adding 360, for simplicity. Now we sort the array. If we used just this array, we'd sweep from first to last point. But we could start our cone at one of the last points and have it extend. We could do some kind of array wraparound, or we can duplicate the array, but offsetting each duplicate by adding 360 to represent the extra rotation. Now we can start the sweep with l and r pointers. r goes from 0 to array end. First we check if we need to shrink the window, by checking angle[r] - angle[l] > cone_angle. This is a float compare tho, so for precision we add a small epsilon to the subtracted angles. If the check fires, we advance l, do that in a while loop. Then calculate the window size (r - l + 1) and store if its max. Finally return max window size plus the always_seen counter.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*log(n)) Space: O(n)", "order": 182 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 777, "name": "Swap Adjacent in LR String", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can notice that the L and R swap operations are asymmetrical. Ls can only move backward, while Rs can only move forward. We can use this to scan through both strings, looking for non-X characters and verifying if the case we found is fix-able by swaps. We keep two indices into s and e, l and r. We loop while either is smaller then their len, we dont early out if one reaches the end because we need to fully scan both strings to cover all edge cases.\nInside the loop, we advance l while its < |s| and s[l] != 'X'. We do the same for r. If both reached the end, we can early return true since we had a run of Xs until the end. If only one of either reached the end, we early return false because this case is not fixable (e.g. s='XX', e='XR'). If s[l] != e[r], we return false as the they broke on a differing character which we cant fix. Now we can check if our break is fixable. If s[l] == 'L', we can only fix by moving L backward. For this to be true, the pos s in has to be after the pos in e, otherwise we can swap back. So return false if (i < j). If s[l] == 'R' we have to be able to swap forward, so i has to be behind j. So return false if (i > j). Then advance i and j. If we exit the loop, return true.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 183 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1284, "name": "Minimum Number of Flips to Convert Binary Matrix to Zero Matrix", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can solves this with a BFS, which incidentally will find the solution with the fewest steps since we explore in order of number of steps. There are m*n possible states each step, and each state can be included in the solution or not, so there are 2^(m*n) paths to explore, but the matrix is at worst 3x3 so we can afford to brute force it.\n\nWe make ourselves a set of matrices (set works since it relies on equality and vector has operator==()) to avoid revisting seen states. Then we keep a queue of frames (mat, ones, steps). We count the number of ones in the src matrix, and early return 0 if there are 0. Counting the ones lets us count them later after modifying the mat, and we know we have a solution if its 0, so we can avoid checking the whole matrix for every state.\nWe insert src_mat, ones and 0 into queue, then iterate while the queue has entries. We explore level order, so each step look at all the elements that are currently in queue. Pop the front. Then get the next states. We do this by iterating over all cells in the matrix (the dfs version would avoid duplicate work here by not re-flipping already flipped cells), and generating a new matrix by flipping the cell and its neighbors. We also count the new number of ones. If seen already has this new state, discard it. Else add it, the new ones and step + 1 to result, return all new states. In the main loop, now loop over every new state. If its one's are 0, return its steps, this is the shortest path. Else insert the new state into seen, and add the new frame to queue.\nIf we exhaust the queue without finding a solution, return -1, there is no solution.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n * 2^(m*n))\nSpace: O(2^(m*n))\n\nNotes: Similar to \"2128. Remove All Ones With Row and Column Flips\", we can notice that there is no solution if we're forced to flip the same cell twice, since that'll just return the cell to the state it was in before. Because of this, we know we don't need to consider solutions that revisit previously flipped cells. We could therefore implement this with a DFS that tries to flip or not flip a cell at each step, but this has to explore a lot of steps and so is slower than BFS.\n\nIf we treat the matrix as a bit mask (we have at worst 9 values so can fit in a u16), we can save ourselves all the memory allocations for matrices. Then we could also use an unordered set for seen.\n\nThis solution is very fast, but i do not understand why the order in which we explore (e.g. why dont we have to try flipping [0][0] after we skip it at first and then flip one of its neighbors), so I'd rather not rely on it.", "order": 184 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1631, "name": "Path With Minimum Effort", "risk": "Med", "back": "Solve using Dijkstra. We traverse the paths in order of minimum effort, and for each cell track what the least effort path currently found to it is, so we can re-open cheaper new paths.\nMake a path struct with cur coords, last_height and max_effort. Create a min_heap of paths. Create an array to track the min path to each cell, inited to INT_MAX. Insert the first cell with last_height of that cell and max_effort 0 into queue, then mark the path array for the first cell with 0. While the queue isnt empty, iterate. Pop from the queue. If the popped cell is the target, return the path's max_effort. Else iterate the four directions. If new coord is out of bounds, discard. Else calculate the next effort as abs(next_cell height - last_cell height). If next effort is >= the effort in min_effort array for next_cell, discard. Else set entry for next_cell as next effort, then insert the next path into queue using next_cell coordinates, next_height and max(cur_path.max_effort, next_effort).\n\nThe priority_queue always makes us explore the min cost path, so even if we inserted a path at the target cell already into the queue, if a less cost path elsewhere is still open, we wil explore this first, until either that path finds the target, or it becomes larger or equal cost to the previous path.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(m*n*log(m*n))\nSpace: O(m*n)\n\nNotes: Can also be solved using union find. Create a UF with an entry for every cell in array (mapping 1D index from 2D index). Then generate an edge list, with a weight that is the absolute effort between the two cells. Sort the edge list by effort. Then in that order connect components until the start and end cell are connected. The effort of our current element when the connection is achieved is the min effort, since we traverse edges in effort order.", "order": 185 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1376, "name": "Time Needed to Inform All Employees", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can solve this with a top-down dfs, but we need to construct the tree for this. We can do so using a map of arrays, where the key is the manager and the values the emloyees. Then we DFS starting at the manager, counting up the time to inform along the path. At each step, check if the path's time to inform is the max. Return the max found during the DFS\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: We visit each node once during the DFS. Memory grows linearly with more nodes.\n\n— alt —\n\nAlternatively, we can run a bottom up DFS. We save ourselves the time and space of constructing the graph. The tradeoff would be that we explore the same path multiple times (first entry an the array is a leaf, next entry is its manager, next is that ones manager, etc.), but we can avoid this by accumulating the time up along the tree and compressing the paths we already explored.\n\nWe still iterate through each entry i in n. For each we call DFS, which returns us the time for this i. We check if its the max, which we return later. DFS takes current i, manager and time array. If manager[i] is not -1 (we haven't checked / compressed this path yet), we DFS with manager[i], and add the returned time to time[i]. This sums the path up to the root and adds it to the entry of the current i, so it can then later be directly looked up, since we already computed it once. To compress the path and see later that we already computed it, we set manager[i] to -1. We then return time[i].\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 186 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 2162, "name": "Minimum Cost to Set Cooking Time", "risk": "Med", "back": "The upper bound of this problem is constant, so we can try to brute force it. We can at most try a combination of 4 different digits, and for each digit we have ten choices. So thats a depth of 4, with 10 branches -> O(10^4).\nWe implement a recursive check function that takes the current digit we are hovering, the current path's cost, the pressed digits array, and the constants we are passed at the start. First calculate how many seconds the current digits make up, we iterate backward through the array, and treat each digit as its place cost (first is single seconds, second is 10s seconds, etc.). If the current seconds are > target, return INT_MAX for no solution. If it is == target, return cur_cost. Else if we have 4 digits, return INT_MAX, we havent found a solution on this path.\nNow iterate through the ten digits. Calcuate the cost depending on if we need to move, then recurse with the new digits, digits and cost. Check if the returned value is the min value for this path. Return that min value at the end. After recursing, pop the last digit back off our digits.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(10^4) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Spaces is constant because we never have more than 4 branches of stack depth in 4 ints of buffer space.\n\n— alt —\n\nThere is much smaller constant time solution, because we can notice that there;s really only two possibilities to express our target seconds:\nWe can divide the number up into minutes and seconds as is -> min = target / 60, sec = remainder.\nOr we can take a minute from min and add 60 seconds to sec in exchange (because our seconds dont overflow at 60, we can have 99). We dont have more options, because if we take away 2 minutes, we add 120 seconds, which is guarenteed to overflow our valid display options.\nFor both of these cases we also have to check that they are valid to display, which is that they are >= 0 and < 100 (microwave display has a range of [0,99]).\nNow we can compute the cost of both paths, and return the min. So we calculate our first option as described above, then the second option as min - 1, sec + 60. We call get cost for both, which has some annyoing edge cases. We implement this by building a digit array, then scanning through it.\nFirst, if min <= 0, we skip adding minute digits. Else we get the tens place by min / 10 and the ones by min % 10, if tens > 0, we push it (could have single digit mins), then push ones (we already checked we have minutes at all, and we need the 0 if we have a digit after). Now we get the tens and ones sec the same way. We push tens secs if either min > 0 or tens_sec 0 (we need the 0 if we have digits after it, or if the value itself is non-zero). Then push ones sec (we always one). Now iterate digits. if digits[i] != start, add move cost, then always add push cost. Then set start to digits[i], repeat. Return total cost. Main function returns total cost between the two options (always defaults to INT_MAX to filter invalid case).\n\nComplexity: Time: O(1) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: Example of the two cases: 630 seconds can be:\n1) 10 min 30 seconds\n2) 9 min 90 seconds\n\nThe time is also some constant > 1, but it is Infinitesimal smaller than 10^4.", "order": 187 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 552, "name": "Student Attendance Record II", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can solve this with top-down DP. Without any restrictions, there would 3^n possible permutations. But we can discard any paths with >= 2 absent days, and >= 3 consecutive late days. Even with this pruning, we'll still run into duplicate permutations, so we speed it with a cache. Normally this would take a lot of memory, since it'd be 3D, but our later 2 axes are restricted because of the restrictions on late and absent days. So our cache is [n + 1][3 (possible values of late 0, 1, 2)][2 (possible values of absent 0, 1)]. \nSo we implement a DP function that takes n (how many days are left to choose), absent (how many days were we absent so far) and late (how many consecutive late days have we had). If n == 0, return 1, we found one valid permutation. Then we check the cache, and return the value if we found one. Else, we try adding a present day, so recurse with (n - 1, absent, 0). 0 is for late, as we reset our consective late days. If absent < 1, we can try being absent, so recurse (n - 1, absent + 1, 0). If late < 2, we can try being late, (n - 1, absent, late + 1). At each step, add the return value to ways count, then mod ways count with our mod (10^9 + 7). Finally write to the cache, return ways.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(2*3*n) Space: O(n*2*3) cache + O(n) stack space\n\nNotes: There are very neat and mathy bottom up solutions to this, and I did try going about this with combinatorics, but ultimately I have better things to do with my time.", "order": 188 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 418, "name": "Sentence Screen Fitting", "risk": "Med", "back": "We are interested in how many words we can fit on screen, in order, starting at the first word. We could brute force this by calculating the lines one word at a time, but we actually do a lot of wasted work, because there is only a limited number of possible lines: we can only start with each word in sentence, since we cant break words and wont ever start with a space. So to take advantage of this, we can pre-calculate for each word, how many words we can fit on screen if we start with it, then use this table to calculate how words we can fit in total.\nWe make an array wordsFrom to store the precomputation. Iterate through words. Count the words in line, chars in line and spaces in line, starting at 0. Set curWord to start word. Loop while true. If curWord is numWords, set it back to 0 to wrap around. Now calc the total length of our line so far as spaces + chars + curWordLen. If this is > cols, break, we cant fit curWord. Else increase numWords since we can fit curWord. Then if totalLen == cols, break, as we fit the line exactly. Else inc spaces and chars, then in curWord. We can just inc spaces because we dont care about a dangling space if we break on the next word, as we dont need to print the line (if we did we'd need to avoid adding dangling spaces to the line). After the loop, if numWords is 0, return 0 early since we have a word that cant fit on a line. Else store the numWords in an array.\nNow we can compute the result. Set curWord 0. Iterate from 0 to rows. Add wordsFrom[curWord] to totalWords. Set curWord = (curWord + wordsFrom[curWord]) % numWords (what next word do we start on after this line). Finally return totalWords / numWords. We can do this because we still jump through the words in the correct order, so the divide will clamp us down to the correct number of fits.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(num_words * (col / avg_word_len) + O(rows) Space: O(num_words)", "order": 189 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1055, "name": "Shortest Way to Form String", "risk": "Med", "back": "Normally when substring matching, there is one choice: If the current characters in both src and dst match, we advance the match by incrementing both. If they dont match, we increment only src. But here we need to consider all ways to split, so we have an extra option when the chars match: we can reset the src index to 0 and try matching the rest of dst from the start of src again. We can consider each path and look for the overall shortest path. By itself, there are at worst two branches, and we go at worst |dst| deep, so we would have a worst case of O(2^|dst|). To speed this up, we cache duplicate sub problems, we should get us closer to |src| * |dst|.\nSo we recurse with (i 0, j 0, src, dst). If j == |dst|, we found a valid match, return 1. Else if i == |src|, we ran out of src without fully matching dst, so we return a symbolic value to say we found no match, INT_MAX. Now we check the cache and return a value if found. Else if src[i] == dst[j], we have a match. We try recurse (i + 1, j + 1) to keep matching this run of src. We also try (0, j + 1), to continue the substring, but start from beginning of src again. We take the min value of the two. If src[i] != dst[j], we have call with (i + 1, j), since a later char in i might still match, and take this as the min val. Finally we write the min val into cache and return it.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(|src| * |dst|) Space: O(|src| * |dst|)\n\n— alt —\n\nEarlier decisions don't actually depend on later results in this problem, as it is always best to choose as many character from src as possible before splitting. If we need to split, we can re-use the whole src string, so we would not benefit from having made a different decision earlier. So this suggests a greedy algorithm.\nWe have two indicies i, j = 0 and num_subtrs = 0. We iterate while (j < |dst| && num_subtrs <= j). The first is our valid exit condition, the second for when we get stuck and cant do a further match. First while i < |src| and src[i] != dst[j], advance i. Then if i == |src|, we need to reset as we have used up our src string. So i = 0, then increment num_subtrs. Finally if src[i] now == dst[j], advance i and j. At the end, if num_subtrs <= j, return num_subtrs, else -1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*m) Space: O(1)\n\nNotes: The invalid condition works because we cant use more subtstrings than we have letters in target. So in a valid case, num_subtrs will never be > j. If we get stuck on a letter in target, we'll at worst try to wrap around src a couple of times, until num_subtrs goes past j, at which point we can be sure that there was no way to solve the problem.", "order": 190 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1554, "name": "Strings Differ by One Character", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can naively solve this in O(n^2 * m) time by comparing each string with each other in lockstep. \n\nAnother option is to go through each string, and try for each character to replace it with some symbolic character (e.g *), then hash it into a set. This will identical strings for the kinds we are looking for (e.g. abc and axc both generate a*c). We need to save on memory, which we can do by a) modifying the string in-place and b) hashing the string itself and keep a set if hash codes, so we avoid storing the key of each hash. This is weak to hash collisions however.\n\nAnother option is to iterate through the length of the string, iterate each string and again either remove the char at that pos or replace it, then use the hashset.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n^2 * m) Space: O(1) / O(n^2)\n\n— alt —\n\nIf we want to go faster, we need to use a rolling hash algorithm, like Rabin Karp. The idea is the following: if we compute a hash as value * some base ^ a power. We can compute a partial hash with one of the values removed, if we subtract the value times its base to the power that was used. The base can be the range of characters we have, 26. The power can increase by with each letter. This is just one possible hash function. To keep values in range we also mod with some large prime.\nSo first we iterate through each, word through each letter. We have an array hashes inited to with words entries. For each letter, we calculate the hash of the word as alphabet_size (26) * prev_hash (hashes[i]) + letter_value (word[j] - 'a') mod a large prime (e.g. 10^7 + 9). Now we have the complete hash calcualted for each word.\nWe now iterate through the number of letter backward (makes calculating the appropriate base easier), and iterate each word. For each letter we keep a map of hash to word idx. Base is 1 at the start of the loop (the close we get to the start of the loop, the more multipled in bases we have to remove). We calulate the new hash as (prime + hash[j] - base * letter_value % prime) % prime. The inner add and mod of the prime is to avoid the subtraction going negative but has no impact on the arithmetic. Now we have the hash of the word with the value for that letter removed. We can try to insert the hash into our map (along with its word idx). If we already have this key, we have a collision and a possible match. We have to do the bruteforce check though first on those two words, as there could have been a hash collision. If the brute force check passes, we have a match and can return true. Else we continue. After the word loop, we need to increase the base, which is just multiplying in the power, so base = 26 * base % prime. At the end if we found no matches, return false.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*m) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: The brute force checks should have no impact on our average case complexity, since if we use a large prime collisions should be very rare.\n\nO(n*m) because for each letter m, we do words m constant operations, which is either compute the total hash value (first loop), or remove the current letter's hash value (second loop).", "order": 191 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 975, "name": "Odd Even Jump", "risk": "Med", "back": "There are two things we need to solve: 1) We need to for each index know if we can reach the end. To do that efficiently, we need to know 2) know for each i, what is the next smallest larger value and the next largest smaller value.\nWe can break this into two problems if we notice something: We can build a recurrence relation ship. For index i, we can make a valid odd jump to the next largest index, and that index can reach the end. For an even jump, we can make a valid jump if the next smallest can make an odd jump and reach the end. If we compute this back to front, we can know that i is valid if its jumps are valid, and their jumps are valid, etc. unitl the end. We have a base case, which is the last element can always finish even and odd.\nSo now if we can efficiently lookup the larger and smaller elements for each index, we can compute the valid jumps in one pass. One structure that lets us do such lookups is a sorted set. A lower_bound operation can help us find the first element >= our arr[i] (which is exactly the odd condition), and then we can look at the prev of that result to get the last entry that is <= to our arr[i]. Because we only look depend on the already computed results for our checks, we can build the map as we go. This makes sense because if the next biggest or smallest idx is before our current index, we cant use it and so we have no valid jump. \nWe make a sorted map<int, int> where the key is the array value and the value is the array index. We count good_starts, which begins at 1 (end value). We also make to arrays, odd and even which store of i has a valid odd and even jump. We set odd and even .back() to true.\nFor each i, we look up the lower_bound of arr[i]. It the return it != end, we have a value. We set odd[i] = even[it->second] (we're doing the odd jump with the larger value first). If odd[i] is now true, we increment good_starts, this has a valid first (odd) jump. \nNow we use a little trick for the even lookup. If it->first (value) == arr[i], we have e.g 3,4,5 in the map and we are looking up 4. The it will point at 4. The backward lookup will also want to see 4. So if the values match, we advance the iterator, so we will later look back at the value we want to find. If the map has 3,5 and we look for 4, we currently have 5 and the backward lookup will see 3, which is what we want, so we can leave the iterator as is.\nNow after the end clause, we check if it != begin(), as we want to look back for the even check. If valid, we set it to prev(it) and then set even[i] to odd[it->second], so that later odd lookups can use it. Finally we set map[arr[i]] = i, which will either insert the value first time, or if already present overwrite it with a smaller i, which we want to use in preference to a later i because of the problem description. This builds our map for later lookups.\nFinally return good_starts.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n*log(n)) Space: O(n)\n\nNotes: We could also index sort the array ascending and the descending and use monotonic stacks to build the lookups, but this is more code and tedious, using multiple linear passes.", "order": 192 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 2242, "name": "Maximum Score of a Node Sequence", "risk": "Med", "back": "The naive solution is to build the graph and then perform a DFS on each node in the graph. The DFS would base case if we hit a depth of 4 and sum up along the path, finding the max path. This causes us to revisit the same paths many times over however, worst case ending up as (V+E)^2. We cant really cache the paths because whether a visited path returns a valid result depends on how many nodes we visited previously. Our base case also prevents us from exploring all the nodes in the path on certain times we visit. So this would be come really complicated.\n\nInstead we can take a different approach. If there is a solution, one of the edges graph will be part of the chain of 3 edges. And there will be two other edges connecting to either end. So, we can choose each edge, \"fix\" it as the middle edge and then consider each edge neighboring either node of that edge. We can find the max node this way, provided the combination doesnt form a cycle. However, if we consider all neighbors of all nodes with each other, we easily end up in E^2 again, considering each edge with each other. But we dont have to check all edges, we only need to check the ones that maximize the score, so we can sort them by score and visit in that order. To avoid doing E^2 work, we only need to consider enough edges so that we sure find a valid combination. This happens to be three edges per node, because if we only consider 1 or 2 each they could all be edges that form a cycle. With 3 each, we'll find atleast one edge that breaks the cycles, and it will be the max score one.\n\nFor the implementation, we build the graph. Then we partially sort the node's edges descending by score, retaining only the top 3. We can use std::partial_sort, a k-min_heap, or we can avoid building the graph and instead build a priority_queue per node (this would be the fastest, as each que takes node_edges * log(3) to build). Now we iterate through each edge in edge list. We iterate through the edges of node 1 in the edge, and for it we check each edge in edges if node2. We have to check that neighbor1 != neighbor2, that neighbor1 != node2 and neighbor2 != node1, as any of these could cause us to form a cycle. If this passes, we can sum up the 4 node's score and retain it if it is max. At the end if we found any max score, we return it, else we return -1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(E + E * (avg_edge * log(3)) Space: O(V+E)\n\nNotes: Time is debatable because we need to sort. If we have tons of edges this could dominate in the node_edges * log(node_edges). If we partial sort, or use a heap per node, the cost to sort compresses to node_edges * log(3).\n\nThe time to calculate the max edges is O(E * 9). So we compress the cost of checking neighbors against each other to constant.\n\nAs to why three edges is enough and two isnt, imagine we pick a middle edge where the highest scoring edge is the other node in the middle edge. Now imagine both nodes share an edge to the same node as their next best edge. This is only 3 node, forming a triangle with not enough node. As soon as we add a 3rd node, even if both middle nodes have an edge to it, its possible to find an acyclic path through this subgraph. This works natively because the edge list contains no duplicates, if it did we would need to filter them.", "order": 193 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 1101, "name": "The Earliest Moment When Everyone Become Friends", "risk": "Med", "back": "The problem is essentially asking what the time is when the graph of people first became fully connected. We can answer this using UnionFind. So we implement UnionFind as nomal, with path compression (root[n] = root[root[n]] during getRoot) so we can amortize the uf operations to constant. Then we sort our logs by timestamp, since otherwise we'd connect the components out of order. Then we iterate through each log, join the two users, and if they were nearly connected decrement our component count (which starts as n). If component count becomes 1, we fully connected the graph and can return the timestamp of that log. If we finish the loop without fully connecting, return -1.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(timestamp * log(timestamp)) + O(timestamp) Space: O(users)", "order": 194 }, { "cat": "Google", "num": 2135, "name": "Count Words Obtained After Adding a Letter", "risk": "Med", "back": "The modify operation reads confusing at first but it really means we can turn start into target iff we add exactly one letter to start, then optionally reorder the letters in any way. What this really means is that we can turn start into target iff target matches start with any one of its letters removed. This is actually really easy to check for us because the problem constraints say there are no duplicate letters in any word, and words are at most 26 letters long, so every word has a unique identity. There are multiple ways to represent this identity, but an easy one is to construct a bit mask with one better allocated to each letter.\n\nWe iterate through startwords, creating mask of each word and inserting it into a hashset. Now we iterate through targetwords. Make a mask of word. Now iterate through each letter in word. Mask that letter out of mask, then check if the new mask is in our start set. If yes, we can stop checking letters and increment our matches. Because we only check mask with letters removed, we ignore cases where startword == targetword. Return match count.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(max(|start| * word_len, |target| * word_len) Space: O(|start|)\n\nNotes: Because there are no duplicate letters, we dont have to worry about word sizes, because of there were, cases like [\"aa\", \"a\"] would fail our algorithm.", "order": 195 }, { "cat": "Facebook", "num": 680, "name": "Valid Palindrome II", "risk": "Med", "back": "We can solve palindrome matching easily: Start a left idx at 0, a right idx at len - 1. Move the pointers inward until the overlap, if every character matches until they do, we have a palindrome. The modification to allow delete can have two choices, we can delete either character of the non-matching ones, which can have different consequences later in the string. So we try both. We implement palindrome match as a helper. Now in main we do the normal palindrome check until we hit a mismatch. We try isPalindrom both with l + 1 and r -1, and return if either returns true. If the main loop finds no mismatches, we can also return true.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 196 }, { "cat": "Facebook", "num": 408, "name": "Valid Word Abbreviation", "risk": "Med", "back": "One pass with two indices into word and abbr to verify. Loop while both indices are smaller than their lengths. If the chars match, advance both indices and continue. Else try to parse a number from abbr[j]. Scan forward finding numbers, each time multiplying the result by 10 and adding the new digit to it. Return false if we find a leading zero, or the result of parsing the number is 0. Else if we parsed a number, advance j to after the digits, advance i by the parsed number. After the loop return if both indices reached the end of their string (deals with cases where the lenght of either word or abbr doesnt match up)\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(1)", "order": 197 }, { "cat": "Facebook", "num": 1249, "name": "Minimum Remove to Make Valid Parentheses", "risk": "Med", "back": "We know how to identify invalid parenthesis using a single pass: We record all the opening parens we find into a stack. When we encounter a closing paren, we remove the top paren from the stack if its an opening paren. If the stack is empty, or the top paren is closing, we found an invalid closing paren and we also add it to the stack. At the end the stack contains all opening parens that had no matching closing, and all closing for which there were no previous opening parens.\nInto the stack we actually record the indices of the parens in the source string. Now we can do a second pass through the source string, appending characters if their index does not match an index in the stack. Skipping all indices that are in the stack yields as a valid, balanced result string.\n\nComplexity: Time: O(n) Space: O(n)", "order": 198 }];
